<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Quake-Calif-Armenians     12-08 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quake-Calif-Armenians,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quake Jolts State's Armenian Communities Into Action</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The earthquake that devastated Soviet
Armenia and caused an estimated 50,000 deaths jolted California's
Armenians into action Thursday, donating thousands of dollars to an
impromptu emergency relief fund.
   ``We need to raise millions,'' said Annig Zindarsian, an
executive of the Armenian Relief Society, which is coordinating the
relief effort with the International Red Cross. ``You can imagine
the devastation there, what it will take ... just to help the people
there.''
   An early morning donor contributed $5,000 to the fund, which was
quickly matched by another donor who learned of the contribution
while standing in the ARS office, said Zindarsian.
   A Fresno surgeon has offered to fly to Soviet Armenia and donate
his skills, and another private benefactor has donated use of four
airplanes to transport supplies from the U.S. to Armenia, she said.
Other needs include blankets, tents, warm winter clothing, food and
medicine, said Zindarsian.
   California is home to about 300,000 people of Armenian descent.
Many live in Southern California, the nation's largest Armenian
community. Another 20,000 live in the San Francisco Bay area.
   In Sacramento, Gov. George Deukmejian, of Armenian descent,
referred to recent political unrest in the region.
   ``The additional turmoil associated with a devastating earthquake
has certainly disrupted the lives of thousands, if not millions of
people,'' he said. ``We are all very concerned about the victims of
this natural disaster and our thoughts and prayers are with them
during this very difficult time.''
   In Southern California, the Western Prelacy of the Armenian
Apostolic Church announced that eight days of mourning would begin
Friday, and that local Armenian churches would hold special requiem
services on Friday and Sunday.
   Archbishop Datev Sarkissian said local Armenians are dazed by the
reports, listing up to 50,000 dead.
   Residents of Fresno, which has one of the state's largest
Armenian populations, are being asked for donations to a special
Earthquake Relief Fund established by the local Armenian National
Committee chapter.
</TEXT>
