<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     12-08 0670</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's suspected that defendants may fib during
trial, that lawyers also may shade the truth, but it's the witness
who arrives late that has the most colorful story, said the state
Supreme Court's top jurist.
   Chief Justice Robert N.C. Nix Jr. described some of his favorites
in an article published Wednesday in the Philadelphia Daily News.
   A Delaware man who showed up two hours late for trial told Nix,
``I asked two people how to get to the courthouse, and they both
said they didn't think one had been built yet.''
   Another late witness admitted he ``was hooked on the lottery, and
I got stuck in a long line waiting for my ticket this morning.''
   And, just as a bench warrant had been issued for a missing
witness, the glassy-eyed man staggered into the courtroom.
   ``Don't get so uptight,'' the man said. ``After a few belts in
the morning, I'd testify against anybody.''
   One woman tried a hard-luck story. She said she pulled her car
into an empty space but the meter was broken.
   ``So I decided to write a note and put it next to the slot,'' she
said. ``But, when I didn't have a pen or paper I had to go to the
store.''
   ``When I got back, there was a ticket,'' she said. ``That's why
I'm late.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MERCER, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It won't make the show-and-tell circuit but
5-year-old Jared Reeher will have some stories to tell his
classmates after helping his mother give birth to his brother.
   ``He asked several times if I was OK, and I said I was, but it
was time,'' said his mother, 26-year-old Michelle Reeher. ``He
helped me into the bedroom and got pillows for me and towels to wrap
the baby.''
   After she went into labor early Sunday, her husband, Kevin, 27,
woke up and ran next door to to the home of William and Cindy
Swingle to call for an ambulance because his house doesn't have a
telephone.
   He returned home, but went back to call again when his wife's
contractions suddenly became more intense.
   When Mrs. Swingle arrived at the Reeher home, she saw the baby
lying on Mrs. Reeher's abdomen.
   ``All Jared said was `Mommy, it's out,''' Mrs. Swingle said.
   Reeher arrived a few minutes later, followed by his parents and a
paramedic who had just arrived. The paramedic cut the umbilical cord
and prepared the mother and baby for an ambulance ride to the
hospital.
   Jared, a kindergarten student at Mercer Elementary School, ``had
some big stories to tell his classmates,'' Mrs. Reeher said.
   Mrs. Reeher and the 7-pound, 14-ounce baby were released Tuesday
from Greenville Regional Hospital. She and her husband have not yet
named the boy.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parents who want to make an investment
in their children's future can buy a few dozen credit hours at
Indiana University _ if they're quick.
   The university is selling _ at today's tuition rates _ 450,000
credit hours that can be redeemed between 1990 and 2010. Similar
programs are being tried in other states.
   The Guaranteed Tuition Certificates, worth about $30 million, go
on sale Monday at 400 bank offices across the state, and one banker
predicts the credit hours will be sold out within three months.
   ``We think it's going to be very popular,'' said Ward Roth,
executive vice president of Bank One in Indianapolis. The bank
received 225 calls about the plan Monday, the day before university
officials formally announced the offer.
   Indiana University President Thomas Ehrlich said the certificates
will not guarantee admission.
   ``What it does guarantee is the ability to finance the tuition
cost, assuming one is admitted five, 10, 15 or 20 years from now,''
Ehrlich said.
   Tuition on the Bloomington campus now costs about $2,000 a year.
   For the student who decides not to attend one of the eight
campuses that the credit certificates will be good at, the bank will
help sell the unused certificates.
</TEXT>
