<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--SanJuanMayor     12-08 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--San Juan Mayor,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Non-Statists Take Control of City Hall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Election officials have certified
the mayoral victory of Hector Luis Acevedo, whose 29-vote triumph
ends the pro-statehood New Progressive Party's 20-year lock on City
Hall.
   The final figures announced Wednesday gave 100,525 votes to
Acevedo of the Popular Democratic Party and 100,496 for Jose
Granados of the New Progressives.
   The State Elections Commission had been recounting votes for this
city of 1 million since the Nov. 8 general election.
   In that voting, Puerto Rico Gov. Rafael Hernandez Colon of the
Popular Democrats was re-elected for a third term. Outgoing San Juan
Mayor Baltasar Corrada del Rio lost to Colon.
   City Hall has been controlled since 1968 by the New Progressive
Party, which advocates statehood for the U.S. commonwealth. The
Popular Democrats say they seek more autonomy in issues like trade
and immigration, but do not challenge the fundamental relationship
with the United States.
</TEXT>
