<2ND_LINE>BC-Summit-Shultz-Text - 3rd Add,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: chemical weapons.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   And he made his comments about continuity, and at the same time
his own need, of course, to study the situation for himself and
develop his own positions. So, he was in and out of the conversation
in a very comfortable and strong way.
   Q: It's not clear to me how much real discussion there was on
Gorbachev's conventional cut proposal.
   SHULTZ: There was very little discussion of it at the luncheon.
And you have to remember, he made this speech this morning. The
president and the vice president, neither one of them heard it, and
I heard it, but it was an extensive thing and we tried to write it
down as best we can, but that's no basis for having any intensive
discussion beyond asking him, well, what does he have in mind? He
has in mind trying to restructure things so that they're more
clearly defensive in nature. So we are interested in that comment
and we'll study this carefully.
   Q: You didn't draw him out and he didn't really elaborate that
much on his proposal?
   SHULTZ: Well, I've reported on the range of things that we talked
about. The meeting was a luncheon broad discussion. It was a very _
I thought it was a very _ it was a very interesting luncheon to take
part in. It was _ hit interesting topics, and there was a good flow
across things that had important substance connected with them, and
at the same time rather informal. And Mr. Gorbachev talked about the
situation in Azerbaijan and what that meant, and so on. It was that
kind of a discussion. It wasn't in any remote sense a negotiating
session or anything of that kind, but in many ways better than a
negotiating session.
   Q: Mr. Secretary, in his speech, Soviet leader Gorbachev talked
several times about new thinking. He talked about the need for
cooperation, coexistence of several systems. Do you believe that
this new thinking is for real, to stay? An element of propaganda?
   SHULTZ: I'll just give you my own opinion. I don't think there is
a shadow of a doubt that an effort is under way to change the nature
of the Soviet system. That is what Mr. Gorbachev says. That is what
all of the evidence that we can see suggests. So I _ (chuckling) _ I
don't have any doubt that that's so. Now, how successful can he be
in making these changes, and how fast will it happen? Of course
nobody can answer those questions. But that there is a major effort
going on to change things, I really don't see how that's even an
open question.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
