<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PearlHarbor     12-08 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pearl Harbor,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Visitors Get Personal Touch At Pearl Harbor Memorial Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Visitors to the USS Arizona Memorial received a
very personal reminder of the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor: a
single flower and the name of one person killed on that fateful
morning 47 years ago.
   ``We wanted to personalize it for them, so they could think of
the loss in terms of one human life, rather than just the huge total
number,'' National Park Service spokesman Mike Stuckey said
Wednesday, the anniversary of the attack.
   More than 2,400 people were killed and 1,200 wounded on Dec. 7,
1941, the day President Franklin D. Roosevelt said would ``live in
infamy.'' The USS Arizona suffered the heaviest losses, with 1,177
fatalities.
   ``History was to prove these men did not die in vain. ... We have
become a symbol of freedom, of democracy and of world leadership,''
Adm. David E. Jeremiah, commander in chief of the Pacific Fleet,
said at a private Navy service aboard the Arizona memorial.
   About 150 people, including survivors, military officials and
Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, attended the ceremony aboard the
memorial, which spans the sunken hull of the ship.
   A minute of silence was observed at 7:55 a.m., the moment the
first bombs fell. The silence was broken as National Guard jets
roared overhead in ``missing man'' formation. The ceremony ended
with prayers, a 21-gun salute and Marine Corps buglers playing taps.
   The Park Service said about 3,000 people attended a simultaneous
on-shore ceremony to commemorate the assault that plunged the United
States into World War II. About 5,000 others attended programs and
lectures throughout the day at the memorial and visitor center.
   A survivor who has attended nearly 20 anniversary services said
his sorrow for lost friends deepens each year.
   ``I've been coming to these tributes forever, and they're almost
the same every time, but I get more emotional every year,'' said
Louis Grabinski, 68, of Long Beach, Calif. ``When I hear taps, I
still get choked up, because I know who they're playing for.''
   Grabinski, then a 21-year-old shipfitter, was resting aboard the
USS West Virginia when Japanese submarines and aircraft blitzed the
harbor's Battleship Row.
   ``We were just forward of the Arizona. We took a lot of heavy
hits, but counterflooded the ship so we sank slower and most of us
got out,'' he said. More than 100 of the ship's 1,500 crewmen were
lost.
   The Japanese struck all military installations on Oahu that day,
and smaller memorial services were held around the state.
   In Virginia, 800 members of the Pearl Harbor Survivors
Association gathered in Virginia Beach for a service that featured
military music, prayers and a flyover of Navy planes from nearby
Oceana Naval Air Station.
   In Oklahoma City, Admiral William J. Crowe Jr., chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staffs, led fellow Oklahomans in a special tribute
to the 448 men who died aboard the USS Oklahoma during the attack.
About 300 people, many of them survivors and their families,
gathered under beside a war memorial near the state Capitol to
observe the anniversary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
