<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Summit-SantaClaus 3rdLd-Writethru a0853 12-08 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Santa Claus, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0853,0652</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Bell-Ringing at Gorbachev on Wall Street</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 18th graf, `Soviet fashions...' with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with announcement of Gorbachev's early departure.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HUGH MULLIGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Santa Claus got run out of Wall Street and was
not permitted to shake his bell at Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's motorcade.
   ``Three hours before the sirens screamed, the cops told me to
pick up my chimney and move it,'' grumbled John Davis, a sidewalk
Santa collecting for the Volunteers of America three blocks from his
usual location outside the New York York Stock Exchange.
   As Gorbachev's armor-plated Zil limousine rolled past the
cathedral of capitalism, the narrow sidewalks were jammed with
Yuppie types unable to cross police lines to get to their own
stretch limos.
   In Harry's Bar, where traders gather after the closing bell, the
Soviet tourist was jokingly dubbed the most famous Russian to shake
up Wall Street since Ivan Boesky, the junk bond tycoon indicted in
insider-trading scandals.
   From the observation deck of the World Trade Center, the Soviet
leader got to see New York on one of those rare smog-free late fall
evenings, with the setting sun gilding the windows of the
skyscrapers and a view for miles of the Jersey coast beyond the
green-garbed Statue of Liberty.
   But loud groans went up against glasnost in the waiting room of
the Staten Island ferry when service was delayed for security
reasons while Gorbachev, President Reagan and President-elect Bush
lingered over their lunch on Governors Island.
   Some passengers shook their fists at City Hall when the No. 6 bus
ended its runs there, a mile from the tip of Manhattan, because the
motorcade had pre-empted the rest of its route.
   ``The trouble with this country is that we should be spending
that million dollars on the homeless and not for police overtime to
protect this Gorbachev,'' shouted Meyer Gelman, who identified
himself as a Brooklyn lawyer.
   ``And the trouble with Gorbachev's country,'' the bus driver
joined the debate, ``is that you'd be put in jail for saying that.''
   Although severe gridlock developed late in the afternoon, many
commuters heeded warnings against bringing private cars to town. One
local TV station had cautioned its listeners in a singing commercial
to the tune of ``Santa Claus is Coming to Town'':
   ``Don't bring in your car,
   Stay off of the road,
   If you try to park,
   You're gonna get towed,
   Gorbachev is coming to town.''
   The Soviet leader's now-familiar snap-brim fedora made a big hit
with Murray Ingleman, a men's clothing factor in the Garment
District. ``It's right out of `The Untouchables,''' he said.
``Wouldn't it be great if this caught on and men's hats came back in
style?''
   While the Soviet motorcade moved through Times Square, leggy
Russian models in skimpy leather mini-skirts promenaded down a
runway at the Javits Convention Center, in practice session to
launch ``Style Wars.''
   Soviet fashions are part of a huge export exhibit of almost
everything from bicycles and computers to pianos and electric
samovars. Gorbachev was originally supposed to visit the exhibit
Thursday in hopes of helping rescue his country's flagging economy
with good old capitalist sales techniques.
   The visit was later canceled when it was announced the Soviet
leader would return home Thursday because of a devastating
earthquake in three southern Soviet republics.
   Smug New Yorkers who may think Soviet technology consists of
harvesting wheat with horse-drawn combines will be impressed with
the enormous earth-moving equipment and robotic machine tools on
display, along with luxury cut glass, advanced optics, Soyuz rockets
for rent to launch environment-studying satellites, and models of
nuclear-powered cargo sailing ships.
   Pretty girls wearing ``perestroika'' T-shirts are on hand to
explain these marvels in charming schoolgirl English. All this and
vodka, yet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
