<1ST_LINE>r e PM-APArts:Mousetrap     12-08 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Mousetrap,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>``The Mousetrap'' Snares Another Record</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Mousetrap,'' the world's longest-running
play, goes on... and on... and on....
   Agatha Christie's thriller has its 15,000th performance on
Friday. However, producer Sir Peter Saunders has become inured to
such milestones. ``Records are meaningless now, aren't they?'' he
says.
   The play, which marked its 36th birthday on Nov. 25, has
outlasted nine U.S. presidents and eight British prime ministers to
become as much a part of London life as Big Ben.
   It originally cost 5,000 pounds (then about $20,000) to stage
``Mousetrap'' when it opened at the Ambassadors Theater on Nov. 25,
1952. It since has moved next door to the St. Martin's Theater, and
has grossed over 14 million pounds ($25.6 million) with its story of
murderous intrigue on a stormy night at a deserted country manor.
   Since its premiere, 230 actors have appeared in the play, 66
miles of shirts have been ironed and 7.5 million people have seen
it, consuming 269 tons of ice cream and about 48,000 gallons of
beverages during intermissions.
   It started out with Richard Attenborough playing Det. Sgt.
Trotter. The famed actor-filmmaker has gone on to become the Academy
Award-winning director of ``Gandhi,'' ``A Chorus Line'' and ``Cry
Freedom.''
   Saunders, 77, said he remains mystified by the play's success.
   ``How it got to be the longest-running play is a question I can't
answer,'' said Saunders, who has produced many other Christie plays,
all far less durable.
   However, he acknowledged that the play's momentum is related less
to the theater than to being a British mainstay.
   ``If you go to Paris, you have to go see the Louvre once, even if
you hate pictures. The same applies to `The Mousetrap,''' he said.
   The cast is annually changed to keep the play fresh, and its 18th
director, Kim Grant, took over on Nov. 28.
   Saunders advises directors against excessive tampering. ``This
play is like a famous Dundee cake which has the same recipe for 100
years. You may change the way it's cooked, but you don't change the
ingredients.''
   Grant, who directed a 1983 revival of Noel Coward's ``Hay
Fever,'' has two weeks to rehearse his ``Mousetrap'' cast, as
opposed to the usual West End (London's Broadway) minimum of four.
He said the material was ``deceptively difficult.''
   ``To make it all plausible and realistic is a great challenge,''
he said. ``Christie's plays are actually very difficult to act,
partly because the dialogue is dated in a way.''
   The play has been presented in 24 different languages in 44
countries, including a six-month off-Broadway run in the early
1950s. Saunders sold the film rights to Romulus Films in 1956 with
the stipulation that no movie version appear until six months after
the the conclusion of the London run. He has twice offered to buy
back the rights, but to no avail.
   The producer also has vetoed any Broadway runs.
   ``The American press would crucify it,'' he said. ``Besides, I
want people to come over here to see it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881208-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 0142EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a BC-Summit-ShevardnadzeText     12-08 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Summit-Shevardnadze Text,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Text of Shevardnadze's Statement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is an unofficial transcript of the statement
by Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze on Wednesday night
announcing that Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev would cut
short his visit to the United States. The statement was delivered
through a translator during a news conference at the Soviet Mission
to the United Nations.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   I've been instructed by Mikhail Gorbachev to report to you that
the Soviet Transcaucasian republics has suffered an extremely severe
earthquake with very grave consequences.
   Preliminary data indicate that in the Armenian republic,
thousands of people have died and of course I cannot give you a more
accurate figure for obvious reasons, there being also a lot of
disruption. It's a most grave misfortune, it's a terrible tragedy
not only for the Armenian people, but for all the peoples of the
Soviet Union.
   A special government-level commission has been set up, headed by
the chairman of the Council of Ministers of the Soviet Union,
Nikolai Ryzhkov.
   Despite the fact that all necessary measures are being taken to
overcome the extremely grave consequences of this disaster. Mikhail
Gorbachev believes that when a people is suffering he has to be
there and he has to lead the effort, he has himself to lead the
efforts, these very important efforts himself.
   For that reason we have to cut short this visit and tomorrow we
will be returning home.
   Events scheduled for the general secretary are being canceled
with the exception of the opening ceremony of the Soviet trade
exhibition, which will be held at a different level.
   As for the visits to Cuba and Great Britain, they will take place
later at a time appropriate for such visits.
   In conclusion, let me on behalf of our delegation and on behalf
of Mikhail Gorbachev himself who asked me to say this, to convey to
you our very profound gratitude to all New Yorkers who have been in
these 36 hours extremely hospitable, very friendly, extremely warm
to our delegation, I would like also to extend our gratitude to the
authorities of the City of New York and to the United States
administration.
   This is all I have to report to you.
</TEXT>
