<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 0154EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-GorbachevReturns 3rdLd-Writethru a0431 12-08 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev Returns, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0431,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to clarify republics are Soviet; INSERTS 1 graf
after 6th graf, `A 7...,' to UPDATE with Shevardnadze saying quake
affected Turkey; SUBS 13th graf `CBS News...,' with 2 grafs to
UPDATE with comment from White House spokesman. Deletes redundant
12th graf, `The White...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev to Cut Short Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev will cut short his
visit to the United States to return to Moscow because of a
devastating earthquake that killed thousands of people in three
southern Soviet republics, Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze
said Wednesday.
   Shevardnadze called a surprise news conference late Wednesday
night and announced that Gorbachev was to depart prematurely
sometime early Thursday.
   ``Despite the fact that all emergency measures are being taken
... Mr. Gorbachev believes when the people are suffering he has to
be there, he has to lead the efforts,'' Shevardnadze said through an
official interpreter.
   The Soviet foreign minister said the earthquake Wednesday hit
Armenia, Azerbaijan and his native Georgia in the Caucasus region
south of Moscow. Shevardnadze said the epicenter was near the
Armenian town of Leninakan, and the quake registered 8.0, although
it was not clear whether he was referring to the Richter scale of
ground motion or a different Soviet system of calibration.
   The U.S. Geological Survey in Golden, Colo., said the quake
registered 6.9 on the Richter scale.
   A 7 reading on the Richter scale is a ``major'' earthquake,
capable of widespread heavy damage; 8 is a ``great'' quake, capable
of tremendous damage.
   ``I understand that Turkey, too, has been affected, but I don't
have any information,'' Shevardnadze said.
   Shevardnadze said Premier Nikolai Ryzhkov had flown to the
Armenian capital of Yerevan to take charge of emergency relief
operations.
   Gorbachev had been scheduled to travel to Cuba on Friday and on
to London Monday before returning to Moscow.
   The Soviet foreign minister said Gorbachev would depart early
Thursday. As for the visit to Britain and Cuba, they will take place
later, but at an appropriate time, Shevardnadze said.
   ``It's a terrible tragedy not only for the Armenian people but
for all the Soviet people,'' Shevardnadze said. He said the quake
had killed thousands of people, but more accurate figures were not
yet available.
   Initial word of the sudden change in plans from an official in
the president's entourage who refused to be quoted by name came only
hours after the top Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman, Gennady I.
Gerasimov, told reporters Gorbachev would not abbreviate his visit
due to the earthquake.
   Ambassador Yuri Dubinin called White House national security
adviser Lt. Gen. Colin Powell at about 11:30 p.m. to tell him that
Gorbachev was going home early because of the quake, said
presidential spokesman B.J. Cooper.
   Shevardnadze said that President Reagan and President-elect
George Bush had expressed their condolences during the lunch meeting
with Gorbachev at Governors Island in New York Harbor, before the
extent of the catastrophe became clear to the Soviet delegation.
   Reports from the Soviet Union indicated the earthquake caused
severe damage and loss of life in the Caucasus, although it
reportedly did not do major damage in Yerevan.
   Armenia and the neighboring republic of Azerbaijan also have been
troubled recently by racial strife, leading to the virtual
declaration of martial law in that region.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
