<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 0157EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>b i AM-SovietQuake 4thLd-Writethru a0424 12-08 0927</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Quake, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0424,0955</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Earthquake Kills Thousands in Soviet Union; Gorbachev Returning
Home</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with report of cars blocking
roads outside stricken towns, details, Ryzhkov flown to Yerevan to
take charge of emergency operations. Picks up 6th pvs, `Preliminary
data ...' EDITS thereafter to conform and trim.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY31</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The strongest earthquake to hit the Soviet Caucasus
in 80 years devastated the region on Wednesday, and officials said
thousands of people were killed as buildings collapsed in a wide
area.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev cut short his summit trip to New
York and planned to return to Moscow on Thursday because of the
quake, Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze told a news
conference in New York.
   Gorbachev, who had been scheduled to visit Cuba and London before
returning home, called the earthquake ``a grave tragedy.'' The U.S.
Geological Survey said it registered 6.9 on the Richter schale.
   Eduard A. Shevardnadze said the earthquake hit Armenia,
Azerbaijan and his native Georgia far south of Moscow, near the
border with Iran and Turkey. He said the epicenter was near the
Armenian town of Leninakan, a city of 200,000 people that media
reports say was badly damaged.
   The foreign minister said Premier Nikolai Ryzhkov had flown to
the Armenian capital of Yerevan to take charge of relief operations.
   An Armenian Interior Ministry statement early Thursday on Yerevan
Radio said cars, apparently carrying residents from stricken towns,
were causing congestion on roads linking Yerevan with Leninakan and
Kirovakan and hampering relief efforts.
   ``As a result of the earthquake, a grave situation has arisen in
the republic,'' the statement said.
   Armenia was the hardest-hit area in the Caucasus.
   ``Preliminary data indicate that in the Armenian republic,
thousands of people have died, and of course I cannot give you a
more accurate figure for obvious reasons, there being also a lot of
disruption,'' Shevardnadze said.
   ``It's a most grave misfortune, it's a terrible tragedy not only
for the Armenian people, but for all the peoples of the Soviet
Union,'' he added.
   ``Despite the fact that all emergency measures are being taken
... Mr. Gorbachev believes when the people are suffering he has to
be there, he has to lead the efforts,'' Shevardnadze said.
   Armenia and the neighboring republic of Azerbaijan have been
wracked by ethnic strife, leading to the virtual declaration of
martial law in the region.
   A scientist at the seismic station in Yerevan said he visited the
disaster area and estimated the death toll probably would run into
the thousands. He declined to give his name.
   Gennady Gerasimov, the Foreign Ministry spokesman, said in New
York, ``A small village has practically disappeared from the face of
the earth.'' But he did not identify it.
   The quake killed at least four people and caused extensive damage
in eastern Turkey, authorities said.
   The Geological Survey in Golden, Colo., said the quake, centered
south of the Georgian capital of Tblisi, occurred at 11:41 a.m.
(2:41 a.m. EST) and registered 6.9 on the Richter scale. A quake of
that magnitude is capable of causing widespread, heavy damage.
   The temblor, followed by a moderate aftershock measuring 5.8 on
the Richter scale, struck a mountain region in the Soviet Union
already wracked by months of ethnic violence between Armenians and
Azerbaijanis.
   State-run television, in an unusually prompt and detailed report
from the scene, showed film of crumbled buildings in Kirovakan,
Armenia's third-largest city, and in Spitak, a regional center of
Armenia.
   Workers were shown picking up huge slabs of concrete amid the
rubble. In one dramatic shot, a man put his hands over his head in
grief as he stood amid a collapsed building.
   ``The spontaneous elements didn't spare one-story or multistory
building,'' a TV correspondent said on the evening broadcast.
   The correspondent said thousands were homeless and that ``there
are casualties, injured,'' but neither he nor Soviet news reports
gave figures.
   ``In several regions of Armenia there is significant damage,
deaths and injuries,'' Tass said.
   Officials said communications had been cut off with Leninakan,
near where the quake was centered, and with much of the disaster
area. Leninakan is 100 miles northwest of Yerevan and close to the
Soviet-Turkish border.
   They said the loss of communications complicated efforts to
assess the damage and casualties.
   The government set up a commission to oversee rescue and salvage
operations and sent soldiers and civilian volunteers to the disaster
area, Tass said.
   State Turkish radio quoted the Kars provincial governor, Hasan
Fakir, as saying four residents of the town of Akyaka were killed in
the quake. Many houses were damaged in Akyaka and in the nearby
Cildir township, it said.
   Tass said the quake reached 9 on the 12-point Soviet scale, which
measures tremors on the basis of their visible effects. An
earthquake of 8 on the Soviet scale is described in Soviet reference
works as ``destructive,'' causing ``cracks on sharp slopes and in
wet soils. Monuments are moved or turned over. Houses are
considerably damaged.''
   The Moscow Central Seismic Center put the epicenter 30 miles from
Leninakan.
   Because of violence between Armenians and Azerbaijanis, more than
180,000 refugees reportedly have fled across the border between
their two republics in the past three weeks. The earthquake was
likely to cause further dislocation.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude. Thus a reading of 7.5 reflects an earthquake 10 times
stronger than one of 6.5.
</TEXT>
