<2ND_LINE>PM-Cox-Erhard,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Part of `est' Lawsuit Against Congressman Dismissed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: est is cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Christopher Cox won dismissal of a
libel claim in a $5 million lawsuit by Werner Erhard and Associates,
but slander allegations against the newly elected congressmen were
allowed to stand.
   Although the slander charges remain undecided as a result of the
judge's decision, attorneys for both sides claimed victory.
   The lawsuit filed in May stemmed from a campaign pamphlet that
criticized Cox' opponent Nathan Rosenberg for his ties to est, the
human-potential movement founded by his brother, Erhard.
   The pamphlet was sent to about 110,000 households before the June
7 Republican primary in which Cox defeated Rosenberg. It asked
voters to read a Los Angeles magazine article that said the
Chicago-based Cult Awareness Network has called est and other Erhard
programs ``destructive cults.''
   In a ruling released Tuesday, Orange County Court Commissioner
Eleanor Palk, who is overseeing the case, granted a request by Cox'
attorneys to dismiss the libel charge.
   Palk said the pamphlet was a constitutionally protected political
statement.
   However, she denied a request to dismiss charges that Cox
supporters posing as pollsters phoned voters and asked residents if
they could vote for a candidate tied to est.
   Erhard attorney William O'Hare said the ruling vindicated his
client. Cox attorney Sue Himmelrich also claimed victory.
   Cox, a former White House attorney for President Reagan, was
elected last month to represent the Orange County district.
</TEXT>
