<DOCNO> AP881208-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 0339EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     12-08 0853</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Not All Delinquent Loan Notices Were on Target, USDA Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the 83,480 loan delinquencies targeted
last month for official collection already had been settled by the
time notices were sent out, the Farmers Home Administration says.
   Moreover, many state FmHA offices have been reporting far fewer
delinquencies than the Agriculture Department agency listed on Nov.
25 when it finished sending out the notices.
   Agency spokesman Joe O'Neill said the 83,480 loan delinquencies
reported last month represented ``everybody who owed money'' and
were behind in their payments to FmHA.
   In all, more than $8 billion in overdue loans is involved. The
notices give a delinquent borrower 45 days to fill out forms showing
how the debt will be settled.
   O'Neill said in an interview that lists of 83,490 delinquent
loans were sent to county FmHA offices so local officials could weed
out those who had already made arrangements to settle their debt, or
for some other reason were not slated to get the notices.
   As a result, several thousand borrowers were pared from the
tally, he said. Those remaining were sent notices by certified mail
over a 10-day period beginning Nov. 15.
   ``No, indeed, we did not sent out that many,'' O'Neill said.
``It's probably closer to 80,000, somewhere in there.''
   Congress ordered FmHA in the Agricultural Credit Act of 1987 to
revise its lending practices and to come up with ways of handling
long-overdue debt owed by thousands of farmers. One of the important
features is a debt write-down or foregiveness provision, which took
effect last month.
   The purpose of the notices is to give tardy payers an opportunity
to let FmHA know how they want to handle their debt under the new
law. If a farmer does not respond within the 45-day period after
receiving the notice, the agency can begin collection proceedings,
including foreclosure and forced liquidation.
   O'Neill said another point of misunderstanding is the manner in
which local FmHA offices have been carrying some of the borrowers on
agency books. For example, he said, some offices may not be
including those whose overdue accounts have been ``accelerated,'' or
put into the foreclosure or forced-sale pipeline.
   The 1987 law also changed the definition of a borrower to include
anyone who owes FmHA money. So all those past-due loans in
acceleration _ and even those where the borrower is no longer
farming _ are included in the list of delinquencies.
   ``Anytime you start playing with numbers, it's difficult at
best,'' O'Neill said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 600 farms that have been in the same
families for 200 years have been located, and more are expected to
be found, the Agriculture Department says.
   The department's effort to identify National Bicentennial Farms
was undertaken last year as part of the 200th anniversary of the
signing of the U.S. Constitution.
   Assistant Secretary Wilmer D. Mizell said the farms located so
far are in 16 states, mostly along the East Coast. The program was
led by state Food and Agriculture Councils, which are made up of
USDA officials at the state level.
   Each of the farms located has been given a certificate signed by
Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng ``to acknowledge the vital
contribution of farm families to the growth and strength of this
great nation.''
   Also, the families have been given metal signs to display in
front of their homes, identifying them in red, white and blue as
bicentennial farms.
   Mizell said Wednesday that a total of about 700 farms is expected
to be located. Families wishing to submit applications may contact
state and local USDA and extension offices for more information.
   The oldest farm discovered dates back to 1632 when apprentice
barrelmaker John Tuttle survived a shipwreck off the coast of Maine
and found his way to Dover, Conn., to claim 15 acres granted him by
Charles I, then king of England.
   His decendant, Hugh Tuttle, and Hugh's three children still own
the farm, an enterprise that includes a roadside store.
   As of Nov. 1, bicentennial farms identified by state included:
Connecticut, 36; Delaware, 16; Georgia, 24; Louisiana, two;
Maryland, 33; Maine, 30; Massachusetts, 39; New Hampshire, 47; New
Jersey, 17; New York, 17; North Carolina, 31; Pennsylvania, 95;
Rhode Island, 10; South Carolina, 88; Virginia, about 50; and West
Virginia, 38.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About $106 million is going out to states as
their final share of national forest sales receipts this year, the
Agriculture Department said.
   Deputy Secretary Peter C. Myers said Wednesday the money is in
addition to a preliminary payment of $212 million which went to
states on Sept. 27, bringing the total for the fiscal year that
ended Sept. 30 to more than $318 million.
   By law, 25 percent of the revenues collected by the Agriculture
Department agency for the sale of timber and other use of national
forest resources must be returned to the states where the forests
are located. Actual receipts in fiscal 1988 totaled approximately
$1.26 billion.
   The states are required to use the funds for schools and roads.
</TEXT>
