<1ST_LINE>r w PM-OilReserve     12-08 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Reserve,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Told Of Security Lapses At Strategic Oil Reserve</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is doing a poor job protecting
the Strategic Petroleum Reserve, the nation's main defense against a
sudden cutoff of foreign oil supplies, from possible sabotage or
terrorist attack, a House panel was told.
   ``Improvements are needed in the security program,'' Keith Fultz
of the congressional General Accounting Office told the House
Government Operations subcommittee on environment, energy and
natural resources on Wednesday.
   ``There are vulnerabilities that exist,'' said Joe La Grone, an
Energy Department official responsible for the strategic oil reserve.
   The reserve, created by Congress in 1975 in response to the 1973
Arab oil embargo, currently holds 550 million barrels of oil in
caverns in Texas and Louisiana.
   The House panel also heard details of a mock attack on the oil
reserve in March 1987 by 11 Army Special Forces troops to test
security at the facility, which includes 240 miles of pipelines and
extensive support facilities such as power substations.
   In the mock attack, the invaders successfully knocked out the
support facilities that are vital to pumping and transporting the
stockpiled petroleum in an emergency. They also recorded 53 mock
casualties among the reserve's defenders, including 12 national
guardsmen mistakenly killed by local sheriff's deputies.
   La Grone said officials have taken steps to improve security at
the $18 billion reserve, including more defense forces and a better
communications network so defenders can avoid shooting each other.
   Fultz said that although the department has made some
improvements in security, ``we're not convinced the SPR could meet
drawdown requirements if certain circumstances occur.'' He did not
elaborate.
   Fultz and La Grone said the sheer size of the petroleum reserve _
including six depots and four marine terminals _ makes it
impractical to try to protect every foot of it against sabateurs.
   The Energy Department's defense plan envisions an attack at only
one point, compared with the four facilities hit simultaneously by
the mock invaders. Officials said, however, that there have been no
new multi-point attack tests since last year's.
   Officials said their approach is to concentrate on key sites and
to quickly repair any damage and get the emergency oil supplies
flowing after an attack. But they conceded their repair plans have
never been tested.
   Fultz said the Energy Department has only one contractor to
repair the 240 miles of pipeline _ a situation leaving the
contractor's equipment and spare parts vulnerable to sabotage. La
Grone said a second contractor will soon be hired.
   A detailed General Accounting Office study of the reserve's
security contained a series of recommendations for improvement, but
the study has been classified ``secret'' by the Energy Department.
   La Grone said ``those areas that need fixing, that need upgrading
_ they will get that.''
   After a closed-door session following the public hearing,
subcommittee chairman Mike Synar, D-Okla., said department officials
had agreed to implement some of the specific recommendations made by
GAO and to rethink their assumption that an attack would involve
only one site.
   ``I'm pleased that the department has finally acknowledged the
seriousness of the security problems,'' Synar said. ``All of the oil
in the world won't do you any good if you can't get it out of the
ground and to where you need it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
