<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 0345EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BushEnvironment     12-08 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush Environment,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Aide Outlines Priorities For Global Environmental Meet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An aide to President-elect George Bush says the
new administration would use an international environmental
conference to push for global cuts in carbon dioxide emissions and a
ban on ozone-destroying chlorofluorocarbon chemicals.
   The aide, Bob Grady, told a luncheon Wednesday at the Climate
Institute that the Bush administration also would advocate growing
more forests and clearing fewer of them.
   The Climate Institue is a non-profit group trying to call
attention to environmental threats from climate changes.
   Bush pledged during the presidential campaign to convene an
international conference on the ``greenhouse effect'' causing global
warming and said he would bring a ``conservation ethic'' to the
White House.
   He was not specific, though, on what results should come from a
conference on the greenhouse effect. He said only that it should
``develop a strategy for tackling this global problem.''
   ``His experience is that international cooperation is indeed
possible in these matters,'' said Grady.
   ``I sincerely believe George Bush will use his foreign policy
experience, informed by the conservation ethic, to work toward
global consensus.
   ``The agenda is clear ... We must work together to reduce the
emissions of carbon dioxide and greenhouse gases.
   ``We must plan to phase out CFCs (chlorofluorocarbons) that
destroy stratospheric ozone. We must stem the alarming net loss of
forests around the world.''
   Carbon dioxide from burning fossil fuels is the principal gas
whose buildup in the atmosphere trapping the earth's heat is blamed
by many scientists for the warming trend.
   CFCs, which contribute importantly to the warming, already are
the subject of an international agreement to reduce production by 50
percent by 1998 because they destroy the high-altitude layer of
ozone that protects the Earth's surface from the ultraviolet rays of
the sun.
   These chemicals are used abroad for aerosol propellants and
everywhere for solvents, refrigeration fluids and plastic foam
production.
   Forest clearing, in addition to other harm such as removal of
wildlife habitat, releases carbon tied up in plant tissue which
becomes carbon dioxide when burned. A growing forest, however,
removes carbon dioxide from the atmosphere.
   Brazilian forest burning to create farmland has been estimated to
account for 10 percent of the 5.6 billion tons of carbon dioxide
that reaches the atmosphere every year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
