<HEAD>Dollar Up Moderately Against Yen, Share Prices Plunge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose moderately Thursday against the
Japanese yen, while share prices plunged on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which surpassed
the 30,000-point mark Wednesday for the first time by gaining 381.44
points, plunged 291.92 points or 0.97 percent to finish trading at
29,758.90.
   The dollar closed at 123.02 yen, up 0.59 yen from Wednesday's
close of 122.43 yen. Opening at 123.40 yen, the currency moved in a
range of 122.85-123.48 yen.
   Currency traders said the dollar's rise followed sharp gains
overnight in overseas markets following Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev's announcement at the United Nations that his country
would cut its troop strength by 500,000 and reduce the number of its
conventional arms.
   ``The market took the Soviet move as a helping hand for the
United States toward cutting its huge fiscal deficits'' by easing
U.S. defense obligations, said a currency dealer with the Bank of
Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Meanwhile, on the stock exchange, investors sold shares in a
round of profit-taking following Wednesday's landmark rise.
   ``Market players seemed to be reacting to Wednesday's sharp
upsurge,'' said an analyst at Daiwa Securities.
