<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 0354EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-GovernmentPhones     12-08 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Government Phones,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AT&T, Sprint Win Multibillion-Dollar Federal Phone Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AT&T and Sprint are the winners in a fierce
contest to provide telephone and high-tech communications services
to the federal government, a prize worth up to $25 billion by the
year 2000.
   The losers were Martin Marietta Corp. and its bidding partner,
MCI.
   MCI said it may challenge the decision, which was made Wednesday
by the General Services Administration. Martin Marietta asked for a
detailed briefing on the decision, which awarded contracts for a new
federal telecommunications system called FTS-2000, providing service
to government agencies through the 1990s.
   GSA awarded the multibillion-dollar contracts three years after
outlining its needs for a new government-wide phone service system
that will include video, computer and other state-of-the-art
communications.
   ``We are elated,'' U.S. Sprint Communications Co. President
William Esrey said.
   American Telephone & Telegraph Co. officials expressed equal
delight at the decision, which provided contracts that are among the
largest ever awarded by the U.S. government aside from military and
space program purchases.
   GSA estimated the combined value of the contracts at between $3
billion and $10 billion over 10 years _ but it could reach a maximum
$25 billion. The contracts limit government spending to $15 billion
on the AT&T network and $10 billion on Sprint's.
   The estimates are based on the government's purchase of
long-distance telephone services over a 10-year period. Actual value
will depend on how much service the government actually uses.
   Acting GSA Administrator Richard G. Austin said AT&T received a
contract to provide approximately 60 percent of the service, and
Sprint was awarded the remainder.
   MCI spokeswoman Kathleen Keegan said the company would challenge
the decision in court and before the Federal Communications
Commission if it determines that AT&T used ``predatory'' pricing _
that is, below its direct costs.
   ``MCI priced the long-distance portion of the FTS-2000 bid as
aggressively as possible,'' she said. ``If the long-distance portion
of the winning bids were priced below MCI's, then we do not believe
it is possible for the winners to provide that service on a
profitable basis.''
   The bidding companies designated subcontractors in their
proposals to the GSA. Those included in the losing Martin Marietta
bid were GE-RCA Americacom and McDonnell Douglas Tymnet.
   Boeing Co. and Computer Sciences Corp. were designated AT&T
subcontractors in the winning bid, as well as regional Bell
telephone companies and other local telephone companies.
   Boeing is to provide program management and information services,
and Computer Sciences Corp. will develop and maintain a software
system for billing. The regional telecommunications holding
companies and local companies will provide local network access,
according to AT&T officials.
   Sprint's subcontractor partners include GTE and the regional
telephone companies.
   ``This is an important competitive win for AT&T and our partners
in this project,'' said Richard J. Lombardi, AT&T vice president for
federal services.
   The system is to be phased in over three years, with the first
users to begin service in 1989 and all federal users to be on line
in 1991. Lombardi said he expected service to be in place by next
fall.
   The contract provides for a new all-digital integrated network
replacing what is already the world's largest private
telecommunications network, with service by AT&T. The current system
is capable of carrying only voice and slow-speed data transmissions,
the GSA said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
