<DOCNO> AP881208-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 0356EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HeritageFoundation     12-08 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Heritage Foundation,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conservative Group Releases Recommendations</HEAD>
<HEAD>For 9:30 a.m. EST release; time set by source</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The conservative Heritage Foundation today
released the full 927 pages of what it hopes will be a blueprint for
the incoming Bush administration.
   The third quadrennial ``Mandate for Leadership'' book contains
more than 2,000 recommendations on running the government in a
manner acceptable to the conservative think-tank. Major portions of
the report had already been made public prior to today's formal
release.
   The Reagan administration adhered to many of the recommendations
in the first such volume, issued in 1980, and the foundation hopes
for similar results once George Bush takes office next month.
   The new book includes recommendations on how to run the
transition, how to deal with Congress, foreign affairs and all the
departments and major agencies.
   It recommends a harder-nosed approach on holding down federal
spending, including subjecting all programs including Social
Security to the Gramm-Rudman deficit ceiling law.
   The book repeats a host of other Heritage positions including
letting workers opt out of Social Security in favor of private
retirement accounts, pressing ahead with President Reagan's Star
Wars missile defense system, and renewing military aid to the Contra
rebels in Nicaragua.
   This ``Mandate'' is actually 166 pages shorter than the 1980
tome, which ran 1,093 pages. ``Mandate for Leadership II,'' in
Reagan's midterm, ran 565 pages.
</TEXT>
