<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bukharin     12-08 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bukharin,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Widow Says Soviet Revolutionariy Leader Was Ignorant Of Stalin's
Plotting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Russian revolutionary leader Nikolai Bukharin
returned to Moscow from Paris never dreaming that he'd be jailed and
executed in a Stalinist purge, his widow said in a television
interview.
   Bukharin's ignorance of dictator Josef Stalin's murderous plans
may explain the mystery of why Bukharin came home despite the purge,
Anna Larina Bukharin said in Wednesday's broadcast.
   Her husband and other victims of Stalin may have had some idea of
what was going on, ``But not to such an extent,'' she said.
   Bukharin and 15 other veteran Bolsheviks were posthumously
rehabilitated July 9 and readmitted to the ruling Communist Party.
In February, the Soviet Supreme Court cleared Bukharin and the
others of treason, spying and other charges for which they were
executed or imprisoned.
   Mrs. Bukharin, interviewed in Moscow, spoke in Russian in a
British Broadcasting Corp. program titled ``Bukharin and the
Terror'' that claimed to shed new light on one of the most notorious
episodes in Soviet history.
   Mrs. Bukharin said Stalin, in planning to get rid of her husband,
sent him to Paris in 1936, ostensibly to collect party documents.
   Bukharin's motives for returning to Moscow have long been a
subject of speculated, since it was widely believed he must have
known that he was under threat.
   ``Nikolai didn't have an inkling, no. I think he still wouldn't
have believed (if he had known). He would have returned just the
same. He wasn't like that _ he would have returned to have his say,
to put his case,'' Mrs. Bukharin said.
   Bukharin was often seen as a likely successor to his close friend
Vladimir Lenin, who led the 1917 revolution and founded the Soviet
Union, and to whom Bukharian acted as economic adviser.
   Lenin called Bukharin ``not only the most valuable theoretician
of the party but the favorite of us all.''
   Stalin, the party organizer, used Bukharin as his theorist and
ally after Lenin died in 1924. But Bukharin opposed excesses in
Stalin's forced collectivization and industrialization and in
February 1937 he was arrested and tortured in prison before being
tried in March 1938 and executed.
   The program said Bukharin's body has never been found and that
his widow was also arrested, banished to Astrakhan on the Caspian
Sea and kept in prisons and camps for 20 years, not seeing their
only son in all that time until he was 21.
   Stalin died in 1953. Mrs. Bukharin said that in 1961, when Nikita
Khrushchev was in power, she was called to a commission
investigating her husband's case and shown a testament he had
written, the same document that her husband had asked her to
memorize.
   In his testament, Bukharin said he felt his ``helplessness in the
face of a hellish machine.''
   He said he was sure history would prove him innocent and that a
``young and honest generation of party leaders'' would vindicate him
and reinstate him in the party.
   ``Know comrades, that on the banner which you will bear on the
triumphant procession toward communism there is also a drop of my
blood,'' Bukharin wrote.
   Mrs. Bukharin, who was her husband's third wife and 25 years his
junior, said she first met him when they and Stalin occupied
apartments in what is now Moscow's Metropole Hotel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
