<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Summit-Invitations     12-08 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Invitations,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagans Swapped Invitations With Gorbachevs For Future Visits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President and Nancy Reagan compared notes at the
White House after a day of superpower summitry and found they'd both
swapped invitations with their Soviet counterparts to make return
visits with each other some day.
   The president and first lady had come to New York for their final
official meetings with Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev and his wife,
Raisa. The foursome had been together at three previous summits
dating back to 1985.
   The Reagans plan to retire to their home state of California
after the inauguration of President-elect George Bush in January.
They will have a residence in Los Angeles, and plan to retain their
688-acre ranch in the Santa Ynez Mountains outside of Santa Barbara.
   Prior to Gorbachev's first visit to the United States last
December for the Washington summit, Reagan often said he wanted
Gorbachev to tour the United States. Gorbachev, however, did no
touring and spent only a few days in Washington.
   At the White House late Wednesday, Mrs. Reagan told the president
she'd invited Mrs. Gorbachev to return to the United States, and
that Mrs. Gorbachev had responded in kind. ``The president came home
and said he'd had the same exchange'' with the Soviet president,
said Elaine Crispen, press secretary to Mrs. Reagan.
   The president and Mrs. Reagan had returned to Washington on
separate planes and discussed the events of the day when they got
back to the executive mansion, Mrs. Crispen said.
   The spokeswoman, who flew back to Washington with Mrs. Reagan and
Barbara Bush, said she spoke with Mrs. Reagan by telephone after
she'd returned to the White House.
   While Reagan met with Gorbachev on Governors Island in New York
Harbor, Mrs. Reagan and Mrs. Gorbachev attended an exclusive
luncheon hosted by Marcela Perez de Cuellar, the wife of the U.N.
Secretary General.
   Mrs. Gorbachev told Mrs. Reagan that ``destiny had brought them
together'' and that she was certain they'd see each other in the
future, Mrs. Crispen said the first lady related. Mrs. Gorbachev
expressed the hope that the Reagans would return to the Soviet Union
and see more than they'd been able to during last year's Moscow
summit, Mrs. Crispen said.
   Mrs. Reagan responded, ``Yes, she'd like to do that, and added
that she'd like to have them come to California,'' Mrs. Crispen said.
   Both Reagans told the Gorbachevs ``they had always hoped they
would see the West as well as the East, because they are totally
different,'' Mrs. Crispen said.
   The couples agreed that ``time constraints'' during their past
meetings had kept them from seeing all the sights that they'd
wanted, and that they hoped ``maybe something could be worked out in
the future,'' Mrs. Crispen said.
   The spokeswoman said the invitations were not specific and that
``they didn't talk about times.''
   Mrs. Crispen said Mrs. Reagan and Mrs. Bush celebrated their
joint return home by having a picture taken, because they have
rarely traveled together on official trips.
   ``They talked all the way home,'' Mrs. Crispen said, primarily
about their plans for the holidays.
</TEXT>
