<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     12-08 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Endowments Rise Despite Market Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Caspa correct in 5th graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   College endowments, buffeted by the October
1987 stock market crash, still posted a small gain in the last
fiscal year, a college business group reports.
   The National Association of College and University Business
Officers said preliminary results from its survey of 100 major
endowment funds indicated an average gain of 0.2 percent for the
year ended last June 1.
   That was down from a 13.8 percent gain for the campus endowments
in fiscal 1987, the group said Wednesday. It beat the minus-7.1
percent return on the Standard & Poor's 500 during the year.
Government and corporate bonds rose 7.5 percent during the same year.
   The business officers have tracked major campus endowments
annually since 1971.
   Caspa L. Harris, executive vice president of the association,
said, ``To the extent that one can point to a single reason for the
sharp decline in endowment returns, the October `crash' is
responsible.''
   Endowment funds ``are invested primarily in publicly traded
securities, and history suggests that the market values of such
securities fluctuate widely based on changes in investor
psychology,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Consumers Boost Debt by $3.5 Billion in October</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer spending was up in October, as
Americans took out $3.56 billion more in consumer debt than they
paid off, the government said.
   The October increase followed a tiny $2 million rise in debt
during September, the smallest change in six years, the Federal
Reserve said Wednesday. Consumer credit fell by $81 million in
October 1982 at the bottom of the last recession.
   The October advance, which translated into credit growth at an
annual rate of 6.5 percent, was still down from the 8.75 percent
annual rate of growth recorded over the first nine months of the
year.
   Still, analysts said they believed consumer spending was
strengthening after a period of sluggishness. They noted that retail
sales shot up 0.9 percent in October, the biggest gain in seven
months.
   ``The latest numbers suggest that consumers are a little more
optimistic about buying,'' said Michael Evans, head of a Washington
consulting firm. ``I think they are not fighting higher prices as
much as they had in the past.''
   Consumer spending accounts for two-thirds of overall economic
activity. Newfound strength in the consumer sector has prompted some
analysts to boost their projections for growth in the current
October-December quarter.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Political Parties Considering Convention Changes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of both major political parties are
looking at ways to update and perhaps shorten the next national
conventions in 1992.
   The Commission on National Political Conventions plans to make
recommendations to both the Democratic and Republican parties before
the parties begin planning their next nominating conventions.
   Frank J. Fahrenkopf Jr., who steps down in January as Republican
national chairman, and Charles T. Manatt, former Democratic national
chairman, are co-chairmen of the commission. Both said at a news
conference Wednesday they want to update conventions in an era when
changing nominating rules and growth of the primary system have
removed much of the suspense.
   Fahrenkopf said in some cases professional wrestling programs on
competing stations drew more viewers than the television networks'
coverage of the two conventions last summer. ``It may have been more
interesting at times,'' he said.
   The GOP leader said the commission would consider whether
conventions could be ``streamlined in some way, to make it crisper,
make it cleaner from the standpoint of presenting a program that
will attract more Americans to watch it.''
   He said the panel, which includes some network television
representatives, would also ``take a hard look at what really the
role should be of the media,'' particularly television, in covering
conventions.
</TEXT>
