<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Ailey     12-08 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ailey,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater Has 30th Birthday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alumni came back and danced with the present
company of the Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater. There was
thrilling dancing and attempted dancing by Bill Cosby, with many
short speeches and one long one at the end by Ailey.
   It was a celebration of the company's 30th birthday, on opening
night of a season that will extend through Jan. 1 at the City Center.
   ``This little light of mine, I'm gonna let it shine,'' was
Wednesday night's theme, applied to Ailey's creating a modern dance
company to preserve classics by many choreographers and the black
heritage and to forge into the new.
   Ailey, wearing the decoration of Kennedy Center Honors, which he
received Saturday, around his neck, gestured toward some of his past
dancers and said their secret was they'd kept dancing. ``They're not
as young as they look.
   ``I'm about to burst into tears. Whether they got mad, I fired
them, they left to start their own companies, go on Broadway or have
babies, we always come together. That's the essence of what we're
about, distilling the spirit with movement.''
   The evening began with the ``I Been 'Buked'' section of
``Revelations,'' by present and past company members, including
James Truitte, whose hair now is gray.
   Then Cosby, in a green stocking cap, red tights and leg warmers,
loudly told the audience, ``All my life I've wanted to dance with
Alvin Ailey and now through comedy I got the chance to express
myself.'' He did some undulations, had his posture corrected by a
girl and had men arrive on each side to strike athletic poses. He
reacted by covering his chest with a scarf.
   There were 18 numbers, in most cases parts of dances. The list is
long of even the exciting ones. Mari Kajiwara, Sarita Allen and
Linda Kent, in the part that always was her best when she was a
company member, danced ``The House of the Rising Sun.'' The
beautiful Carmen de Lavallade had a solo. The alumni men, including
Ulysses Dove, George Faison, John Parks, Dudley Williams and Miguel
Godreau, sporting a bush of hair, were thrilling in ``Mean Ol'
Frisco.''
   There was vigor and striking individual turns in Talley Beatty's
hip and streetwise ``The Stack-Up.'' Faison's ``(Try a Little)
Tenderness'' was danced with unflagging verve. The final sections
were from Ailey's own masterpiece, ``Revelations.'' Myrna White's
dancing had a purity in ``Wading in the Water.'' And ``Rocka My Soul
in the Bosom of Abraham'' was, as always, joyfully faith affirming.
   Frank E. Resnick, president of Phillip Morris Companies, the
Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater's largest corporate sponsor since
1981, said the evening would raise $225,000 for the company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
