<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Summit-Gorbachev Bjt   12-08 0638</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Gorbachev, Bjt,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quake Causes Abrupt End to Gorbachev Visit</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: revised schedule uncertain; will be led</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev decided to fly back to the
Soviet Union today ahead of schedule to direct relief efforts in the
wake of a devastating earthquake. ``When the people are suffering he
has to be there,'' his foreign minister said.
   President Reagan and President-elect George Bush expressed their
condolences for the tragedy during their meeting Wednesday with
Gorbachev on Governors Island in New York Harbor.
   Before the day was over, a stream of steadily worsening reports
from the southern Caucasus region of the Soviet Union had prompted
Gorbachev's decision to cut his visit to the United States short.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze called a sudden
news conference late Wednesday night to announce that Gorbachev was
canceling the remainder of his appointments in New York and dropping
plans to fly on to Cuba and Britain. He said Gorbachev would depart
for Moscow before noon EST.
   ``Despite the fact that all emergency measures are being taken
... Mr. Gorbachev believes when the people are suffering he has to
be there, he has to lead the efforts,'' Shevardnadze said.
   Soviet Ambassador Yuri Dubinin called White House national
security adviser Lt. Gen. Colin Powell at about 11:30 p.m. and
``announced that Gorbachev was going back early because of the
earthquake,'' said presidential spokesman B.J. Cooper.
   The earthquake prompted an abrupt end to a tour that had already
won plaudits for the Soviet leader at the United Nations and praise
from Reagan and Bush following a two-hour meeting.
   The Soviet leader went on the diplomatic offensive in a speech to
the United Nations General Assembly, announcing that within three
years he would reduce the Soviet military machine by 10,000 tanks
and 500,000 troops. He also called for a Jan. 1 cease-fire in
Afghanistan, proposed a 100-year moratorium on Third World debt and
promised to prohibit political and religious persecution in his own
country.
   And he prodded Bush not to let the momentum of recent
arms-control achievements lapse. He said The Soviets are ready to
negotiate a dramatic cut in long-range nuclear weapons ``without
long pauses or backtracking.''
   Reagan and Bush applauded the spirit of his remarks, but were
cautious in responding. Bush said he had made it clear that ``we
needed some time.''
   Reagan returned to Washington and said in a speech to
conservatives that he was still an ``anti-communist,'' although he
said the Soviet troop reduction will be an ``important'' step
forward if it is carried out.
   With his diplomatic business accomplished, Gorbachev began what
was to have been two days of sightseeing in New York. But the fun
ended quickly as damage reports mounted from the Soviet earthquake.
   Shevardnadze said the quake hit Armenia, Azerbaijan and Georgia
in the Caucasus Mountains near the Soviet border with Turkey and
Iran, and that the epicenter was near the Armenian town of Leninakan.
   Armenia and Azerbaijan have been wracked for months by racial
strife, leading to the virtual declaration of martial law in that
region.
   The Geological Survey in Golden, Colo., said the quake occurred
Wednesday morning and registered 6.9 on the Richter scale. A quake
of that magnitude is capable of causing widespread, heavy damage.
   ``It's a terrible tragedy not only for the Armenian people but
for all the Soviet people,'' Shevardnadze said. He said precise
figures were not yet available but estimated that the quake had
killed thousands of people.
   He said some remote areas in the mountainous region had been cut
off from the outside world.
   Soviet Premier Nikolai Ryzhkov has been appointed head of a
special government commission to cope with the emergency and was in
the region, Shevardnadze said.
   Shevardnadze said Gorbachev's Havana and London visits would be
rescheduled.
</TEXT>
