<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 0508EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Summit-GorbachevReturn     12-08 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Gorbachev Return,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Man of Action in the Kremlin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev's cancellation of a
three-nation tour to return to his earthquake-stricken nation
demonstrates the Soviet leader's ability to respond quickly to
events in a country he often complains is bound by its own
bureaucracy.
   Barely four hours before the president's decision was announced
at a surprise late-night news conference, chief Foreign Ministry
spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov had dismissed any suggestion
Gorbachev might cut short his stay in New York.
   Although the spokesman acknowledged the situation was serious and
``a small village has practically disappeared from the face of the
earth,'' he told reporters that relief efforts were being handled
routinely by mobilization of the armed forces and physicians. He
noted it was a natural disaster and gave no indication any
presidential action was necessary or even under consideration.
   Gorbachev at the time was attending a star-studded reception at
the United Nations at the end of a day marked by his announcement of
a dramatic, military force reduction. Earlier in the day, he had bid
a friendly farewell to President Reagan, his four-time summit
partner, urged President-elect George Bush not to delay the
strengthening of U.S.-Soviet ties and toured New York for the first
time.
   A short time later, as other members of his entourage were going
to bed, Gorbachev instructed Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze
to round up reporters for the announcement of his imminent return
home.
   Although such decisions are still reached in the secrecy of the
high Soviet counsels, it was apparent the remainder of Gorbachev's
highly publicized New York stay, including the opening of a trade
show, a stroll through Central Park and a tour of an art museum,
would have contrasted sharply with the stark pictures of disaster at
home.
   And Gorbachev, whose nationally televised personable chats with
constituents have set a new, modern style for a Soviet leader, could
hardly ignore the human tragedy. To continue on to Cuba and Britain
in the coming days almost certainly would have evoked comparison
with Reagan, who hesitated before breaking off a California vacation
to return to Washington after the Soviets shot down a Korean Air
Lines passenger jet in 1983.
   The Caucasus calamity took on an added dimension because it
struck a region that for months has been the scene of ethnic strife
between Armenians and Azerbaijanis and more recent nationalist
demonstrations in Shevardnadze's native Georgia.
   The unrest, which has exploded into fatal rioting in several
Azerbaijani cities and sparked massive demonstrations and general
strikes in Armenia, has prompted authorities to deploy troops and
tanks in the streets in some areas. Tens of thousands of refugees
have fled their homes in fear of pogroms.
   But despite the military presence, Gorbachev's policy of
glasnost, or openness, also has been evident in the region.
Authorities have tolerated dissent and criticism they once would
have crushed with brutal force.
</TEXT>
