<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthKorea     12-08 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Replaces Top Political Leaders, Radical Students Go On
Rampage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo replaced the top
leaders of his political party today as he continued efforts to
sever ties to his authoritarian predecessor.
   Roh named veteran legislator Park Joon-kyu chairman of the
governing Democratic Justice Party. Park replaced Yoon Giel-joong in
the party's No. 2 post, with Roh remaining as party president.
   Park immediately promised to work with the opposition parties to
remove all vestiges of the authoritarian rule of former President
Chun Doo-hwan and ensure the introduction of full democracy.
   Roh replaced his cabinet Monday and is planning further shakeups
as part of efforts to defuse nationwide furor over demands for
action against Chun. He has promised to release political prisoners
and compensate people who suffered under Chun.
   About 200 radical students demanding Chun's arrest attacked the
governing party's office in the southern city of Taegu today, the
Yonhap news agency reported. No injuries were reported and police
arrested five protesters, the agency said.
   ``Down with (President) Roh Tae-woo, who protects Chun
Doo-hwan,'' read placards carried by protesters.
   Park, who will oversee the daily workings of the party, said he
wanted to clear all questions about corruption and other abuses
under Chun by the end of the year. He urged the opposition to
cooperate with the government and said he would retain his post for
just one year to show his good intentions.
   A veteran lawmaker, Park was a top political leader in the 1970's
and is regarded as a moderate. He has headed the South Korean
delegation in recent talks with communist North Korea on easing
tension.
   As part of his promise to bring in more moderate officials, Roh
also removed Secretary-General Park Jun-byung, a retired army
general and noted hardliner.
   The two main opposition parties immediately criticized the
appointment of Park as party chairman, saying he had helped suppress
democracy in the past and his selection casts doubt on Roh's
commitment to reforms.
   Lee Sang-soo, spokesman of the Party for Peace and Democracy,
said, ``We get the impression that President Roh is retreating from
his promise that he will cut off ties with the Chun era.''
   The Reunification Democratic Party, the other main opposition
party, said Park's selection proved Roh wanted to maintain military
dictatorship.
   Roh asked the nation to forgive Chun after the former president
apologized to the nation Nov. 26 for abuses under his rule and went
into voluntary internal exile. But opposition parties say there can
be no question of pardon until Chun cooperates with a National
Assembly probe into his government.
   Chun, a former general who took power with military backing in
1980, stepped down in February at the end of an eight-year term.
Roh, also a former general, won presidential elections last December.
   In other party changes announced by Roh, lawmaker Lee Jong-chan,
52, was installed as secretary-general. The party's chief policy
coordinator, Lee Seung-yun, 57, was switched to the vacant post of
chief party policy maker.
   Party officials said a further shakeup, involving lower party
posts, is expected within days.
</TEXT>
