<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Orbison-Hometown     12-08 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Orbison-Hometown,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Texas Oil Town Basis for Orbison's Musical Career</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Orbison, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WENDY E. LANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Those who grew up with Roy Orbison never
doubted the musical ability that would carry him to rock 'n' roll
fame.
   ``I thought early on that Roy was the one of us that really had
the talent,'' said Charlie Evans, who played bass fiddle in a high
school band with Orbison. ``The rest of us were just hang-alongs.
   ``Roy would think and live and breathe music.''
   Orbison, whose piercing voice on such early 1960s hits as ``Oh,
Pretty Woman'' and ``Cryin''' made him a rock legend, died of a
heart attack late Tuesday in Hendersonville, Tenn. He was 52.
   Orbison came with his family to this West Texas oil town of 1,200
during the oil boom of the 1940s. His father, Orvie Lee, worked in
the Permian Basin oil fields but found time to teach his son to play
the guitar at age 6.
   Some here can still remember the singer-songwriter when he was a
skinny 11-year-old playing his guitar outside the drugstore for
small change.
   In high school, Orbison and some friends formed the Wink
Westerners, which played country and Western music at school dances
and bars and later had a radio and television show sponsored by a
furniture store in nearby Odessa.
   Evans recalled the group's first trip outside Texas, when they
traveled to Chicago as the campaign band for a Wink resident who was
running for a national Lions Club office.
   ``That was the first time any of us had been to the big city,''
he said. ``We had never seen a subway.''
   The group changed its name to the Teen Kings after its five
members graduated and played a newer kind of music: rock 'n' roll.
   After a trip to Nashville and a national tour, ``They came back
to Wink and all of them were driving Cadillacs,'' said John Paul
Pitts, a former Wink resident who lived one house away from Orbison.
   ``I used to come out of my house and see Roy in the back seat of
his car, practicing the guitar because his house was so small,''
said Pitts, who wore Orbison's sport coat for his high school
graduation because he didn't own one.
   Town officials last year renamed the street where the singer had
lived Roy Orbison Drive, although the shotgun house his family
occupied is no longer standing.
   Orbison's musical ambition was evinced in the verse beneath his
senior picture in his 1954 high school yearbook: ``To lead a Western
band _ Is his after school wish _ And of course to marry _ A
beautiful dish.''
   Orbison last visited West Texas for an Oil Aid concert in Midland
last year to benefit economically distressed oilfield workers.
   ``I never thought that success changed him,'' said Bill Beckham,
publisher of The Wink Bulletin and the Winkler County News, who
attended high school with Orbison. ``Wink was always home for Roy
even though he had not been there for many years.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881208-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 0749EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--UsherKilled     12-08 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Usher Killed,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Killed In Fall Through Ceiling Of Old Theater</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An off-duty usher exploring old rooms at
Hollywood's landmark Egyptian Theater fell 40 feet to his death when
a section of ceiling caved in, authorities said.
   Erick Pineda, 22, of Los Angeles, had gone to the auditorium
Tuesday on his day off to get passes to other Hollywood Boulevard
theaters, said Detective Glen Day.
   Apparently Pineda and a friend decided to explore the many rooms
leading to the theater's roof so that they could view the
auditorium's ornate ceiling, Day said.
   ``It's like the `Phantom of the Opera' up there,'' he said,
describing the rooms as ``old, dark, dank.''
   Most of the room's floors are concrete, but Pineda apparently
stepped on a section consisting only of acoustic tiles and fell to
the main theater, which was empty.
   The accident occurred shortly after 7 p.m., police said.
   Pineda was pronounced dead at the scene.
</TEXT>
