<DOCNO> AP881208-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 0652EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Summit-CityReax     12-08 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-City Reax,0602</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Many in City Stay Home, Turn on TV Sets during Gorbachev Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH J. HARPAZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most New Yorkers found the best view of the visit
by Mikhail Gorbachev on television.
   But being there, and being part of history, made a little
difficulty worth the effort for some residents of the traffic-choked
city.
   The Soviet leader's tour of Manhattan on Wednesday consisted
mainly of a speeding 45-car motorcade with flashing lights and
screaming sirens, punctuated by two stops during which Gorbachev
delighted crowds by emerging from his limousine.
   The 75-minute tour _ which followed Gorbachev's speech to the
United Nations and lunch with President Reagan and President-Elect
Bush _ will form some of the most lasting images of a trip cut short
by a severe earthquake in the Soviet south.
   Most were glad to see Gorbachev visiting the city, but for others
it either did not live up to their expectations or made things worse
during the hectic Christmas shopping season.
   ``That was it?'' said Joan Swift, as the limousines bearing
Gorbachev and his entourage sped off from the United Nations, where
she had waited more than an hour on Wednesday ``to just wave.''
   Some sidewalk vendors found the visit good for business. But
Santa Clauses complained of being moved from such key locations as
the door to the New York Stock Exchange to prepare for the Gorbachev
caravan.
   ``Gorby gridlock'' _ the traffic jams predicted for the motorcade
_ was never as bad as the most dire predictions. But that didn't
soothe the tempers of those who did bring their cars into midtown
and found evening rush hour worse than normal.
   The visit to Lower Manhattan at the start of the afternoon rush
hour left some motorists in their cars for more than an hour. The
Brooklyn-Battery Tunnel was also closed from 4:35 p.m. to 5 p.m.,
backing cars up several miles on both sides.
   Staten Island Ferry schedules were disrupted during the afternoon
as the Soviet party returned from the meeting on Governors Island.
And some buses couldn't run their normal routes with streets closed.
   In Times Square, police wouldn't let pedestrians through for
about a half-hour before the motorcade passed.
   ``I can't cross the street. I'm just trapped,'' said Ishmael
Roberts, who works in an office building in Times Square and wanted
to catch a bus home.
   Gorbachev's motorcade also closed Fifth Avenue for about an hour,
drawing a ``bah humbug'' from a Santa-suited bell ringer for the
Volunteers of America.
   ``It was bad for business,'' said James Robertson. ``Everything
was blocked off. It slowed down the donations.''
   Gorbachev's day also included a speech at the United Nations,
lunch with President Reagan and President-elect George Bush on
Governors Island, and a stop at the World Trade Center.
   While advocates for the homeless said the police had told the
homeless to leave the U.N. area _ a charge police deny _ officials
couldn't stop some 1,000 demonstrators from massing outside the U.N.
to remind Gorbachev of problems ranging from the plight of Soviet
Jews to unrest in Soviet Armenia. Fifty-six protesters were arrested.
   But most of the thousands who lined Gorbachev's motorcade route
were friendly, and the feeling of good will was not lost on the
Soviet leader.
   ``We're very pleased by the fact that thousands of New Yorkers
have come out to see us,'' he said at the World Trade Center. ``We
saw their faces, we saw their eyes, their friendliness.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
