<DOCNO> AP881208-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 0635EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     12-08 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Share Prices Fall Sharply, Dollar Up Moderately</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING due to computer routing problem</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices fell sharply on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange today, while the U.S. dollar rose moderately against the
Japanese yen following its upward trend in New York.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which jumped
beyond the 30,000-point mark for the first time Wednesday, plunged
291.92 points or 0.97 percent to finish trading at 29,758.90. The
index dropped almost 200 points in early trading and continued to
move lower.
   The dollar closed at 123.02 yen, up 0.59 yen from Wednesday's
close of 122.43 yen. The currency opened higher at 123.40 yen, but
gradually fell while fluctuating between 122.85-123.48 yen.
   The dollar's finish was higher than the 123-yen mark for the
first time since Nov. 16 when it closed at 123.54 yen.
   Stock traders attributed the Nikkei's drop today largely to
profit-taking and the higher dollar in the currency market.
   Many traders, who bought cheaper issues in spot trading and sold
issues in futures trading to turn profits Wednesday, were mainly
selling in spot trading today, pushing prices lower, said an analyst
with Nomura Securities.
   A dealer with a major securities firm said many institutional
investors were either sitting on the sidelines or selling issues for
profit-taking after Wednesday's big gain.
   Volume traded on the first section was estimated at a moderate
900 million shares.
   On the foreign exchange market, traders said the dollar's rise
followed sharp gains overnight in overseas markets after Soviet
leader Mikhail Gorbachev announced at the United Nations that he
would cut Soviet troop strength by 500,000 and reduce the number of
its conventional armaments.
   On Wednesday, the dollar closed at 123.63 yen in New York and at
123.40-123.50 yen in London.
   ``The market took the Soviet move as a helping hand for the
United States toward cutting its huge fiscal deficits'' by easing
U.S. defense obligations, said a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   There was little movement in Tokyo after the market opened, said
Minori Takeuchi of Chemical Bank in Tokyo.
   ``Although the dollar in New York sharply rose following news of
a possible Soviet arms reduction in Europe, players in Tokyo don't
believe the dollar's uptrend will continue much longer,'' she said.
   The Bank of Japan reportedly intervened in the market to support
the dollar before the close of Tokyo trading, buying dollars at
around 122.90 yen, currency dealers said.
</TEXT>
