<1ST_LINE>r p PM-BrothervsBrother     12-08 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brother vs Brother,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ben Stewart Defeats Bob Stewart In Mayoral Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNION POINT, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fourteen votes were enough to re-elect
the mayor over his fiercest opposition _ his brother, an 8-year City
Council veteran.
   Incumbent Ben Stewart won his fifth term as mayor in an election
Wednesday in which 322 persons, or 41 percent of the east-central
Georgia city's 778 voters, went to the polls.
   Stewart defeated his brother, Bob Stewart, 168-154.
   Both Stewarts said they were glad the race between them had come
to an end.
   ``I'm relieved it's over, I'm sorry the situation developed in
the first place,'' said the 39-year-old mayor.
   ``That's the way it goes. It was a close race,'' said Bob
Stewart, 33, adding, ``I didn't want it to happen. I'm glad things
are over.''
   The Stewarts were the only candidates in the non-partisan race.
   During the past few months, published reports said the rivalry
between the Stewarts started out as a feud over the
multimillion-dollar will of their father, the late John Ben Stewart,
who served as mayor from 1967 to 1979. The father was killed in a
automobile accident on Dec. 27, 1987.
   Several months ago, Bob Stewart said he filed a lawsuit against
his brother concerning a partnership in a business venture.
   ``It has nothing to do with the will. Nobody's contesting the
will that I know of,'' he said.
   Bob Stewart said his brother, who lost a bid for a state House
seat, told him he did not intend to seek re-election. Both were
surprised to see each other when they showed up on the first day of
qualifying for the $100-a-month job.
   ``I wanted to be the one to replace him,'' Bob said. ``I didn't
run a race against my brother. He ran against me. I announced
first.''
   In 1980, Bob Stewart, at age 25, was the youngest Union Point
council member ever to be elected.
   Since he could not run for the mayor's office and a council post,
Bob Stewart said his loss will mean devoting his energies into his
insurance agency.
   Ben Stewart, who is in the finance business, said his brother
never asked him if he planned to run.
   ``I qualified first and it was well-known that I was running,''
he said.
   The sibling rivalry fueled much talk among the town's 1,600
residents.
   `A lot of people are friends of both of us, and this has made it
hard,'' said Bob Stewart.
   The contest was ``a very sad, regrettable, unfortunate
situation,'' Ben Stewart said.
</TEXT>
