<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell in moderate trading this morning in
Europe as the foreign exchange market calmed after a sharp rally
Wednesday on news that Mikhail S. Gorbachev pledged to reduce the
Soviet Union's armed forces.
   Gold prices were mixed.
   Traders said the dollar was clearly overbought on Wednesday
following Gorbachev's speech at the United Nations.
   Traders said news that Gorbachev had to cut short his visit to
New York and return to the Soviet Union due to a major earthquake in
Armenia caused some confusion in the market today and took some
strength out of the U.S. currency.
   They said the dollar was likely to remain in a narrow range
during the day.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.59 yen to a closing 123.02 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 122.85 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.7505 West German marks, down from 1.7588
   _1.4720 Swiss francs, down from 1.4790
   _5.9755 French francs, down from 6.0025
   _1.9752 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9675
   _1,289.50 Italian lire, down from 1,290.75
   _1.1963 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1995
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.8480, from $1.8425
Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $423.25 a troy ounce, up
from $422.95 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $423.30.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $423.10, down from $423.50 bid late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.78 to close at a bid $424.88.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.18 a troy ounce,
up from Wednesday's $6.14.
