<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 0705EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua     12-08 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaragua Releases Opposition Leaders Jailed Since July</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRANADA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leftist Sandinista government has
freed the last 10 opposition leaders incarcerated since an
anti-government rally was forcefully broken up five months ago by
riot police.
   Two other leaders of the July 10 demonstration in Nadaime, 27
miles south of the capital Managua, were released last month because
of poor health.
   The day after the protest, the government expelled U.S.
Ambassador Richard Melton and seven other American diplomats in
Managua. It also closed the opposition newspaper, La Prensa, and the
official Roman Catholic radio station.
   Washington responded by expelling Nicaraguan Ambassador Carlos
Tunnermann and seven other Nicaraguan diplomats in Washington.
   The Nicaraguan government alleged Melton was using the U.S.
Embassy to direct a ``conspiracy'' against the government and that
the media were ``orchestrating'' the ambassador's plan.
   The Sandinista government and the U.S.-backed rebels, known as
the Contras, agreed March 21 to suspend offensive operations, but
talks aimed at a permanent end to the 7-year war are at an impasse.
   One leader released Wednesday, Carlos Huembes, said as he left
government custody, ``The only alternative in Nicaragua is the civic
fight.'' He said imprisonment had not intimidated him.
   A few family members and foreign correspondents were on hand when
the prisoners were released. Pro-government reporters did not attend.
   Suspended jail sentences for Huembes and Roger Guevara, of the
Nicaraguan Democratic Coordinate; Agustin Jarquin of the Social
Christian Party; and Miriam Arguello of the Nicaraguan Conservative
Party were based on charges that included causing public harm,
inciting a disturbance and illegal assembly.
   Arguello and Jarquin were released Nov. 15.
   The other demonstrators released Wednesday were given 18-month
sentences.
   The judge issued the order of conditional freedom because, ``They
(the opposition leaders) don't have previous criminal records, they
have good conduct records and their re-entry into society is not a
threat.''
   However, during the duration of their sentences, they will not be
allowed to leave the country and political activities in Nicaragua
will be limited.
   Defense attorneys appealed the sentence, saying it was unclear,
and paid fines for their clients' release.
   Guevara, for example, was forced to pay $406 for vehicle damage
that occurred during the demonstration.
   Miriam Arguello called the punishment ``political revenge'' and
``a judicial abberation.''
</TEXT>
