<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel     12-08 0680</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0705</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinian Shot In Heart By Soldiers, Division Over Arafat
Statement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GAZA CITY, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Arab teen-ager was
fatally shot in the heart today in a clash with soldiers as
Palestinians marked with a general strike the first anniversary of
their uprising against Israeli rule.
   Meanwhile, splits emerged among both Palestinians and Israelis
over PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat's statement recognizing the
existence of Israel.
   Yussef Mohammed Sbaith, 17, died of a bullet wound in the heart
after soldiers opened fire on stone-throwing youths in the West Bank
village of Kafr Rai, according to officials at a hospital in nearby
Jenin.
   The army said it was checking the reported fatality, which would
be the 320th Palestinian death since the uprising began Dec. 8
against Israel's 21-year occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Eleven Israelis also have died.
   Palestinians responded to today's call for a two-day general
strike by shutting down stores and other businesses throughout the
occupied lands, which are home to 1.5 million Palestinians and were
sized by Israel in the 1967 Middle East War.
   The army imposed curfews on all eight Palestinian refugee camps
in the Gaza Strip, confining more than 250,000 people to their homes
indefinitely.
   Residents of Gaza City's Shejayeh section said Israeli troops
also ordered a curfew there over loudspeakers and called on men 16
to 35 to report to a neighborhood courtyard.
   One resident said the move came after a firebomb was thrown at an
Israeli jeep, one of dozens of Israeli military vehicles seen on the
otherwise deserted streets.
   In the West Bank cities of Bethlehem and Nablus, troops ordered
residents out of their houses to paint over fresh graffiti and
forced teen-agers to tear down outlawed Palestinian flags.
   Many slogans mirrored differences over Arafat's statement and the
recent declaration of independence in Algeria by the PLO's
parliament-in-exile that implicitly recognized Israel.
   ``What do you want, Israel, after recognition?'' said one slogan
in Bethlehem signed by Arafat's mainstream PLO faction Fatah.
   Opposite views appeared in graffiti signed by the fundamentalist
Moslem group Hamas, or Zeal, and the Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine, a Marxist PLO faction.
   ``No concessions, not even an inch of Palestine,'' was scrawled
on a wall in Nablus.
   ``Yes to holy war against the enemy,'' declared another, painted
in traditional Islamic green, on one Bethlehem wall.
   Israelis also disagreed in their reaction to Arafat's latest
statement issued in Stockholm on Wednesday that called for peace
negotiations and accepted Israel's existence.
   Asked to clarify the statement, Arafat replied: ``This was clear
in resolutions adopted in the last session of our Palestine National
Council where we said clearly there are two states in Palestine, the
Palestinian state and the Jewish state, Israel. ... Is this now
clear enough?''
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres responded by laying down conditions
for recognizing the PLO.
   He said the PLO would have to drop conditions attached to
accepting U.N. Resolution 242, stop terrorism, including violent
anti-Israeli resistance in the uprising, and accept Israel's right
to live in peace.
   The U.N. resolution calls for Israeli withdrawal from lands
occupied in the 1967 Middle East war and for the right of all states
in the region to have secure borders.
   Peres, however, said he did not believe Arafat met his conditions
and referred to the PLO leader's latest moves as ``an exercise in
public relations.''
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir rejected Arafat's statement
totally. ``I don't see, and I don't think I ever will see, any real
change, because they (the PLO) were established in the name of
destroying Israel,'' he said on Israel television.
   Avi Pazner, a close adviser to Shamir, said Arafat should disband
the PLO if he really recognizes Israel because the organization was
created to destroy the Jewish state.
   ``He should clear the way for moderate Palestinians to emerge,''
he said.
   Ran Cohen, a leader of the small, left-wing Citizens' Rights
Movement, welcomed Arafat's statement, saying: ``I think rational
politicians should bless the process and ask how we can advance it.''
</TEXT>
