<HEAD>With A Smile, Barbara Bush Endures Watch Repair at Tiffany's</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's not everyone who gets a watch repaired at
Tiffany's, or Secret Service protection while they're waiting.
Future first lady Barbara Bush does.
   Mrs. Bush surprised Christmas shoppers Wednesday with a stop at
the famed jewelers before her luncheon meeting with first ladies
Nancy Reagan and Raisa Gorbachev.
   Secret service agents stationed in front of Tiffany's on Fifth
Avenue first drew a crowd as Mrs. Bush browsed inside.
   ``We're not shopping,'' she called out with a smile as customers
stopped to wish her well. Mrs. Bush made a quick stop at the store
to have her watch repaired, a store spokeswoman said.
   She engaged in small talk with those who stopped to congratulate
her on her husband George's election victory and signed an autograph
for Joshua Steinberg, 9, of Brooklyn.
   ``Now you all go shop,'' Mrs. Bush joked to the crowd.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Vigilant Police on Hand for Summit Nab Robbers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The extra police on the streets for the visit of
Mikhail Gorbachev helped lead to the capture of four men who
allegedly robbed a Brooklyn bank and killed a teller, authorities
said.
   ``They were pretty dumb,'' said police Officer Scott O'Brien.
``There were all kinds of police, Secret Service and FBI in the area
because of the Gorby visit.''
   During the course of the robbery at the Bowery Savings Bank on
Wednesday, a teller, Patricia Interdonato, 29, was shot in the chest
``because she didn't move fast enough,'' said Sgt. Edward Burns said.
   Interdonato, who lived in Brooklyn, died later at Methodist
Hospital, he said.
   The four suspects escaped in the car, but a nearby police patrol
car soon caught up with them, Burns said.
   ``We were on the presidential detail ... when we heard the job on
our radio,'' said O'Brien, who helped nab the suspects.
   The four alleged robbers, who all live in Brooklyn, were charged
with murder, robbery, criminal possession of a deadly weapon and
criminal possession of stolen property, Burns said.
   Police recovered $165,000 in cash, a police radio, a radio
scanner and three handguns, he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>A Picture's Worth A Thousand Words _ If It's Reagan And Gorbachev</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As a memento of their fifth meeting and last
get-together, President Reagan gave Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev a photograph taken during their first meeting more than
three years ago.
   Reagan presented the picture to Gorbachev Wednesday at the
conclusion of their luncheon meeting at Governors Island, a Coast
Guard station in New York Harbor, White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater said.
   The photograph showed Reagan and Gorbachev walking in the woods
at the Geneva summit in 1985. It was inscribed, ``We have walked a
long way together to clear a path for peace,'' and signed by Reagan.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Artist Delivers Gorby Goods, And Expects Something Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Artist Tom Stanford delivered a couple of
presents to the Soviet Mission Wednesday. He wants one back.
   Stanford, 38, gave security officers a portrait of Gorbachev, a
box of flowers for Raisa and a pencil drawing of the Soviet leader,
President Reagan and Vice President Bush.
   The agents, he said hopefully, ``were going to try to get the
drawing autographed for me.''
   Gorbachev can keep the portrait, he said.
   ``I wanted to be here to be a part of this. I came down here to
give him the painting, to deliver the flowers, and maybe take home a
treasure,'' Stanford said. ``Welcome to America, from a citizen.''
   Stanford seemed convinced that the Soviet leader would sign the
drawing and return it before his hurried departure today. ``I know
he's going to see it.''
