<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     12-08 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cold Air Sweeps Snow Through the Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold air mass swept down through the nation's midsection today,
dumping snow in Colorado, western Texas, New Mexico and parts of
Arizona, while thunderstorms struck northeast Texas.
   In Colorado, more than 12 inches of snow was measured around
Boulder, and the Denver area had between 4 and 7 inches on the
ground Wednesday evening. Colorado Springs had from 3 to 5 inches of
snow.
   Snow accumulated on some roads in the Texas Panhandle and
northern New Mexico. Rain changed to snow as far south as Roswell,
N.M., and across portions of Oklahoma and northern Arkansas.
   The heaviest snow was expected in the mountains of southern New
Mexico and southwest Texas.
   In the middle Rio Grande Valley of New Mexico, including the
Albuquerque area, winds gusted to 45 mph late Wednesday and were
expected to exceed 60 mph in some areas.
   Early today, thunderstorms and heavy rain hit portions of
northeast Texas. A flash flood watch was in effect this morning.
Small hail was reported from a thunderstorm in Leon County, Texas.
   Rain and thunderstorms also reached into much of Oklahoma,
Arkansas and northwest Louisiana.
   In the Northeast, light snow and freezing drizzle fell through
parts of Vermont and the Adirondacks of northeastern New York. Many
roads were reported icy, including interstate highways.
   Clear skies prevailed across the southeastern states.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from the
eastern two- thirds of Texas to eastern Oklahoma, the lower
Mississippi Valley and the Tennessee Valley; snow through western
Oklahoma, western Texas and much of New Mexico; rain scattered
through southeast Arizona; snow across Michigan; and high winds in
Southern California.
   High temperatures were forecast in the teens from eastern Montana
to North Dakota, northern Minnesota and western upper Michigan; the
20s and 30s from the the Rockies to most of the Great Plains, the
upper half of the Mississippi Valley, the Great Lakes and New
England; the 60s and 70s from south central Texas to the Gulf Coast
and the south Atlantic Coast, and from the desert Southwest to
Southern California; and in the 40s and 50s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 3
degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 74 degrees at Key
West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 46 fair; Boston 45 fair; Buffalo 28 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 48 foggy; Cincinnati 32 fair; Cleveland 34 partly
cloudy; Detroit 32 partly cloudy; Miami 65 fair; New York 46 fair;
Philadelphia 42 fair; Pittsburgh 31 partly cloudy; Portland, Maine
36 cloudy; Washington 45 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 12 fair; Chicago 27 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 46
foggy; Denver 17 snow; Des Moines 19 fair; Indianapolis 31 partly
cloudy; Kansas City 24 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 18 cloudy;
Nashville 44 cloudy; New Orleans 57 foggy; St. Louis 34 cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 31 windy; Anchorage 14 cloudy; Las Vegas 53
windy; Los Angeles 65 fair; Phoenix 49 fair; Salt Lake City 30 fair;
San Diego 66 fair; San Francisco 60 fair; Seattle 45 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 25 partly cloudy; Toronto 21 fair.
</TEXT>
