<DOCNO> AP881208-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 0715EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Shultz-NATO 2ndLd-Writethru a0488 12-08 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz-NATO, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0488,a0533,0720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Secretary of State Urges Further Soviet Cutbacks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with remarks at meeting from NATO general-secretary,
INSERT five grafs after 10th graf, `Reporting on ... official said.'
Picks up 11th pvs, `Shultz, in ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz met
today with NATO allies to try to persuade them to insist on further
cutbacks in Soviet troops in Europe beyond the 50,000 Mikhail S.
Gorbachev has offered to withdraw from East Germany, Czechoslovakia
and Hungary.
   In his farewell meeting with the 15 foreign ministers, Shultz
hoped to keep the allies focused on the 2-to-1 manpower edge U.S.
officials say the Warsaw Pact still enjoys.
   ``I'm not trying to suggest this decision should be sniffed at,''
a senior aide to Shultz said of the unilateral cutback offer
Gorbachev made Wednesday in a U.N. speech in New York.
   But the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, contrasted
the Soviet leader's decision to withdraw six tank divisions from the
three East European countries with the 20 divisions stationed in
East Germany alone. And, the official said, the 500,000 troops
Gorbachev offered to demobilize are only a fraction of the 5.5
million-man Red Army.
   Shultz called the proposal a ``welcome and significant step.''
But Gorbachev's appeal for ``certain steps soon'' by the West in
return apparently will not be answered.
   The Reagan administration, which has only 6{ weeks left in
office, does not intend to bring home any of the 335,000 U.S. troops
in Western Europe in response to the Soviet leader's move, U.S.
officials said.
   Despite the Soviet manpower edge, several American analysts have
called for a partial U.S. withdrawal. One reason, they suggest, is
to have the allies assume a larger share of the burden of defending
Western Europe.
   Instead, the United States and its allies are aiming at joint
negotiations early next year with the Warsaw Pact on a mutual
reduction in non-nuclear forces and tanks across the vast expanse of
Europe.
   The Reagan administration contends the Soviet-led alliance has a
3-to-1 advantage in tanks over the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization.
   Today, NATO Secretary-General Manfred Woerner opened the two-day
meeting by calling the Soviet decision to make unilateral troop cuts
in Eastern Europe an ``encouraging development which we welcome.''
   But, he said, ``the steps announced ... reduce, but clearly do
not eliminate Soviet superiority and do not establish a stable
balance.''
   ``If carried out,'' he said, ``they would undoubtedly be an
important step in the right direction and we will be looking forward
to their implementation.
   ``If this step means that the Soviet Union is coming to accept
the reality that their conventional superiority constitutes the
principal threat to stability and security in Europe, then we would
find (the) announcement still more encouraging,'' he said.
   Woerner said the allies were seeking ``binding and verifiable
agreements which would eliminate the present conventional
asymmetries.''
   U.S. officials had said reporting on Gorbachev's luncheon meeting
Wednesday in New York with President Reagan and President-elect Bush
was the ``lead item'' on Shultz's NATO agenda.
   Shultz, in his final session with the Western foreign ministers
before retiring, also scheduled a report on developments in Eastern
Europe and steps taken by the Soviet Union on human rights.
   In contrast to their cool reaction to Gorbachev's proposal to
restructure the Soviet armed forces, U.S. officials were
enthusiastic about the Soviet leader's promise to institute legal
reforms and take up every case in which the United States claims
political prisoners are being detained.
   Disputing Gorbachev, Shultz said there are still political
prisoners in the Soviet Union. But, he said, ``There have been a
great many released.''
   These and other steps taken by the Soviets are close to meeting
all U.S. demands before wrapping up a review in Vienna of the 1975
Helsinki agreement.
   In that 35-nation accord, the Soviets pledged improvements in
human rights in exchange for implicit Western acceptance of their
dominant position in Eastern Europe.
   Once the Vienna review is concluded, NATO and the Warsaw Pact
hope to open troop reduction talks. U.S. officials said it was still
possible to begin the negotiations before the Jan. 20 windup of the
Reagan administration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
