<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Summit-Afghanistan     12-08 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Afghanistan,0654</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Rejects Gorbachev's Proposal to Cease Arming Afghans</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to fix category code.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George Shultz rejected a
proposal from Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev to stop arming
Afghans and said anti-communist guerrillas were justified in trying
to seize territory before the Red Army completes its withdrawal.
   The fighting would continue, said Shultz, ``because the people of
Afghanistan, broadly speaking, do not accept the fact that the
puppet regime is entitled to hold certain areas of that country.''
   Gorbachev, in a wide-ranging speech Wednesday to the United
Nations General Assembly, called for a New Year's cease-fire in
Afghanistan, challenged Washington to stop arming the guerrillas,
and urged the warring parties to quit battling over terroritory.
   ``The bell of every regional conflict tolls for all of us,''
Gorbachev said, calling for superpower cooperation to end fighting
in Afghanistan, Angola and Cambodia.
   The Red Army invaded Afghanistan in December 1979. Last spring
Gorbachev agreed to withdraw the estimated 110,000 Soviet troops
there by Feb. 15. He suspended the withdrawal last month on grounds
the guerrillas were firing on departing Soviet troops.
   The Soviets also introduced advanced jet fighters and Scud
ballistic missiles and began to use them against the guerrillas,
according to Reagan administration officials.
   Gorbachev offered to end the dispute and remove outside forces
from the Afghan conflict.
   ``I don't want to use this rostrum for recriminations against
anyone,'' he said.
   Shultz, however, brushed aside the two main points of Gorbachev's
Afghan proposal: that the superpowers stop arming the warring
parties and that the combatants not attempt to gain any more
territory.
   ``We proposed to the Soviet Union quite some time ago a mutual
cessation of supplies, and they rejected that,'' Shultz told a news
conference after Gorbachev, President Reagan and President-elect
George Bush left Governors Island following a lunch meeting.
   Besides, said Shultz, the anti-communist guerrillas known as
Mujahedeen ``don't need a great deal of war supplies because they
are capturing a lot'' from the Soviet-backed Afghan army.
   It was unrealistic to expect the rebels not to seize territory as
the Soviets pull out because of anger stemming from the war, he said.
   Prior to the Soviet occupation in December 1979, said Shultz,
Afghanistan had a population of 15.5 million, of whom 1 million have
since been killed or wounded, more than 3 million driven into
Pakistan, 2 million into Iran and 2 million displaced within the
country.
   ``So I don't think it's surprising that people who have been
exposed to that kind of turmoil don't want to have anything to do
with a puppet regime ...'' said Shultz.
   Nevertheless, said Shultz, ``I think it is a good thing that the
Soviets are talking directly to the Mujahedeen'' during
unprecedented negotiations that began last Sunday in Saudi Arabia.
   An agreement between the Kremlin and resistance forces might
prevent further attacks on Soviet forces as they leave, he said.
   U.S. officials have said they expect the Red Army to meet the
Feb. 15 deadline to withdraw completely from Afghanistan.
   Gorbachev's proposal called for:
   _ A comprehensive cease-fire as of Jan. 1.
   _ The cessation of all offensive operations or shellings.
   _ The rival Afghan groups retaining, during peace talks, all
territories under their control.
   _ On the same day, Jan. 1, suspension of all arms supplies.
   _ Establishment of a ``broad-based'' government in Kabul, the
Afghan capital. He did not specifically call for participation by
Communist elements, which the Moslem fundamentalist insurgents have
vowed to resist.
   _ Sending a contingent of United Nations peacekeepers to Kabul
and ``other strategic centers of the country.''
   _ Facilitation by U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
of an international conference to neutralize and demilitarize
Afghanistan.
</TEXT>
