<1ST_LINE>u i PM-NATO     12-08 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NATO,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NATO Foreign Ministers Gather To Formulate Arms Reduction Strategy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Shultz-NATO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO foreign ministers today called for
substantial reductions in conventional forces in Europe as part of
their negotiating position at upcoming arms talks.
   The NATO position, intended to cover Western and Soviet bloc
forces, was released one day after Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev said he would unilaterally cut the Soviet armed forces by
500,000 troops, including 50,000 in the East bloc.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz also met with NATO members
today to try to persuade them to insist on further cutbacks in
Soviet troops.
   In a statement today, the NATO ministers said they will propose
an overall limit on the total number of arms in Europe.
   ``This limit should be substantially lower than existing levels,
in the case of tanks close to half,'' it said. ``This would mean an
overall limit of about 40,000 tanks.''
   In the statement, the allies also said no country should be
allowed to have more than a fixed proportion, such as 30 percent, of
total arms in Europe. Such a formula, it said, would set a cap of no
more than about 12,000 tanks for any one country.
   It also said NATO negotiators would propose limits on forces
stationed in other countries' territory.
   The statement said the allies' position would apply to all of
Europe.
   ``In order to avoid undue concentration of these weapon
categories in certain areas of Europe, we shall propose appropriate
sub-limits,'' it said.
   The allies' position will be offered at the Conventional
Stability Talks, scheduled to get under way early next year in
Vienna, Austria.
   Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher of West Germany said the
allies hoped to end preliminary discussions next month for the
negotiations.
   Genscher told reporters ``a new chapter could be opened in the
history of disarmament'' because of Gorbachev's move, made in a U.N.
speech Wednesday. But the ministers were preparing today's proposals
before the Gorbachev speech.
   The ministers' statement said the troop reductions ``are a
positive contribution in correcting'' what the 16-nation alliance
contends is an enormous superiority of Soviet bloc forces in Europe.
   A recent NATO report said the Warsaw Pact maintained 3.1 million
ground forces, or personnel, compared with 2.2 million for the NATO
countries.
   ``They indicate the seriousness with which the conventional
imbalances which we have long highlighted as a key problem of
European security are now also addressed by the Soviet government,''
the ministers said.
   In addition to reduction in arms, the ministers said they will
ask the Warsaw Pact countries to go along with ``stabilizing
measures'' that will cover deployment, movement and levels of
readiness of conventional armed forces.
   They also said they will demand ``a rigorous and reliable regime
for monitoring and verification.''
   NATO Secretary-General Manfred Woerner opened the foreign
ministers' meeting by saying the unilateral troop cut in Eastern
Europe was an ``encouraging development'' but will not ``eliminate
Soviet superiority.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
