<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Women'sShelterShooting     12-08 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Women's Shelter Shooting,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Dead, Two Wounded at Home For Battered Women</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A resident of a home for battered women opened fire
on shelter residents, killing a worker and wounding two other people
before surrendering after being promised hair curlers, police said.
   Juanita Angela Whitaker, 40, was being held for investigation of
first-degree murder. She was scheduled to be arraigned today.
   Witnesses told police the woman entered the shelter, operated by
the Volunteers of America, Wednesday morning and began firing,
hitting three people.
   Jeanne Archuleta, 24, a housekeeper at the shelter, was shot in
the head and chest while she was vacuuming an office and died later
at a hospital. Ken Sanchez, 29, also an employee, was shot in the
stomach and Pamela Hand, 31, a client, was hit in the right leg.
Both were in satisfactory condition.
   Police said the woman continued walking down the first-floor
hallway, firing into closed doors.
   After the shooting started, Sanchez and Hand locked themselves in
a first-floor office and Whitaker ran downstairs and locked herself
in her basement apartment.
   Sgt. Phil Dinan, who negotiated the woman's surrender, said she
demanded hair curlers before turning herself in.
   ``She was saying, `I need to get dressed, I need to put on my
make-up. I need my curlers. I can't find them,''' Dinan said.``She
was threatening to kill officers, and she was threatening to kill
herself.''
   Dinan said the woman wanted to surrender, but was afraid.
   ``She kept saying, `I watch TV, I know you cops come in and kill
people,''' Dinan said.
   Whitaker finally gave up and surrendered after being told she
would be taken out an exit shielded from news cameras. Police said
Whitaker was a former nurse's aide from Norfolk, Va.
   Authorities said they were still trying to determine a motive,
although Carla Eilts, Whitaker's roommate, said the woman was
distraught over a phone call informing her that she would have to
leave the center.
   Before hanging up, Whitaker said, ``That's the end for me,''
authorities said.
   ``Then she had that mean look like she was getting frustrated.
She got mad ... and she took it out on everybody,'' Eilts said.
</TEXT>
