<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DrugSweep     12-08 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Sweep,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Official Admits Drug Program A Failure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Operation Clean Sweep, the District of
Columbia's drug enforcement program, has not helped curb drug use in
the nation's capital but has created huge problems in the courts and
prisons, according to Police Chief Maurice T. Turner Jr.
   ``I don't see it having any impact on the demand for drugs,''
Turner said Wednesday. ``Arrests are not the answer.''
   ``We must reduce the demand side for the drug business,'' he said
in a Washington Post interview.
   The program, an expensive centerpiece of Mayor Marion Barry's
crackdown on drugs, has produced more than 43,000 arrests since
August 1986.
   Previous attempts to eliminate the program were strongly
criticized and blocked by the Barry administration.
   The city has recorded 336 homicides so far in 1988, most of them
drug-related. The previous high for a year was 287 in 1969.
   Turner said the police department has increased its ability to
arrest drug dealers. But at the same time, he said, the number of
drug users also has grown. ``All we have is more arrests,'' that
have ``crowded court calendars in D.C. Superior Court and pushed
prisons above their capacities,'' he said.
   Operation Clean Sweep usually is staffed by officers working
overtime. The overtime bill in the operation's first 18 months was
$6 million.
</TEXT>
