<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CemeteryMall     12-08 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cemetery Mall,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rabbis Say Shopping Center Doesn't Harm Cemetery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH RIVERSIDE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shopping center being built at one
edge of a Jewish cemetery shouldn't disturb visitors to graves
nearby, said two Orthodox rabbis who toured the construction site.
   ``I have taken the facts which seem to indicate there was no
violation of burial areas,'' said Rabbi Gedalia Dov Schwartz of the
Chicago Rabbinical Council. ``That is the main consideration.''
   Rabbi Israel Fishweicher, executive director of the rabbinical
council, agreed.
   Developers want to build a shopping center on an unused portion
of Jewish Waldheim Cemetery, just west of Chicago.
   Plans for the center, to include consumer electronics and
clothing stores, were drafted more than a year ago and the village
rezoned the property in June.
   Criticism erupted when construction was witnessed by a few people
paying their respects at the cemetery. One objector even said he
might move the remains of his parents.
   Schwartz and Fishweicher toured the area Wednesday with shopping
center developers.
   Schwartz noted that a road separates the cemetery from the
shopping center, and Sportmart, the sporting goods retailer
developing the land, plans to erect a buffer of trees and bushes.
   A committee of the rabbinical council was scheduled to discuss
the issue at a meeting tonight, and the rabbinical council might
issue a report by the end of the week, Schwartz said.
   The Des Plaines Cemetery Corp., which owns the land, said the
land was originally reserved for burials but many Jewish families
have moved from the area, reducing the demand for burial plots.
</TEXT>
