<2ND_LINE>PM-Youngster Returned,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kidnapped 2-Year-Old Freed Unharmed With Instructions To `Take Her
Home'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 2-year-old girl kidnapped with her
baby sitter was released unharmed 12 hours later, apparently by
captors who told a group of children ``she's missing, take her
home,'' police said.
   The child, who was taken from her home Tuesday night, appeared to
be in good physical condition, Police Officer Gary Luckett said.
   ``She was released in front of some third graders outside of
Woodcrest Elementary School'' around 8:30 a.m., he said. ``They told
the students, `She's missing, take her home,' and then they drove
away.''
   The child and her baby sitter, who was released earlier, were not
identified by police, but Luckett said members of the child's family
were not public figures.
   A man was arrested in the kidnapping after he allegedly attempted
to pick up ransom money, police said. They declined to release his
identity. Two other men also were being sought in the case.
   The child and the 26-year-old baby sitter were abducted by two
armed men who forced their way into the youngster's home,
blindfolded the baby sitter, then drove off with them, Luckett said.
   The woman was released around midnight and told to ```start
walking and don't turn around,''' Luckett said.
   The kidnappers then called the child's grandfather and demanded a
$300,000 ransom be placed in a safe at a location in South-Central
Los Angeles, Luckett said.
   Police accompanied the grandfather as he left the ransom money at
the spot and later arrested a man who tried to pick up the cash.
