<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RideauClemency     12-08 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rideau Clemency,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gov. Roemer Denies Clemency Request</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governor has rejected a request to
reduce the prison sentence of a killer who left death row to become
a model inmate and a nationally recognized prison journalist.
   Wilbert Rideau, who is serving a life sentence, was originally
sentenced to death for a 1961 bank robbery in which he kidnapped
three employees, shot and wounded two of them and killed the third
by slitting her throat.
   Although Rideau, 47, has been praised by prison officials for his
behavior behind bars, his previous bids for a reduced sentence have
been rejected because of strong opposition from Calcasieu Parish law
enforcement officials and the victims.
   Gov. Buddy Roemer cited the same reasons in issuing his decision
Wednesday.
   ``Given the horrible nature of this crime, the fact that both
surviving victims oppose clemency and the fact that Calcasieu law
enforcement officials oppose clemency, I deny Rideau's plea for a
reduced sentence,'' Roemer said.
   A reduced sentence would have made Rideau eligible for parole.
   Rideau was arrested shortly after the robbery and murder and
confessed in front of television cameras. He spent 10 years on death
row until the U.S. Supreme Court struck down the state's capital
punishment law in 1972.
   With his sentence commuted to life in prison, he became the first
black to gain a position on the prison magazine, the Angolite, and
is now editor.
   Rideau has said his journalism is proof of his rehabilitation.
   He is one of the most visible inmates at the Lousisiana State
Pentitentiary at Angola, frequently appearing on national television
shows. He and other editors have been singled out for national
recognition by organizations ranging from private foundations to the
American Bar Association.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
