<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 1028EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ArchaeologistSlayings     12-08 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Archaeologist Slayings,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Sentences Killer To Death in Archaeologist Slayings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORRISTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury ordered the death penalty for a man
convicted of stabbing two women to death and wounding a married
couple at an archaeological site.
   In announcing the death penalty Wednesday, jury foreman David J.
Roscoe said the panel believed Arthur Faulkner had ``a degree of
mental illness,'' but that was outweighed by the savagery of the
crimes for which the jury had convicted Faulkner on Tuesday.
   Faulkner, 32, was found guilty of murder, attempted murder,
aggravated assault, rape and other offenses in the April 1 stabbing
deaths of the women and the wounding of a husband and wife.
   When the death sentence was announced, Faulkner shrugged.
   Delores Dorner, mother of one of the victims, said: ``I prayed
very hard for this day. It will never bring her back, but at least
she'll rest in peace now, and I'll have peace of mind.''
   Faulkner's court-appointed attorney, Robert A. Selig, portrayed
his client during the sentencing hearing as suffering from paranoia
and schizophrenia, disorders he said could have prompted Faulkner to
commit the murders.
   Gerald Cooke, a forensic psychologist, testified that Faulkner
hears voices and had been psychotic for many years.
   But Dr. Timothy Michaels, a prosecution witness, said Faulkner
does not meet the criteria for a paranoid schizophrenic and that he
did not suffer from organic brain damage, another defense assertion.
   Selig's plans to present an insanity defense for Faulkner during
the trial fell through when Montgomery County Common Pleas Judge
Samuel Salus ruled the two psychiatric experts who had evaluated
Faulkner could not testify because they had not found him legally
insane. Selig called no witnesses during the trial.
   Faulkner was convicted in the stabbing deaths of Clarice Dorner,
30, of Elk Grove Village, Ill., and Annalise Killoran, 22, of Lynn,
Mass. Faulkner also was charged with attacking Glenn Sheehan, 39,
who operated S.J.S. Industries, the archaeological firm where
Faulkner and the victims worked, and Sheehan's 31-year-old pregnant
wife, Anne Jensen.
   After the sentencing hearing, District Attorney Michael Marino
called Faulkner ``a brutal, sadistic murderer who hates women. The
man's an absolute menace and the death penalty is entirely
appropriate for him.''
   Selig said he would appeal. He said he ``would feel better if
this had been a fair trial.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
