<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Mandela 1stLd-Writethru a0474 12-08 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mandela, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0474,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black African Leader Transferred To House On Prison Farm</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with calls for Mandela's release,
other details. Changes byline. No pickup.
^By LAURINDA KEYS</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of African National
Congress leader Nelson Mandela today demanded his unconditional
release, saying his transfer to a house on a prison farm simply gave
him a more luxurious cell.
   The government has been under intense domestic and international
pressure to release the 70-year-old Mandela, who has been in prison
since 1962.
   ``The government is playing games. Mr. Mandela is still a
prisoner, confined to the premises of a jail,'' said Anglican
Archbishop Desmond Tutu.
   ``Let the government release him and all other political
prisoners unconditionally. Then they will see the enormous influence
for good, for peace and reconciliation that he will be,'' he said.
   Mandela was transferred Wednesday night from the private
Constantiaberg Clinic near Cape Town where he had recovered from
tuberculosis, the government said. He was taken to a suburban-style
house with a swimming pool and garden at the Victor Verster prison
farm in Paarl, a scenic wine-growing town northeast of Cape Town.
The government says he can have unlimited access to his wife,
children and grandchildren.
   ``Mr. Mandela is not confined to the house and has free use of a
wide range of facilities,'' the Prisons Service said today.
   But officials indicated Wednesday that Mandela's release is not
imminent and restraints on him will be eased in stages so the
government can assess the political impact of his possible freedom.
   ``That is not freeing him unconditionally,'' said Helen Joseph,
83, the first South African ever placed under house arrest for
anti-apartheid activities. ``It's scandalous to play cat and mouse
like this. He's not free, he's just in a luxurious prison, a more
comfortable jail.''
   Mandela's wife, Winnie, in a statement released by attorney
Ismail Ayob, rejected the offer of unlimited visits and said she
would continue the monthly 40-minute visits ``until all political
prisoners are given the same privileges.'' There was no indication
that other visitors, such as the media, would be allowed access to
Mandela.
   Mandela was convicted in 1964 of sabotage and plotting to
overthrow the white minority government.
   The outlawed African National Congress is the largest guerrilla
organization fighting the government and apartheid.
   Mandela has rejected the government's repeated offers to release
him if he renounces violence or lives in a tribal homeland. He has
said the government should renounce violence, end apartheid and
legalize the ANC.
   In August, Mandela was diagnosed with tuberculosis and
transferred to a hospital from Cape Town's Pollsmoor Prison. Later,
he was moved to the Constantiaberg Clinic, a private hospital near
Pollsmoor, and officials announced last month Mandela would not
return to Pollsmoor upon recuperation.
   Mandela's transfer is one of a series of moves by the government
in the past two weeks aimed at easing international pressure on
South Africa.
   The government has commuted the controversial death sentences of
six blacks known as the Sharpeville Six and freed two other
prominent, long-serving black prisoners _ ANC leader Harry Gwala and
Zeph Mothopeng, president of the rival Pan-Africanist Congress.
   But the government has given no indication that it is willing to
negotiate with freed black leaders on their demands for one-person,
one-vote democracy.
   Under apartheid, South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881208-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 1031EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Bush-Labor 1stLd-Writethru a0487 12-08 0770</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Labor, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0487,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Men, Woman Still in Running for Labor Secretary</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with AFL-CIO, inserting new grafs 5-6, Ridge's and</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressman who raised money from unions for
other GOP House candidates, the government's top personnel officer
and a Washington labor lawyer are the top candidates for secretary
of labor in the Bush administration, officials said.
   Both Rep. Thomas Ridge of Pennsylvania and Office of Personnel
Management Director Constance Horner have been conducting low-key
campaigns to get the job.
   William J. Kilberg, whose wife Barbara is a member of
President-elect George Bush's transition staff, has told associates
he is ``absolutely not interested'' because it would mean giving up
a lucrative law practice, but his name is still in the pot, a
transition official said Wednesday.
   ``All three of them have been mentioned frequently; all three are
still alive,'' the official said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Ridge's and Horner's names were mentioned to the AFL-CIO earlier
this week by Bush's transition team, according to one business
lobbyist, who said Horner apparently was labeled as unacceptable to
the labor leaders.
   The labor federation endorsed Democrat Michael Dukakis in the
presidential election. Rex Hardesty, an AFL-CIO spokesman, said it
would have no comment on any discussions concerning the Republican
president-elect's personnel actions until after they are announced.
   Also mentioned as a long-shot candidate is Frank P. Doyle, senior
vice president for General Electric Co. in charge of the company's
labor, government and media relations.
   Doyle acknowledged in an interview that he has been approached
about the job and is interested but said his political party
affiliation is a major hurdle.
   He's a Democrat _ not just a registered Democrat but a person who
has raised political money for Democratic candidates, a sure
disqualifier, according to one senior Republican official.
   Although they have been adversaries across the bargaining table
for three decades, labor leaders familiar with Doyle view him as one
of their more ``enlightened'' opponents and would have no problem
with his nomination.
   However, several business leaders do. Many of them view Doyle as
too ``progressive,'' citing GE's willingness to accept congressional
legislation mandating 60-day advance notices of plant closings and
layoffs and its support for a bill that would have made employers
warn workers about potential health hazards on the job.
   Ridge, 43, represents a heavily blue-collar district around Erie,
Pa., and helped raise money from several unions, including the
building trades and the United Food and Commercial Workers, for
other GOP House candidates as an active chairman of the
congressional Republican Labor Council.
   ``He's young and a total break from the past,'' said one union
official. ``If George Bush wants a bridge to labor, Ridge could
build it. He's also someone who knows Capitol Hill at a time when
there are going to be a lot of labor initiatives legislatively.''
   Horner, who had worked in Bush's 1980 campaign for president,
sought the labor post a year ago when President Reagan gave it to
Ann McLaughlin. Her point position for the administration on drug
testing of federal workers and opposing comparable worth efforts to
raise women's pay engendered heavy opposition then from public
employee unions.
   However, the leadership of the largest federal workers' union,
the American Federation of Government Employees representing some
700,000 employees, has changed hands since then.
   Its new president, John Sturdivant, a black whose white opponent
was endorsed by Jesse Jackson, says he has a good working
relationship with Horner and would not oppose her. Other union
sources, however, say opposition to her remains intense among other
high-ranking labor leaders.
   Kilberg, 42, was the Labor Department's solicitor from 1973 to
1977 and also was chief counsel for the Federal Mediation and
Conciliation Service during the Nixon administration.
   He is now a partner in a Washington law firm, representing
employers in dealings with government agencies and unions and
Congress, and also is editor-in-chief of the Employee Relations Law
Journal.
   Kilberg attended Cornell University on a local scholarship from
the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers and is
considered by both labor and business leaders to have been a
knowledgeable ``honest broker'' in the government posts he held.
   Kilberg is said to be reluctant to give up his practice. He also
is involved in complicated pension cases that he is reluctant to
leave, said one person close to him.
   However, Kilberg and his wife are family friends of the Bushes.
And both the president-elect and his wife, Barbara, showed up at a
fund-raising picnic for Mrs. Kilberg when she ran for a seat in the
Virginia Legislature.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
