<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Dukakis-BudgetWoes 1stLd-Writethru a0564 12-08 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Budget Woes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0564,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis: State Facing $636 Million Deficit; Savings Ordered</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates lead to include proposed layoffs, SUBS 7th graf, ``We
have ...,' with 2 grafs to add dropped word, more on Dukakis
proposals.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis, using measures he had
hoped to apply to the federal budget, unveiled a package of spending
cuts, layoffs, and increased tax enforcement to close a
Massachusetts budget deficit of at least $636 million.
   But less than a month after losing the presidential election to
Vice President George Bush and his ``read my lips'' pledge not to
raise taxes, Dukakis gave his strongest hint yet that he might
consider new levies if the package doesn't balance his $11.6 billion
budget.
   The Democratic governor said he would wait until the end of this
month to monitor spending and tax collections before deciding.
   ``I'm not going to recommend increased taxes unless I think we
must have them. I want to make sure we do everything we can to meet
these goals before we go down that road,'' he said.
   Dukakis spoke to reporters at a Statehouse news conference jammed
with anxious legislators and government staffers to give his first
detailed assessment of the state's fiscal predicament since the Nov.
8 election.
   After months of warnings from legislators about the state's
budget, Dukakis estimated the budget deficit would be at least $636
million in the fiscal year that ends June 30. He reached the
forecast after trimming his revenue projections by $308 million, as
recommended by the Revenue Advisory Board.
   ``We have serious problems facing us,'' Dukakis said, but he
added that the state must make investments in the future. ``If they
are not going to be made in Washington, they have to be made, to
some extent, right here in Massachusetts.''
   Among his proposals were eliminating 300 unspecified management
positions, reducing the state's consultant budget by $15 million and
adding millions of dollars in new fees.
   In a message apparently intended for his liberal supporters,
Dukakis insisted he would not retreat from the agenda he has
followed since returning to office in 1983.
   ``I want to make it very clear that we're going to fight for the
goals and values that have guided us for the past six years,'' he
said, citing education, employment, environmental protection,
housing and health care.
   To close the budget gap, he said the state would draw $121
million from its ``rainy day'' fund, raise $90 million through
stepped-up tax collection efforts, delay $84 million in college
scholarship funds and save $100 million by cutting Medicaid waste
and squeezing executive agencies.
   The plan also includes at least $165 million in forced spending
cuts by the state bureaucracy.
   Dukakis defended his plan to tap the ``rainy day'' fund, which
bond-rating agencies consistently cite as a reason for the state's
high credit rating. The governor said the stabilization fund was
created for situations similar to what the state is facing.
   Asked whether his presidential campaign had contributed to the
problem or delayed his response to it, Dukakis noted that he cut or
withheld $200 million before signing the budget in July and said tax
collections were on target in the first four months of the fiscal
year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
