<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 1126EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LeadersSummit     12-08 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Leaders Summit,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet-American Emerging Leaders Summit Ends With Agreements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet and U.S. citizens ended a weeklong
meeting with some tearful goodbyes, but vowed to continue improving
relations between the superpowers.
   ``We are confident that what we have started here in Philadelphia
will continue in the future, and be beneficial not only to the
people of our two great nations but to all people of the world,''
the 170 Soviets and 169 Americans said Wednesday in a joint
statement capping the U.S.-U.S.S.R. Emerging Leaders Summit.
   ``It was a good beginning,'' said Stephen Hayes of Columbus,
Ind., president of the American Center for International Leadership,
which co-sponsored the gathering with the Soviet Union's Committee
of Youth Organizations.
   The Soviet delegates enjoyed last-minute shopping before leaving
the city for Washington and four days of sightseeing before heading
home. The group also spent two days in Chicago before arriving here.
   A reciprocal summit is tentatively planned in the Soviet Union
next year.
   ``We as emerging leaders are about to become the custodians of
this planet. When we take charge, I hope we do so in the spirit of
cooperation without fear of each other and a commitment to see to it
that the next generation, and the generations after that, will live
a long and peaceful life,'' said leadership board chairman Raoul
Carroll.
   Hayes and Sergei Chelnokov, chairman of the Soviet committee,
said many of the agreements reached at the summit covering 16 areas
ranging from religion to Soviet-American relations will be made
public within the next two months
   One agreement announced by the science and technology commission
recommended: ``Scientific communities of our nations should join
efforts to overcome unjustified restrictions imposed on the exchange
of information and ideas.''
   The commission suggested establishing joint workshops on an
unpiloted mission to Mars before the year 2000, alternative sources
of energy, the global warming crisis and computer-based information
gateways.
   Meanwhile, Drexel University President Richard D. Breslin made
sure there was ``at least one tangible result'' from the summit.
   He announced the creation of a full-tuition scholarship that will
enable a Soviet student to pursue three years of graduate study at
Drexel. Of Drexel's 12,265 current students, only four are from the
Soviet Union, according to university officials.
   The details of the scholarship _ which could be worth up to
$28,800 _ still need to be worked out with the Soviet Ministry of
Education, he said.
   The student is expected to start at Drexel in September 1989.
   ``It's going to be marvelous,'' Breslin said. ``We hope that the
scholarship is a beginning of an exchange ... of faculty members and
learning between ourselves and some of their fine learning
institutions.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
