<2ND_LINE>PM-Steinberg, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0556,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nussbaum Testifies They Planned to `Adopt' Lisa Before Her Birth</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with 10 new grafs of today's testimony, picks up 4th
graf pvs ... `The sex ...'; FIXES 6th graf pvs to read `to
conclude,' sted `of'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The live-in companion of an accused child killer
testified today that she and the defendant knew before their
``adopted'' daughter, Lisa, was born that the baby would probably be
given to them.
   Joel Steinberg, 47, is charged with fatally beating the illegally
adopted child. She was removed unconscious from his apartment on
Nov. 2, 1987, and died of a brain injury three days later.
   Hedda Nussbaum, Steinberg's battered former companion and the
prosecution's chief witness, testified at the trial today that the
baby's biological mother was a friend of hers and Steinberg's.
   ``We were kept aware of her health and progress,'' Ms. Nussbaum
said.
   Michele Launders, 27, the mother, has watched the trial daily
from a front-row seat. Steinberg, a lawyer who has since been
disbarred, had told Ms. Launders that her child would be placed with
a middle-class Catholic family in Manhattan and she paid Steinberg
$500 for ``filing fees.''
   Ms. Nussbaum, 46, testified she and Steinberg began talking about
adopting a child in 1980.
   ``I had been trying to conceive and was unable to,'' she said.
Steinberg, as a lawyer, ``had done a number of adoptions and we
talked about doing one for ourselves.''
   Lisa was born May 14, 1981. Ms. Launders has said that she was in
the baby's presence only for seconds before the infant was taken
away.
   Testimony resumed after a one-day break Wednesday,
   Nussbaum testified Tuesday that she and Steinberg were told by a
physician friend in October 1983 that his wife had abused Lisa, then
2. Ms. Nussbaum said Lisa's genital area was bruised when the girl
returned from a stay with the physician and his wife.
   The sex abuse allegation was first discovered in papers found by
police when they searched Steinberg's apartment after Lisa's death.
In the papers, Dr. Michael Green accuses his wife, Shayna, of
sexually molesting the girl in the summer of 1983 when the child
visited the Greens' Long Island home.
   But Assistant District Attorney Peter Casolaro said out of the
jury's hearing that the statement was ``created by Mr. Green at
Steinberg's urging ... for the purpose of slandering his (Green's)
wife in a divorce.''
   A source said the prosecution investigated and found no basis to
conclude Mrs. Green had molested Lisa. The source said the Greens
told investigators that if Hedda saw anything on the girl, it was
``diaper rash.''
   Green told police Steinberg ``coerced'' him into accusing his
wife of abusing Lisa and that he was severely beaten by Steinberg
and Ms. Nussbaum.
   The source said Green admitted in interviews with prosecutors
that his statement was a ploy to use against his wife in their
divorce.
   The Greens, who Ms. Nussbaum said joined her and Steinberg in
cocaine parties, have since reconciled and live near Harrisburg, Pa.
   When asked by a reporter Wednesday about Ms. Nussbaum's
allegations, Green replied, ``They're unfounded.'' He said ``a good
percentage'' of her testimony was untrue.
   Ms. Nussbaum made the allegation of sexual abuse under
cross-examination by Steinberg's lawyer, Ira London.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
