<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Armenia-Glance     12-08 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Armenia-Glance,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armenia At-A-Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some facts and figures on Armenia, the southern Soviet
republic where a devastating earthquake killed thousands of people.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE LAND _ Armenia is a mountainous republic covering 11,490
square miles, an area similar in size to the state Maryland. It is
bordered by Turkey on the west, the Georgian Soviet republic to the
north and the Azerbaijan Soviet republic to the east. To the south
lie Iran and the Soviet republic of Nakhichevan. The capital of
Armenia is Yerevan.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE PEOPLE _ The population is 3.3 million, about 90 percent
Armenian, most of whom are Christian. About 5 percent are
Azerbaijani, 2.3 percent Russian and 1.7 percent Kurd.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE ECONOMY _ Mining is an important industry, and Armenia has
large deposits of metals and minerals. Other industries are
chemicals, textiles and wine-making.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HISTORY _ Armenia was proclaimed a Soviet socialist republic on
Nov. 29, 1920. In February, Armenians began agitating for annexation
of the Armenian enclave of Nagorno-Karabakh, a mountainous region in
Azerbaijan. The protest caused anti-Armenian riots in cities in
predominantly Moslem Azerbaijan, and so far the unrest has resulted
in about 60 confirmed deaths.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
