<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SenateOfficials     12-08 0169</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Senate Officials,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Retains Top Appointed Officers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate's top appointed officials will keep
their jobs in the upcoming 101th Congress, Senate Majority Leader
George Mitchell said Thursday.
   Walter J. ``Joe'' Stewart, secretary of the Senate the past two
years, will remain in that post. He previously served as secretary
for the majority from 1979 until 1981, when Republicans took control
of the chamber and he became secretary for the minority. He later
resigned to work in private business, returning to the Senate as its
chief administrative and financial officer in 1987.
   Henry K. Giugni will return as sergeant-at-arms and doorkeeper, a
position he has held for two years. The sergeant-at-arms is the
chief law enforcement and protocol officer of the Senate.
   Mitchell, D-Maine, who was elected majority leader by fellow
Democratic senators last week, also announced that C. Abbott
``Abby'' Saffold will remain as secretary for the majority and
Martha S. Pope will serve as chief of staff for the majority
leader's office.
</TEXT>
