<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SAfrica-TreasonTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0574 12-08 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Treason Trial, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0574,0634</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Sentences 11 Activists After Major Treason Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 13 grafs to UPDATE with U.S., Tutu, Boesak reax;
PICKS up 9th graf pvs, ``Human rights ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today sentenced three black
leaders of the country's largest anti-apartheid group to prison
terms of 10 to 12 years after a highly publicized three-year treason
trial.
   ``I would rather err on the side of leniency,'' Judge Kees van
Dijkhorst said as he sentenced Patrick Lekota, 40, the publicity
secretary for the United Democratic Front, to 12 years for treason.
   Popo Molefe, 36, the front's national secretary, and Moses
Chikane, 40, Transvaal Province branch secretary, each received 10
years for treason.
   A person convicted of treason can be sentenced to death in South
Africa.
   Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu described the sentences as
vicious. The U.S. Embassy called the judgment regrettable because
the defendants were ``men of good will working peacefully for a
non-racial, democratic South Africa.''
   Thomas Manthata, 48, a church field worker, also was sentenced to
six years in jail for treason.
   Supporters raised clenched fists in the courtroom and shouted,
``Viva!'' Then the audience and defendants sang ``God Bless
Africa,'' the anthem of the anti-apartheid movement.
   Mohammed Valli Moosa, the front's acting national secretary, said
the sentences were ``extremely harsh when you take into account
these are non-violent people who were engaged in peaceful protest.''
   Van Dijkhorst ruled that the United Democratic Front was a
revolutionary organization which collaborated with the outlawed
African National Congress to incite anti-government violence in 1984.
   Tutu and the Rev. Allan Boesak were named as unindicted
co-conspirators with more than 900 other front supporters.
   ``It's a vicious sentence,'' said Tutu. ``I myself will certainly
be very, very involved in ensuring that I leave no stone unturned in
overturning that conviction and sentence.''
   Boesak, president of the World Alliance of Reformed Churches,
said he had been involved in consumer boycotts just like the
sentenced men.
   ``If you allow this to happen that means that we will concede
that everything we have been doing is criminal, is illegal, is
wrong, is treasonous,'' Boesak said.
   Human rights activist Max Coleman said the sentences were lighter
than expected to fit a recent government policy of projecting a
softer image. But he said ``what would be legitimate protest in most
countries is a crime here.''
   Of seven other defendants, convicted of terrorism, six received
suspended five-year prison terms and the other was sentenced to
serve five years. Those with suspended sentences were banned for two
years from talking to the press, attending public meetings or
participating in politics.
   Van Dijkhorst said he was lenient because, ``None have been found
guilty of planning or executing direct violence.''
   Defense lawyer George Bizos had argued for suspended sentences,
noting most defendants had spent at least three years in prison.
   The trial began in 1985 in Delmas farm town and later shifted to
Pretoria. Eleven of the original 22 defendants were acquitted at
various stages.
   Ambassadors from the United States, Britain, France and West
Germany were among spectators packed into the courtroom.
   Several leading opponents of South Africa's system of racial
segregation, including novelist Nadine Gordimer, testified for the
defendants.
   Able to speak freely because restrictions on anti-government
statements do not apply in the courtroom, the witnesses voiced
support for the ANC and refused to condemn its use of violence.
   The sentences came the day after the government transferred ANC
leader Nelson Mandela to a comfortable home on a prison farm. It was
the first time since 1962 that he has been out of a cell, except for
hospital stays.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
