<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Summit-Demonstrations 3rdLd-Writethru a0591 12-08 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Demonstrations, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0591,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Human Rights Protesters Put Blight on Gorbachev's Day</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf with clergymen not meeting with
Gorbachev.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE P. BAYLISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands may have cheered Mikhail Gorbachev as
he sped through the city in his motorcade, but the Soviet leader got
a more doleful dose of free speech from about 1,000 demonstrators
outside the United Nations.
   Fifty-six people from the Students Struggle for Soviet Jewry were
arrested after they crossed police barricades and sat in the street
outside the U.N. on Wednesday to protest the treatment of Jews in
the Soviet Union. They were taken away in vans, charged with
disorderly conduct and released.
   Other protesters included Ukrainians, Armenians and supporters of
dissidents in the Baltic states, where nationalism has been on the
rise.
   Many speakers at the demonstration, including city Comptroller
Harrison Goldin, called on Gorbachev to push for human rights as
well as glasnost, his policy of openness.
   ``We hope that as (Gorbachev) pursues glasnost he will be equally
vigorous in implementing a fundamental human freedom: the right to
emigrate and freely practice one's religion,'' said Goldin. ``For
Jews, that is fundamental.''
   Another speaker, Rabbi Haskel Lookstein, said, ``We appreciate
the initial steps ... but there's much more to be done.''
   Franklin Smiles, a rabbinical student, was asked if he thought
Gorbachev _ who stepped directly from his limousine to the U.N.
building _ even heard the demonstrators' message.
   ``It's more important that it reaches Americans,'' he said,
explaining that they can pressure U.S. officials to pressure their
Soviet counterparts.
   Several hundred Eastern European emigres demonstrated on the
other side of the street. A group of Ukrainians, many of them
elderly, waved Ukrainian flags in favor of independence from the
Soviet Union.
   Members of an Estonian group waved their national flag and
chanted ``One two three four, open up the iron door.'' Estonia
recently declared limited autonomy from the Soviet Union.
   Arunas Degutis, 30, editor of an opposition newspaper in
Lithuania, was not particularly impressed with the turnout. He said
that 250,000 people were at the last demonstration he attended in
Lithuania, and that 10,000 protesters can be mobilized there with
two hours' notice.
   More than 100 Armenian-Americans protested Gorbachev's handling
of ethnic unrest in the neighboring republics of Azerbaijan and
Armenia.
   ``The extent to which glasnost ... will truly offer democracy has
yet to be seen,'' said an organizer, Dr. Ara Caprielian. ``Talking
about the past and getting something today are two different
things.''
   Groups of Armenian and Jewish protesters also gathered outside
the Soviet mission, where Gorbachev spent two nights. They chanted,
sang and made speeches.
   About 4:30 a.m. today, two people who tried to set up a banner
near the mission were arrested when they ignored a police order to
move, said Sgt. Ed Burns, a police spokesman. They were given
disorderly conduct tickets and released.
   Later, six Armenian clergymen hoping to see Gorbachev were
allowed through police barricades and into the mission. The most
prominent among them were identified by police as Torkom Manoogian,
archbishop of the Eastern Diocese of the Armenian Church in North
America and Archbishop Vazken Keshirshian, primate of the Armenian
Church in Canada. They left nearly an hour later, saying they had
not met with Gorbachev.
   The Soviet leader was forced to leave New York a day early today
because of a devastating earthquake in the Soviet south, Soviet
Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze said.
</TEXT>
