<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Ulanhu     12-08 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Ulanhu,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ulanhu, Legislative Vice Chairman, Dies At 82</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Only one name for Ulanhu is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ulanhu, vice chairman of the National People's
Congress who fought for native Mongolian rights during his more than
60-year political career, died Thursday. He was 82.
   Ulanhu died in Beijing after being hospitalized for an
unspecified illness, the official Xinhua News Agency said.
   He worked for Inner Mongolia's independence from
Nationalist-ruled China in the 1930s and also fought Japanese
efforts to occupy Inner Mongolia. He also served as personal
secretary to a Chinese warlord in the region and did underground
work for the Chinese Communist Party.
   After the party's victory in 1949, Ulanhu held a series of posts
in the central government, including vice premier.
   He also was appointed government chairman, party secretary and
army commander in Inner Mongolia and ruled the vast barren region
virtually single-handedly for nearly two decades before being
toppled in 1967 during the Cultural Revolution.
   As Inner Mongolia's top official, Ulanhu urged China's majority
Han nationality to respect the rights of the country's minorities,
including the Mongols.
   When radical youth groups called Red Guards tried to take over
Inner Mongolian government offices in 1967, Ulanhu used his troops
against them. Leftist leaders in Beijing finally sent in outside
troops to remove Ulanhu from office on charges of having made
himself ``ruler in an independent kingdom.''
   Ulanhu's supporters in Inner Mongolia fought the outside troops
for months, calling themselves the Genghis Khan Combat Corps, in
honor of the 13th century Mongolian general who conquered much of
Central Asia, including parts of China.
   After being rehabilitated in 1973, Ulanhu held posts in the
party's top policy-making bodies, the Central Committee and the
Politburo, but was never returned to office in Inner Mongolia. He
also led numerous delegations overseas in the late 1970s.
   He has served as a vice chairman on the National People's
Congress, the legislature, since 1975. Currently there are 18 other
vice chairmen.
   He retired last year at the 13th National Party Congress.
   Ulanhu was ``a long-tested veteran communist, an outstanding
party and state leader and a proletarian revolutionary as well as a
noted guide of minority-nationality affairs,'' said Xinhua, quoting
an obituary issued by the party.
   He was born in 1906 in Inner Mongolia to an aristocratic family.
He was educated in Moscow and Beijing, where he joined the Communist
Youth League in 1923 and the Communist Party soon after.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881208-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 1257EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Sudan Bjt   12-08 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan, Bjt,0688</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fear of Food Riots Delays Distribution of Relief Supplies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Red Cross workers fearful of food riots
have held off distributing relief supplies to thousands of Sudanese
who lived for months on grass, roots and leaves after fleeing civil
war, an official said Thursday.
   Food flown to the area for the past five days is being stored to
ensure adequate supply when workers begin handing it out, said
Pierre Pont, the Khartoum representative of the International
Committee of the Red Cross.
   ``We couldn't start mass distribution until we had stockpiled
enough food, or else there would be riots,'' said Pont, who flew
with Wednesday's Hercules C-130 flight to Wau, a government-held
southern city surrounded by rebels.
   Pont said the only food distributed so far has gone to hospital
patients, children in an orphanage and other small ``vulnerable''
groups.
   The rebels in the predominantly animist and Christian south are
fighting a 5-year-old war for social reform and autonomy from the
Moslem-dominated government in the north. Relief flights to the
south began Sunday after the rebels dropped their threat to shoot
down the planes, but recent rebel attacks on relief convoys have
been reported.
   Beginning Sunday, the C-130 carried 18 tons of food at a time
from Khartoum to Wau, 625 miles to the southwest, and flights from
Kenya took food and medicine to rebel-held towns in the bush, Pont
said.
   Another airlift, organized by the United Nations, is using
smaller planes to take food to Aweil, 45 miles northwest of Wau.
   ``Wau is lacking in everything,'' Pont said in an interview. ``It
is a dramatic situation there, but you don't see people dying in the
streets any more.''
   Before the current airlift, he said, the last relief shipment
arrived six or seven months ago in Wau, whose population swelled to
100,000 from its normal 50,000-60,000 because of people displaced
over the summer.
   ``They survived by eating roots, leaves and grass,'' said Pont.
``The old people and the children were the worst affected.''
   But, he said, ``all goes well with the airlift. We are confident
that eventually the displaced can be fed and slowly we can improve
the nutrition status.''
   In Wau as elsewhere, most of the displaced people have returned
to the countryside to harvest wild rice. Cole Dodge, Khartoum
representative of the U.N. children's relief organization UNICEF,
said the crop is good enough to produce stocks that will last until
next year's early-summer rainy season.
   The Red Cross has 10,000 tons of relief supplies in Sudan, where
relief workers estimate half a million of the 6 million southerners
died this year from the war and the famine it induced. U.N.
officials say conditions have deteriorated to such an extent that
famine is sure to strike again with the rains in 1989.
   The airlift is the first since Sudan's civil war began in early
1983 that has its safety guaranteed by the government and the rebel
Sudan People's Liberation Army.
   The rebels have shot down three civilian aircraft since 1986,
killing more than 70 people. Until now, they had threatened to fire
on any aircraft in the south that was not carrying supplies for
rebel-held areas.
   Aweil, normally home to 30,000 people, grew to 90,000 over the
summer, when rains isolated it from the outside. Pont said it has
received no relief help in more than a year, and 8,000 people are
thought to have died there.
   Unlike Wau, a city with buildings, Aweil is a ``real African
village with lots of African huts,'' said Pont, who also flew there
on Wednesday. ``It's very pretty.''
   Pont said Aweil's village market is functioning, but the only
food its merchants offer is roots and peanuts.
   Also Thursday, the U.N. World Food Program announced that food
aid worth $5.4 million will be sent to some 370,000 nomadic
shepherds in northeast Sudan. The Rome-based agency said the
shepherds lost most of their animals during the 1983-85 drought and
are now rebuilding their herds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
