<HEAD>Poor Safety Training Costs 13 Miners' Lives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirteen miners suffocated in a coal mine fire
because they had not been trained to use their emergency oxygen
equipment, a newspaper said Thursday.
   Some of the dead from the September accident were found clutching
the emergency tanks in their hands, the Workers' Daily reported,
quoting the China General Corporation of State-Run Coal Mines.
   Investigators discovered that the victims had tried
unsuccessfully to use their equipment, which included a two-hour
oxygen supply, the newspaper said.
   The fire occurred in the Feng Feng Mine Bureau's Xuecun Mine in
Hebei province, about 250 miles south of Beijing. The Workers' Daily
reported it for the first time Thursday, but did not say why it had
not been reported earlier.
   The paper said the mine had not made a serious effort to train
its contract workers _ those hired temporarily. It said other recent
mine accidents revealed that contract miners lacked even the most
basic safety training.
   Huang Yicheng, minister of energy resources, said this week that
more than 100 people were killed in coal mine accidents in November,
the highest monthly total this year.
