<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HeritageFoundation     12-08 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Heritage Foundation,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conservative Group Recommends Budget Freeze, Staff Discipline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A conservative think tank weighed in Thursday
with 927 pages of recommendations for President-elect Bush on how to
run the government, including a freeze on government spending and
dismissal of staff members who deviate from administration policies.
   Leaders of the Heritage Foundation said their third quadrennial
``Mandate for Leadership'' book contains more than 2,000
recommendations from 400 experts, many veterans of the Reagan-Bush
administration.
   Heritage President Edwin Feulner Jr. told a news conference that
based on the influence of the 1980 and 1984 books on Ronald Reagan,
``We can confidently predict that the Bush administration ... will
pay close attention to these recommendations.''
   Several top Bush administration officials, including Vice
President-elect Dan Quayle, have already been briefed on the
recommendations, and Bush will get his own copy of the book Friday,
Feulner said.
   The book recommends a harder-nosed approach on holding down
federal spending, including subjecting all programs including Social
Security to the Gramm-Rudman deficit ceiling law. It urges Bush to
propose a freeze on spending, and to base his budget blueprint on a
freeze, not on current services.
   The president is required by law to submit a current services
budget, which sets forth what it would cost to maintain government
services and programs in the next budget year, taking inflation into
account and before any proposals for cuts.
   Charles L. Heatherly, a Heritage vice president and co-editor of
the book, complained that the current services approach ``determines
the whole way the debate is framed.''
   Heatherly said Bush should ``fire somebody, anybody, for not
staying in line with official administration policies'' early in his
presidency.
   He said Bush should also move quickly to figure out who his
friends and enemies in Congress are, rewarding the friends and
giving the enemies the cold shoulder.
   It is essential that Bush have at least a reliable core of
one-third-plus-one members of both the House and Senate to sustain
his vetos, Heatherly said.
   ``The veto will be the only trump card,'' he said.
   The book repeats a host of Heritage positions including letting
workers opt out of Social Security in favor of private retirement
accounts, pressing ahead with President Reagan's Star Wars missile
defense system, and renewing military aid to the Contra rebels in
Nicaragua.
   This ``Mandate'' is actually 166 pages shorter than the 1980
tome, which ran 1,093 pages. ``Mandate for Leadership II,'' in
Reagan's midterm, ran 565 pages.
</TEXT>
