<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Quake</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<HEAD>Reagan Offers US Aid; Red Cross Prepares Medical Supplies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan today told Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev the United States stands ready to do whatever
it can in the aftermath of the devastating Armenian earthquake as
the Red Cross sent $50,000 and prepared to dispatch medical supplies.
   Reagan, in a telephone call to Gorbachev shortly before the
Soviet president flew home from New York to lead the recovery
effort, expressed Americans' sorrow and said, ``If there is any way
we can be of assistance, either bilaterally or through the
international community, please let me know.''
   As he left New York, Gorbachev thanked Reagan and ``the American
people for those feelings and for their readiness to give
assistance,'' but did not say what, if anything, the Soviets would
ask for.
   Meanwhile, the president of the American Red Cross said that
$50,000 had already been sent to aid in the relief efforts as ``an
immediate gift.''
   Richard F. Schubert, president of the organization, said that
members of the Armenian community in Los Angeles had already offered
to help.
   Donations, Schubert said in a statement, should be sent to local
chanters or to the American Red Cross, International Disaster
Relief, P.O. Box 37243, Washington, D.C., 20013, and marked
``Soviet-Armenian Earthquake.''
   ``We have agreed that just as soon as an assessment is made, we
will begin to supply their needs as we have the ability to do,''
Schubert said in an appearance on the television show ``CBS This
Morning.'' He said early indications are that the Soviets will need
large supplies of antibiotics.
   ``Soviet Red Cross officials reported a particular need for
blood, and more than 850 donations were taken from volunteers and
staff, students, workers and military personnel during the early
hours of the morning there,'' Schubert said in his statement. ``All
blood needs for the earthquake victims will be collected from
internal Soviet Union resources,'' he said.
   The temblor that devastated much of Soviet Armenia on Wednesday
leveled cities and killed thousands of people.
   One unconfirmed report put the number of dead at 70,000.
   The 16,000-resident town of Spitak, near the epicenter of the
tremor, was reportedly wiped out. The government newspaper Izvestia
said just one of the town's eight schools still stood.
   ``This is an incredible disaster,'' Schubert said, an event
``that would tax the resources of any society, including the Soviet
Red Cross.''
   Besides blood, Schubert said, the Soviets ``also have airlifted
in about 15 tons of blankets, tents, first aid kits.
   ``Armenia at this point in the year is pretty cold, and so there
is a critical need for emergency shelter,'' he explained.
   Schubert said that in addition to U.S. assistance, Soviet
officials have been in touch with the international League of Red
Cross Societies in Switzerland, which will coordinate aid programs.
</TEXT>
