<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AMA-CareTechnologist     12-08 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AMA-Care Technologist,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AMA Says It Will Go Ahead with Plans for New Type of Hospital Worker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Medical Association officials say they are
going ahead with plans to establish training programs for a new type
of hospital worker who would provide bedside care.
   The decision came Wednesday, despite objections from some members
of the association's 422-member House of Delegates, the group's
policy-making body.
   Called a ``registered care technologist,'' or RCT, the new worker
category also has been opposed by the nursing profession.
   Lucille Joel, president of the American Nurses Association, told
an AMA committee Monday that her organization would not cooperate.
   Ms. Joel and other nursing leaders have argued that RCTs, trained
to provide bedside care such as emptying bedpans or delivering
meals, would only duplicate work already performed by nurse's aides
and licensed vocational nurses.
   Hospitals should instead hire more workers to stock cabinets and
perform other tasks unrelated to patient care that have fallen upon
nurses, Ms. Joel said.
   But Dr. James Sammons, executive vice president of the AMA, said
Wednesday that just because the nurses association doesn't want to
cooperate doesn't mean that nurses don't want to.
   ``I'm sorry Lucille said that, because she now has driven the
wedge even deeper,'' Sammons said at a news conference after the
final session of the House of Delegates semiannual meeting in Dallas.
   ``RCT is not a nurse. It's not meant to be a nurse, and it's not
meant to replace a nurse,'' said AMA trustee Dr. Joseph Painter, a
vice president of M.D. Anderson Cancer Center in Houston.
   An RCT advisory committee made up of doctors, nurses and hospital
officials will convene in January. Painter said the first pilot
program should begin by mid-1989.
   While the AMA delegates agreed that they must investigate
short-term and long-term solutions to the national nursing shortage,
the New York delegation proposed dropping any reference to RCTs.
   ``Basically, we have a big problem with the inflammatory term of
registered care technologist,'' said a New York delegate, Dr.
Richard Eberle of Syracuse.
   In what appeared to be a close show of hands, the House of
Delegates defeated New York's proposal to drop the term RCT. The AMA
tallies votes only at the request of the speaker of the House of
Delegates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881208-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 1328EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SnakeCity     12-08 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Snake City,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pythons Found Moving Into Neighborhood</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLDSMAR, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The seventh large python snake found
slithering around the same neighborhood has officials puzzled, but
not panicked.
   Experts are not sure where the snakes have come from, but say
rodents are in far more danger than residents.
   The latest python to be spotted in the 20-block area was captured
Wednesday. All seven snakes have been either full-grown Burmese
pythons or reticulated pythons from Southeast Asia, averaging 12 to
15 feet in length and weighing up to 175 pounds, said Debbie Parker
of Wildlife Rescue and Rehab Inc., a St. Petersburg facility that
cares for injured or abandoned wild animals.
   But because they are not aggressive and appear well-fed, Parker
believes they may have been turned loose by their owner.
   ``We're talking about big, big snakes, as big around as my leg,''
Parker said. ``If I lived in the area, I'd be worried. They're big
enough to eat a small child.''
   Pythons are constrictor snakes and suffocate prey, normally small
mammals such as raccoons and opossums.
   Burmese pythons are unlikely to attack people and should flee
when confronted by humans, said Patrick Parisi, president of the
West Coast Herpetological Society. He said such a snake would have
to be starving before it would attack a child for food.
   But pythons have small, sharp teeth that can inflict a painful
bite, he said. They also have a natural fear of falling that could
cause them to coil around anyone who attempts to pick them up.
   Reticulated pythons are the world's largest snakes, reaching
lengths of up to 36 feet. Burmese pythons can grow to 24 feet,
Parisi said. Both snakes can live up to 50 years in captivity.
   Parisi said it's possible the pythons may be offspring of snakes
that either escaped or were turned loose by the now-defunct Tarpon
Springs Zoo, which closed more than two decades ago. Development may
be forcing the snakes out of woodlands, he speculated.
   All of the snakes have been taken to the Wildlife Rescue
facility. If they are not claimed within 10 days, they can be
donated to schools, zoos or other educational facilities, said
Vernon Yates, director of the center. Five of the snakes already
have been donated to other institutions, he said.
   ``I don't think there's too many people in this world we have to
tell to stay away from them,'' said Sheriff's Office spokesman John
Bocchichio.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881208-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 1335EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a BC-GorbachevText     12-08 0773</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Gorbachev Text,0786</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Text of Gorbachev's Comments at Airport Farewell</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of the comments of Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, as spoken by his translator, at John F. Kennedy
International Airport prior to his departure for the Soviet Union on
Thursday:
   ``I would like to say that I have to cut short this visit and to
return to the Soviet Union because late last night, it was reported
to me that the earthquake that struck the Transcaucasian Republics
of the Soviet Union and particularly Armenia was extremely severe
and had extremely grave consequences, devastation and grave loss of
life. I urgently have to return to the Soviet Union.
   ``At present, a government commission is already at work, headed
by the prime minister of the Soviet Union. It is already in the
disaster area. Urgent measures are being taken to help all those
affected by this terrible tragedy, and I have to be there in this
effort.
   ``This morning, I had telephone conversations with President
Reagan and Vice President Bush. Both of them expressed profound
condolences on behalf of the American people to those affected and
to the government and people of the Soviet Union. I thanked them for
the expression of those feelings, and let me say here again on
behalf of myself, of the Soviet people and on behalf of those to
whom those feelings of sympathy were expressed by the president and
the vice president, let me extend our deep gratitud and our profound
appreciation.
   ``The president and the vice president conveyed their willingness
to extend assistance and appropriate help in this situation. I would
like to thank them, and I would like to thank the American people
for those feelings and for their readiness to give assistance in
this difficult hour.
   ``It has so happened that we had only one working day here in New
York. But I and my delegation believe that this was a very important
day. We were able to set out our views at the United Nations on the
world today and on the prospects of the world's development. We did
that at the United Nations, an organization which we value very
highly, and whose role we believe will grow in the development of
new international relations.
   ``We also were able to have another of the useful exchanges at
the United Nations, to talk to representatives of many countries,
and we feel that they understand what we said at the United Nations.
   ``Yesterday, I had the meeting with President Reagan and Vice
President, the president-elect, George Bush, and members of the
current and future U.S. administrations. We and the American side
share the view that this was a very important meeting which has
confirmed the high level of Soviet-American relations, which makes
it possible to discuss very important questions affecting relations
between our countries and problems of improving international
relations.
   ``This was a good meeting held in a very good atmosphere, an open
and trusting atmosphere. We believe that it was characterized by a
readiness to understand the positions of each other. And yesterday,
when I was asked to describe in one word the essence and the main
motive of that meeting, I said that word was continuity.
   ``So that meeting yesterday, and the telephone conversations that
we had today when we also briefly addressed our future cooperation,
make us confident, make the Soviet Union and the United States
confident, that our relations will expand and improve on the basis
of cooperation, on the basis of mutual respect for each other's
interests, and also taking into account responsibilities for our
nations and for the world.
   ``I think I would remiss in my duty if I went home without saying
how much we are grateful to New Yorkers for the hospitality and
feelings of friendship that they have been expressing over these
days. So to all New Yorkers, our very warm gratitude. We value that
very much. We believe that this may have been one of the most
important things that happened on this day of our stay in America.
That shows increased and increasing respect and friendliness and
willingness to cooperate on the part of the Soviet people and the
American people.
   ``The road ahead will be tough but we will go ahead, and we will
_ I believe _ be building on what has been achieved if we act as we
have been acting, and also maybe add something new. I think that
would open up good prospects for our two peoples and will be
extremely important for the world as well.
   ``Goodbye and thank you.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>End of Text</HEAD>
