<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Health-PromotingStates     12-08 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Health-Promoting States,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>States Vary On Health-Promotion Measures, Survey Finds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Virginians and Californians are among the most
exercise-concious Americans, and residents of Missouri and Maryland
among those most likely to be overweight, a study of 21 states shows.
   Florida topped an overall ranking of how much people do to
promote their health, in the results released Thursday.
   New York topped the list of four metropolitan areas surveyed for
overall health promotion, followed by Los Angeles, Philadelphia and
Chicago.
   The rankings are based on surveys commissioned by Prevention
Magazine and carried out by pollsters Louis Harris and Associates
Inc., from 1983 through 1987. They are based on average scores for
the five years and do not account for changes within the period,
researchers said.
   Only the 21 most populous states were analyzed because at least
100 people in each state answered the survey questions, the report
said. The states cover 78 percent of the nation's population, the
study said.
   The percentage of residents who exercised strenuously at least
three times a week ranged from 42 percent in Virginia and 39 percent
in California to a low of 25 percent in New York state.
   Sixty-five percent of Missourians and 63 percent of Maryland
residents were reported to be overweight, with a low of 48 percent
among Californians.
   For overall health promotion, each state and metro area was
ranked by the extent to which residents followed health-promoting
behavior from a list of 21 practices. The scores were weighted to
emphasize practices with the most health impact.
   Items included on the list, called a ``Prevention Index,'' were
not smoking, wearing a seat belt, following healthy dietary
practices, avoiding driving after drinking, getting frequent
exercise and an annual blood pressure test, and taking steps to
control stress.
   The New York metropolitan area scored 1.01 above the national
average for the index, with New York City as a subcategory ranking
even higher at 1.17. The other areas in order were Los Angeles,
Philadelphia and Chicago. Chicago scored 1.13 percent below average.
   Florida scored 1.67 percent above the national average, while
Minnesota ranked last with 2.90 percent below average.
   The other states, in descending order from second place, were
Virginia, Massachusetts, New York, California, Washington state,
Michigan, Pennsylvania, Georgia, Texas, New Jersey, Maryland,
Illinois, North Carolina, Missouri, Louisiana, Tennessee, Ohio,
Indiana and Wisconsin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
