<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Education     12-08 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Education,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protest March Starts Week of Educational Turmoil</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELENA SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 4,000 students and striking
technical school teachers on Thursday began a week of protests
across Greece with a march to press for increased government
spending on education.
   ``Nothing, nothing, will stop us now!'' the demonstrators shouted
outside the offices of Education Minister George Papandreou, son of
socialist Premier Andreas Papandreou.
   ``We have no professors, books, laboratories or lecture halls .
.. simply because government spending on education is so low,'' said
Costas Vassiliou, a technical school student.
   The younger Papandreou refused to meet with the student leaders,
ministry officials said.
   The protest was the first of several slated to take place before
the government's 1989 budget is debated in Parliament Dec. 15.
   Education spending, 8.2 percent of total government outlay, will
rise by less than 1 percent next year, according to the proposed
budget.
   Inflation is running at 14 percent.
   Students and teachers claim a 15-percent increase is needed to
end chronic shortages of technical equipment, books and teaching
staff.
   ``The increase neither keeps abreast of inflation nor takes into
account our soaring tertiary-school trained population,'' said
Stelios Klimopoulos, who heads the Union of Technical School
Educators.
   Earlier this year, George Papandreou promised wide-ranging
reforms in education and pledged his father's government would raise
the education allocation to 15 percent of the national budget.
   Greece's 17 state-run universities and technical colleges shut
down on Wednesday as professors staged a 24-hour walk-out to back
their demands.
   Educators said they planned to repeat the strike next week unless
the government pledges a major increase in education spending.
   The educators said they want a 50-percent salary hike and funds
for updating books and expanding graduate research programs. A
university lecturer with six years' experience currently earns $785
monthly.
   ``Because of our teaching duties, we're obliged to give short
shrift to research and because of lack of funds we don't have the
equipment to conduct it,'' said a lecturer at Athens' prestigious
Polytechnic Univeristy.
   The absence of graduate research opportunites is evidenced by the
large number of students who flock to Western universities to
continue their studies.
   More than 20,000 Greek students are working in graduate programs
in the United States and the European Economic Community, according
to Education Ministry officials.
</TEXT>
