<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FamilyPoisoning     12-08 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Family Poisoning,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Rule Out Coke Plant as Source of Toxin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALTURAS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators have ruled out a Coca-Cola
bottling plant as the source of a deadly pesticide found in soft
drink bottles at the home of a central Florida family, authorities
said.
   Officials are searching for the source of the chemical, thallium
sulfate, that poisoned four family members, leaving one in critical
condition.
   Traces of thallium sulfate, an insecticide and rat poison banned
from general use in 1965, were found Dec. 1 in four empty Coca-Cola
bottles at the home of Peggy Carr, 41, her son Duane Dubberly, 16,
and her stepson Travis Carr, 16, said Polk County sheriff's Capt.
Ray Church.
   Mrs. Carr is in critical condition and the teen-agers also remain
hospitalized. Mrs. Carr's husband, Parearlyn, absorbed traces of the
chemical but did not become ill, officials said.
   Investigators from the FBI, Food and Drug Administration and the
Polk County sheriff's office inspected the Tampa Coca-Cola Bottling
Co. plant on Wednesday.
   ``We're reasonably confident tht there's no problem in the
manufacturing or distribution process,'' said William Grigg, an FDA
spokesman in Washington.
   ``If tampering occurred, it happened after the bottles were
filled and capped,'' said sheriff's spokesman Steve Hulsey.
</TEXT>
