<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Gorbachev 1stLd-Writethru a0667 12-08 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Gorbachev, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0667,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thatcher Says She Understands Gorbachev Change in Plans</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with message from Queen,
itinerary. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, ``In a ...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher learned from a
radio news bulletin Thursday that Mikhail S. Gorbachev wasn't coming
to visit her, and she promptly called the station to say she
understood.
   ``Mr. Gorbachev has got to go home, anything else would be
unthinkable,'' Mrs. Thatcher said of the Soviet president's decision
to cancel his visit to London because of the earthquake in Armenia.
   Queen Elizabeth II and her husband, Prince Philip, sent a message
to Gorbachev expressing ``our heartfelt sympathy to you and all
those affected by this tragedy.''
   ``Naturally, I am sorry that we shall not be able to welcome you
to London next week,'' the message said. ``We look forward to doing
so soon.''
   Gorbachev had planned to have lunch with the British monarch at
Buckingham Palace and hold talks with Mrs. Thatcher during the Dec.
12-14 visit. His itinerary included laying a wreath at the tomb of
the Unknown Warrior in Westminster Abbey and visiting St. Paul's
Cathedral and a factory.
   In a chatty call from her 10 Downing St. residence to the BBC's
early morning news program, ``Today,'' Mrs. Thatcher said she'd
heard the news on the program.
   ``It was the first indication we've had'' of the canceled visit,
she said.
   ``Then I heard later that you (the BBC) didn't know whether I'd
heard so I thought I'd better let you know I had ... that I heard
through your program,'' she said.
   Mrs. Thatcher sounded unconcerned no one had informed her
officially.
   ``His people would expect it (his return) and he is just the sort
of person who would do it,'' Mrs. Thatcher said of Gorbachev, with
whom she has a good rapport. He has visited Britain twice and she
visited Moscow last year.
   Later Thursday, Soviet Ambassador Leonid Zamyatin met with Mrs.
Thatcher and gave her a message from Gorbachev apologizing for
canceling the trip.
   In a letter of reply, Mrs. Thatcher congratulated Gorbachev on
his announcement of big conventional arms cuts Wednesday, expressed
sympathy about the earthquake and invited him to Britain whenever he
can come.
   ``It holds out new hope _ and makes it all the more important
that we should meet soon to discuss the way ahead,'' Mrs. Thatcher
wrote of Gorbachev's proposal.
   In the letter, released to reporters by her office, she also told
Gorbachev: ``I entirely understand ... your place must be at home at
a time of such tragedy, and I know you would feel this very
strongly.''
   Emerging from Downing Street with the ambassador, she said
Gorbachev's speech reflected a ``whole new philosophy of treating it
all now as one world.''
   The prime minister cut off a reporter who suggested to the
ambassador that Gorbachev was returning home abruptly because of
political dissent.
   ``We're having none of that,'' said Mrs. Thatcher, standing
alongside the ambassador. ``This is a tragedy, it's a great tragedy
... this is a time for all to come together.''
</TEXT>
