<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     12-08 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pakistan, Afghan Guerrillas React Coolly to Gorbachev's Proposals</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gorbachev, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan guerrillas and their Pakistani
backers reacted coolly Thursday to Soviet Presdient Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's proposals for a cease-fire and arms cut in Afghanistan.
   ``A cease-fire in the presence of invading forces is meaningless
in Afghanistan,'' said Abdul Rahim, spokesman of the powerful
Jamiat-i-Islami guerrilla group.
   Pakistan's official news agency quoted the country's U.S.
ambassador, S. Shah Nawaz, as saying Gorbachev's speech Wednesday to
the United Nations was ``statesman-like'' but that his Afghan
proposals were unrealistic.
   The agency also reported that an Afghan pilot landed his MiG-21
jet in Pakistan on Thursday and surrendered. A government official
speaking on condition of anonymity said the plane landed at Miram
Shah in North West Frontier Province, 10 miles from the Afghan
border.
   The agency identified the pilot only as Capt. Asadullah.
   Tass, the official Soviet news agency, reported a clash between
the Afghan army and the insurgents, saying at least 86 guerrillas
were killed and 56 wounded. The report, which could not be
confirmed, did not give a date for the clash.
   There was no immediate response from Foreign Minister Sahabzada
Yaqub Khan on Gorbachev's proposals. However, a ministry official
who spoke on condition of anonymity said an end of hostilities was
``not practical'' because Afghan guerrillas were determined to fight
to victory.
   Gorbachev proposed a Jan. 1 cease-fire between Soviet-backed
Afghan forces and the U.S.- and Pakistan-supported guerrillas, with
both sides holding their ground.
   He called for a mutual arms freeze on the same date and for an
international conference to restore peace in the war-torn country.
   Moscow agreed in a U.N.-mediated accord last spring to withdraw
its troops from Afghanistan by Feb. 15, 1989. Half of the troops
pulled out under the schedule, but the Soviet Union suspended the
withdrawal last month but pledged to remove its troops on schedule.
   Soviet forces intervened in December 1979 and stayed on to help
defend the Marxist government against an increasingly ferocious
insurgency.
   ``There is no demarcated line of battle where the cease-fire
could be enforced,'' Nawaz was quoted as saying by the agency
Associated Press of Pakistan.
   He said Gorbachev's proposal for an international conference on
Afghanistan was not new, and was ``aimed at giving legitimacy to the
Kabul regime,'' which seized power in 1978.
   The guerrillas have gained large parts of eastern Afghanistan
since the Soviet pullout began May 15. Communist government forces
still control most major cities while insurgents rule the
countryside.
   Rahim, whose party leader Burhanuddin Rabbani currently chairs
the seven-party guerrilla alliance, said the guerrillas would keep
fighting until all Soviets have left the country and the Kabul
government falls.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
