<DOCNO> AP881208-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 1423EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan Bjt   12-08 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan, Bjt,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan's News Conference First in 6 Months, Likely His Last</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be topped with 8 p.m. EST news conference</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan prepared Thursday for his
first news conference in six months, likely his last formal meeting
with reporters as the clock runs out on his eight-year presidency.
   One day after his fifth meeting with Kremlin leader Mikhail
Gorbachev, Reagan was ready to deal with questions about the
evolution of his views about the Soviet Union, from calling it an
``evil empire'' to signing the first superpower treaty ever to
abolish an entire class of nuclear weapons.
   Reagan said his summit with Gorbachev in New York, along with
President-elect Bush, had been a ``very useful meeting for both
sides.'' The Soviet leader capped his trip by announcing a
unilateral cutback of 500,000 Soviet forces, a reduction of about 10
percent.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater did not rule out the
possibility of another news conference before Reagan leaves office
on Jan. 20. However, first lady Nancy Reagan told reporters earlier
this week, ``Be nice. It's his last one.''
   Reagan, before going to the Oval Office on Thursday, placed a
farewell telephone call to Gorbachev, who abruptly cut short a New
York visit and flew home because of a devastating earthquake that
killed thousands of people in Soviet Armenia.
   As related by Fitzwater, the president expressed Americans'
``deep personal sorrow '' and asked Gorbachev if there is any way
the United States could help. Gorbachev later publicly expressed
gratitude for the U.S. offer.
   Reagan told Gorbachev he fully understood ``that you have no
choice but to return to your own country and be with your people
following the early morning earthquake. I know I speak for all
Americans when I express my deep personal sorrow at the loss of life
caused by this earthquake.''
   ``We understand that it was a very serious one,'' the president
said, according to Fitzwater. ``If there is any way we can be of
assistance, either bilaterally or through the international
community, please let me know.''
   ``I want to tell you again how much both the vice president and I
enjoyed meeting with you yesterday,'' Reagan said. ``I think it was
a very useful meeting for both sides. I wish you much success in the
future and a safe journey home. Godspeed.''
   Mrs. Reagan also spoke with Raisa Gorbachev on the telephone,
expressing sorrow over the quake and saying that she and the
president hope to see the Gorbachevs again either in California or
the Soviet Union.
   The Reagans will move to Los Angeles when he leaves office.
   In nearly eight years in office, the president has had relatively
few news conferences _ only 45 full-scale meetings with the press,
four of them this year.
   Two of this year's news conferences were held out of the country,
one at the conclusion of his summit with Gorbachev in Moscow on June
1 and another 20 days later in Toronto at the end of the
seven-nation economic summit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881208-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 1440EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Summit-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0495 12-08 0865</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0495,860</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 11 grafs new with Bush call to Gorbachev; picks up 4th
graf pvs, As the.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush called Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev today to express sympathy for the
``horrible disaster situation'' caused by a devastating earthquake
in Armenia.
   ``Nobody really knows the numbers of people killed, but I had an
opportunity to tell him how strongly Barbara and I feel in human
terms about that loss,'' Bush said.
   Gorbachev, who held a summit luncheon in New York Wednesday with
Bush and President Reagan, cut short his visit to return home to the
Soviet Union to deal with the earthquake in Armenia.
   Bush said he told Gorbachev that he enjoyed the meeting, but the
two only discussed ``broad themes'' in their ``very pleasant''
15-minute conversation conducted with the use of simultaneous
translators.
   While Bush says he wants to build on the Reagan administration's
recent record of improved relations, he has refused to make any
foreign policy initiatives until he has his national security team
in place.
   Bush said the two discussed ``the toll in human life in this
horrible disaster situation.'' Though Bush didn't specifically offer
U.S. aid to quake victims, he said the ``American people will want
to hold out their hands to those families who lost loved ones.''
   Reagan telephoned Gorbachev to offer American assistance.
   Gorbachev remarked that the death toll was so high in part
because the quake occurred in the middle of the day when people were
out and around, according to Bush. There have been preliminary
estimates reported of up to 50,000 people killed in the quake.
   Bush, whose voice is hoarse because he has a cold, made his
comments on the earthquake at a picture-taking session to unveil the
inaugural license plate. He attached the red, white and blue plate
with the number 1 on it to his black limousine.
   The personalized, commemorative license plates cost $50, and can
be used on public roads until March 31, 1989, if registered through
The American Bicentennial Presidential Inaugural.
   In his address to the U.N. General Assembly Wednesday, Gorbachev
said that he looked forward to working with Bush _ as he had with
Reagan.
   As the three leaders parted in New York, Bush told Gorbachev, ``I
enjoyed the meeting. Hope to see you soon.''
   During a brief exchange with reporters on his return to Andrews
Air Force Base in suburban Maryland, Bush, suffering from a cold,
said he told Gorbachev that ``we hadn't put together our full team''
and that ``I'm in the process of doing that.''
   Bush named longtime associate James A. Baker as secretary of
state the day after his election Nov. 8, and he has named former
Ford administration national security adviser Brent Scowcroft to
serve in the same capacity. But the vice president hasn't yet
settled on a secretary of defense, although there have been
persistent reports the job will go to former Sen. John Tower,
R-Texas.
   Bush said that in his talks with Gorbachev, ``I also made clear
that we needed some time, and he understood that. He didn't have any
problem with that at all.''
   Bush called the luncheon ``a good, productive meeting,'' and said
he saw several positive aspects to Gorbachev's speech to the General
Assembly. The Soviet leader, among other things, announced that he
was reducing Soviet ground force troop strength by 500,000 from the
current level of roughly 5.6 million.
   ``There was no pressing on substantive details'' at the session,
Bush said, although he said weighty issues were discussed.
   ``And now I've got to go back and get our full national security
team together and set our strategy and establish our priorities,''
he said. ``As I said in the campaign, have our secretary of state
touch base with the allies, make contact and have a lot of contact
with (Soviet Foreign) minister (Eduard A.) Shevardnadze. ...
   ``And then, down the line, at an appropriate line, a meeting
between me and General Secretary Gorbachev can be discussed,'' the
vice president said. ``But there's no pressure on that. The main
thing is to formulate our plan to move them forward, so we have
progress. That's what I want.''
   Secretary of State George Shultz, briefing reporters on the
roughly two-hour luncheon summit, said there were ``general
references to the desirability of having the level of contact _ the
intensity of contacts at all levels _ maintained.''
   But Shultz said ``there's no immediate plan for any meeting that
came out of the session, as I saw it ... although obviously there
will be one at some appropriate moment.''
   Bush said in advance of the summit that he was going there in his
role as vice president, and that he would mostly listen.
   This stance produced one of the lighter moments during a
picture-taking session as Reagan, Gorbachev and Bush and several
aides sat at a long rectangular table.
   When Bush was asked to give his reaction to Gorbachev's troop
cutback announcement, he replied that ``I support what the president
says.''
   As people broke up in laughter, Gorbachev said, through his
interpreter, ``One of the best answers of the year.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
