<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon-Swiss     12-08 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Swiss,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Red Cross Suspends its Services in South Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Swiss Red Cross has shut down
operations in south Lebanon and ordered the rest of its foreign
workers out of the area after one of them was abducted last month, a
spokeswoman said Thursday.
   The two offices in the coastal towns of Sidon and Tyre, which
extended humanitarian services to the entire region, have been
closed, said Francoise Derron, a spokeswoman for the International
Committee of the Red Cross.
   ``All our expatriates in south Lebanon have been pulled out,''
the she said. ``But we continue to work normally in the rest of the
country,'' she added.
   Since the Nov. 17 abduction of Swiss worker Peter Winkler, Red
Cross spokesmen in Beirut and Geneva have insisted the all-Swiss
organization does not plan to halt all its operations in Lebanon.
   The Swiss government has urged its nationals not to travel to
Lebanon.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be identified under standing
regulations, said Lebanese drivers evacuated nine of the Red Cross'
12 vehicles in Tyre on Tuesday.
   Three Swiss nationals working in Tyre, Christophe Girod, 38,
Laurent Shophere, 35, and Philip de Korod, 36, drove the remaining
three Peugeot cars to Beirut on Wednesday, said the spokesman.
   The police spokesman said a Swiss Red Cross employee left Lebanon
on Wednesday aboard a Zurich-bound Middle East Airlines jet. He
refused to identify the employee.
   That brought to nine the number of Swiss personnel who have left
Lebanon since the Winkler's abduction. Twenty-two other delegates
remain.
   After the abduction, the Red Cross said it was closing down only
in Sidon, where Winkler was abducted.
   Winkler, 32, said in a handwritten note released by his captors
Friday that he was abducted because he was a Swiss citizen. The Red
Cross confirmed the authenticity of the handwriting.
   No group has claimed responsibility for his abduction.
   Fourteen other foreigners, including nine Americans, are missing
and believed kidnapped in Lebanon. The longest-held hostage is
American Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The
Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
