<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Paraguay-Rights     12-08 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Paraguay-Rights,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Urges End to Detention of Opposition Leaders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department urged the government of
Paraguay on Thursday to halt the ``authoritarian and arbitrary''
practice of detaining opposition leaders and to permit a peaceful
march on Saturday to commemorate the 40th anniversary of the
Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
   Phyllis Oakley, a department spokeswoman, said more than a dozen
opposition leaders have been jailed without formal charges in
Asuncion, the capital of the South American nation.
   ``The Department of State deplores the Paraguayan government's
authoritarian and arbitrary practice of detaining opposition
figures, usually for several days at a time without arrest warrants
or formal charges,'' Mrs. Oakley said.
   ``We understand that the Paraguayan government is apparently
trying to prevent a march planned for Saturday by a number of
political, human rights and labor organizations to commemorate the
40th anniversary of the signing of the Universal Declaration of
Human Rights,'' she said.
   ``We hope that both the government of Paraguay and the marchers
will honor the peaceful nature of the occasion,'' she said. ``A
peaceful march in Asuncion on Saturday would be a fitting
contribution by the Paraguayan people and the government to the
international celebration commemorating the U.N. human rights
declaration.''
   The declaration declares that all human beings are entitled to
basic rights. Article 9 of the declaration states: ``No one shall be
subjected to arbitary arrest, detention or exile.''
