<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Veterans-Hammerschmidt     12-08 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Veterans-Hammerschmidt,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Colleagues Tout Arkansas Lawmaker to Head Vets Department</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top members of the House Veterans Affairs
Committee have joined a lobbying effort aimed at winning the
appointment of Rep. John Paul Hammerschmidt, R-Ark., as the first
veterans affairs secretary.
   Reps. Sonny Montgomery, D-Miss., the committee chairman, and
Gerald B.H. Solomon, R-N.Y., supported the appointment in a letter
to President-elect Bush. The letter was also signed by
representatives of seven veterans organizations.
   The Department of Veterans Affairs was created last month when
President Reagan signed legislation elevating the Veterans
Administration to the 14th Cabinet agency. The new department will
come into being next March.
   Hammerschmidt, 66, was easily elected last month to his 12th
House term. He was a pilot in World War II and owned a lumber
company before entering Congress. He is a member of the Veterans
Affairs Committee.
   Hammerschmidt did not return telephone calls Thursday seeking
comment on the letter, but he has said he is not actively seeking
the job.
   The letter to Bush said Hammerschmidt ``is held in high esteem by
all members of Congress, both House and Senate, and he is highly
regarded by the national veterans service organization. He is a man
of the highest character and integrity and would serve America and
its veterans well.''
   Hammerschmidt is one of three men who have been prominently
mentioned to head the new department. The others are Everett
Alvarez, a former Vietnam prisoner of war who worked on Bush's staff
and has been deputy VA administrator; and former Sen. Jeremiah
Denton, an Alabama Republican who was also a Vietnam POW.
</TEXT>
