<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Gorbachev-Irwin     12-08 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev-Irwin,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Astronaut Gives Soviet Leader Moon Flag</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last gift presented to Mikhail S. Gorbachev
during his visit to New York was a Soviet flag that went to the moon
in 1971 with the Apollo 15 mission.
   The flag was handed to Gorbachev by former astronaut James B.
Irwin just before the Soviet leader climbed the steps to his plane
at Kennedy Airport on Thursday.
   Irwin said he and his crewmates in the July 1971 moon flight,
David R. Scott and Alfred Worden, had signed the flag, which was one
of a number of flags carried by the moonwalkers.
   ``We carried it for you and for the people of the Soviet Union.
And we visited the moon in peace for all mankind,'' Irwin told
Gorbachev.
   He also gave Gorbachev a coffee-table book, ``The Home Planet,''
which contains photos from space and text by American and Soviet
space travelers.
   ``I think you'll find it inspirational reading material for your
flight back home,'' Irwin said.
   Gorbachev shook his hand and tapped him on the shoulder.
   Irwin said he had tried to give the flag to Gorbachev during a
two-week visit last month to the Soviet Union but it could not be
arranged. He was invited, however, to present the flag at a
reception Gorbachev planned for Thursday night. When Gorbachev cut
his visit short, the Soviets let Irwin make the presentation at the
airport.
   Irwin left the space program in 1972 and founded the High Flight
Foundation of Colorado Springs, Colo., a nonprofit Christian group.
He also has mounted expeditions in search of artifacts that would
confirm biblical lore.
   He has made a half-dozen trips to Turkey in search of Noah's Ark
and earlier this year went to Egypt to try to find the chariots
swallowed when the parted waters of the Red Sea closed on the
soldiers of the pharaoh who were pursuing Moses and the Jewish
people.
</TEXT>
