<2ND_LINE>AM-Weight Bias,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Overweight Firefighter Offered Settlement In Weight Bias Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATH, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former firefighter who says he was fired
because he was too chubby has been offered a settlement in his
discrimination complaint.
   Supervisor Richard Brook would not divulge the settlement
approved this week by the board of Bath, in central Michigan, but he
said Clarence Edward Christy would not be reinstated and that the
amount was less than had been requested.
   ``I guess the board feels we did the best we could for the
community under the circumstances that were there,'' Brooks said.
   Christy claimed he was discriminated against when he was fired in
1985 on the grounds that his weight kept him from doing the job
properly. The 5-foot-6-inch former smoker weighed 260 pounds when he
was fired.
   Christy was seeking reinstatement, back pay totaling $4,000 and
$6,000 for emotional and mental stress.
   Although Christy had not seen the settlement, he said Wednesday
that he would accept it.
   ``They've been messing around with this for three years and
there's been a lot of heat toward me from the township. I think I
just better take what they offer and let the matter die down,'' he
said.
   Officials in the township 15 miles northeast of Lansing contended
that physical exams showed Christy's breathing ability was below
normal, raising the possibility that other firefighters might have
to carry him out of a fire.
   The state Civil Rights Department charged the township in July
with unlawfully discriminating against Christy due to weight and
handicap.
</TEXT>
