<DOCNO> AP881208-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 1518EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Gorbachev-NewYork Bjt   12-08 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev-New York, Bjt,0664</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Early Departure Elicits Sympathy, Sorrow and Savings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sudden departure of Mikhail S. Gorbachev,
eliminating a full day of Big Apple sightseeing, produced sympathy,
sorrow and savings _ and some sighs of relief Thursday from those
who missed out on the historic visit.
   ``The mood is very sad,'' said Elaine Fink, principal of the
Manhattan elementary school that had been scheduled to play host to
Raisa Gorbachev in the afternoon. ``The children are very down that
a terrible tragedy killed thousands of people, and that Mrs.
Gorbachev will not get to see a school in the United States.''
   Her feelings were reflected at each planned stop by the
Gorbachevs on their final day in Manhattan. The Soviet leader left
New York a day early to rush home because of a massive earthquake
that devastated Soviet Armenia.
   In addition to the trip to P.S. 6 on the Upper East Side,
Gorbachev and his wife had planned a short walk through Central Park
before a visit to the Metropolitan Museum of Art and had scheduled a
morning stop at the Javits Convention Center for a Soviet trade show.
   ``I guess I'll just go do some Christmas shopping and go home,''
said John Chrystal, chief operating officer of Bankers Trust Co. of
Des Moines, Iowa, who had been invited by Gorbachev to attend the
trade event.
   Chrystal's uncle, Roswell Garst, owned the Iowa farm that Nikita
Khrushchev visited in one of the high points of his 1959 American
tour, and the Iowan had come to New York solely to see Gorbachev.
   He was not alone in feeling let down.
   ``Yes, we are disappointed, but who can argue with an
earthquake?'' asked a resigned Parks Commissioner Henry Stern, who
was to be Gorbachev's host in the park. ``We hope he can come back
another time.''
   At the Metropolitan Museum of Art _ the final tourist attraction
on the Gorbachev tour _ the mood was somber, said John Ross, head of
public relations.
   ``I think the only thing we can say is to express sympathy for
the earthquake victims,'' said Ross. ``The leader of the Soviet
Union is not someone who comes by every day, and if he comes back,
we would be pleased if he came to see the museum.''
   While Stern said little was done to prepare Central Park for the
visit (``We cleaned up a bit, but we do that every day''), Ms. Fink
said the students and teachers at P.S. 6 had a crash course on the
Soviet Union to prepare for Mrs. Gorbachev.
   ``The kids were ready, the excitement was at an incredible
level,'' she said. ``Now it's a tremendous sadness over the tragedy.
... It's a lesson in disappointment for us all.''
   While there was sympathy and sorrow, there were also savings for
the New York City police. Officials were busy computing how much of
the $1 million in overtime set aside for the trip would be saved by
eliminating a day's work.
   The sighs of relief came from the Transportation Department,
which battled the ``Gorbylock'' that paralyzed midtown Manhattan on
Wednesday evening as Gorbachev's motorcade wound through town.
   ``We're doing better now,'' said Joe O'Brien, a spokesman for the
department. ``To a large degree, we don't have to worry about
traffic today. There's just the regular traffic to worry about.''
   Also left in the lurch by the change in plans was billionaire
developer Donald Trump, whose invitation to have Gorbachev visit the
opulent Trump Tower was rejected. Trump was among a group scheduled
for dinner Thursday night at the Soviet Mission; instead, the
closest he came to the Soviet leader was a glimpse of a Gorby
look-alike on Tuesday.
   Trump, unsurprisingly, was undaunted.
   ``Donald said he's going to see him anyway next year in the
Soviet Union,'' said Trump spokesman Dan Klores.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
