<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 1519EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Summit-Reagan 3rdLd-Writethru a0648 12-08 0890</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Reagan, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0648,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Offers US Help in Quake's Aftermath</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Reagan on quake aid, human rights, subbing 6
grafs for 7th graf pvs, At the</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan expressed Americans' ``deep
personal sorrow '' at the devastating earthquake in the Soviet Union
today and asked Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev to let him
know if the United States could help.
   In a telephone call to Gorbachev from the second-floor living
quarters of the White House, Reagan also told the Soviet leader he
believes their meeting Wednesday on Governors Island in New York was
``very useful ... for both sides.''
   Nancy Reagan also spoke with Raisa Gorbachev on the telephone,
expressing sorrow over the quake and saying that she and the
president hope to see the Gorbachevs again either in California or
the Soviet Union.
   In an airport statement before his departure from New York,
Gorbachev said he also received a telephone call from
President-elect George Bush offering condolences and help.
   Speaking through an interpreter, the Soviet president said, ``On
behalf of the myself, of the Soviet people and on behalf of those to
whom those feelings were expressed by the president and the vice
president let me extend our deep gratitude and our profound
appreciation.
   ``The president and the vice president conveyed their willingness
to extend assistance and apppropriate help in this situation and I
would like to thank them and I would like to thank the American
people for those feelings and for their readiness to give assistance
in this difficult hour.''
   Reagan, when asked later whether he expected the United States to
provide assistance, replied, ``They haven't asked for any yet.''
   He spoke briefly with reporters after signing a proclamation
observing the 40th anniversary of the United Nations Declaration of
Human Rights.
   In remarks at the signing ceremony the president noted that human
rights was among the subjects he discussed with Gorbachev on
Governors Island. He said the United States is ``not yet satisfied''
with the Soviet human rights record but also said progress was being
made.
   ``We want to see the release of all political prisoners,'' Reagan
said. ``Dozens remain in prison.''
   He said the United States also seeks changes in Soviet laws used
against dissidents and that he was told during his meeting with
Gorbachev that ``some progress is being made'' in this regard.
   At the White House, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
relayed the Reagans' end of the earlier conversation with the
Gorbachevs.
   ``I received word last night of your early departure from New
York and wanted to tell you how sorry I am that you must leave,''
the president told Gorbachev.
   ``I fully understand, however, that you have no choice but to
return to your own country and be with your people following the
early morning earthquake. I know I speak for all Americans when I
express my deep personal sorrow at the loss of life caused by this
earthquake.''
   ``We understand that it was a very serious one,'' Reagan said.
``If there is any way we can be of assistance, either bilaterally or
through the international community, please let me know.''
   ``I want to tell you again how much both the vice president and I
enjoyed meeting with you yesterday,'' he said. ``I think it was a
very useful meeting for both sides. I wish you much success in the
future and a safe journey home. Godspeed.''
   Gorbachev was cutting short his trip and returning to the Soviet
Union today because of worsening reports of damage and deaths from a
massavie earthquake in the Transcaucasus that devastated areas of
northern Soviet Armenia and eastern Turkey on Wednesday.
   Speaking to the conservative scholars of the American Enterprise
Institute upon returning from Wednesday's meeting on Governors
Island in New York Harbor, Reagan said he found his talks with the
Soviet president ``positive and encouraging.''
   Still, he said, ``fundamental differences between our countries
remain in many areas.''
   Referring specifically to Gorbachev's pledge to reduce Soviet
conventional forces, he said the United States must exercise caution
as East-West dealings enter ``this critical junction.''
   ``We came to Washington together in 1981, both as anti-communists
and as unapologetic defenders of a strong and vibrant America,''
Reagan told members of the conservative think tank.
   ``I am proud to say I am still an anti-communist,'' he said to
applause. ``And I continue to be dedicated to the idea that we must
trumpet our beliefs and advance our American ideals to all the
peoples of the world until the towers of the tyrants crumble to
dust.''
   ``Freedom works, and freedom is on the march, and yes, I am an
optimist, and yes, I believe I have every reason to be.''
   At the end of their private session, before they joined aides for
lunch, Reagan gave Gorbachev an inscribed photograph of the two of
them walking in the woods during their first summit meeting in
Geneva in 1985.
   ``We have walked a long way together to clear a path for peace,''
he wrote over his signature.
   The two men met again in Reykjavik, Iceland, in 1986, in
Washington in 1987 and in Moscow in 1988. Wednesday's session, with
President-elect George Bush along in his role as vice president, was
arranged to coincide with Gorbachev's visit to the United Nations.
</TEXT>
