<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagans-Health, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0695,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagans to Get Annual Post-Cancer Surgery Checkups</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds last 5 grafs with background</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan and his wife, Nancy, will go
to Bethesda Naval Hospital on Friday for their annual post-cancer
surgery checkups, the White House announced today.
   ``Both the president and the first lady have remained completely
asymtomatic, with no clinical suggestion of recurrence,''
presidential physician John Hutton said in a statement issued by the
White House.
   The president, who underwent surgery for colon cancer in July
1985, will undergo a colonoscopy, a chest X-ray, a CAT scan, a
cardiac stress test and a pulmonary function evaluation, Hutton said.
   Mrs. Reagan, who had her left breast removed in October 1987,
will have her second mammogram since undergoing the modified radical
mastectomy, Hutton said.
   Following the exams, the couple will go to Camp David, Md., for
the weekend, the statement said.
   In Reagan's initial surgery, doctors removed a two-inch cancerous
polyp and nearly two feet of his colon as well as the surrounding
tissue.
   Since 1985 and up until last January, Reagan had a colonoscopy
every six months to check for any recurrence of cancer. Each time,
doctors found polyps _ or small, fleshy growths _ and removed them.
They were all found to be non-cancerous.
   No polyps were found in his last such examination in January of
this year. Reagan did not have such a checkup this summer.
   The colonoscopy is an examination of the large intestine with a
long, flexible instrument that uses fiber optic technology to allow
doctors to see inside the bowel.
   The CAT scan is a computerized three-dimensional X-ray of the
internal organs.
</TEXT>
