<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FirstAmendment     12-08 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-First Amendment,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Decries Reagan's Record on First Amendment Issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A liberal organization that concerns itself
with the First Amendment said Thursday that the Reagan
administration turned a cold shoulder ``to the fundamental liberties
guaranteed by our founders.''
   It said President-elect Bush is showing more sensitivity toward
constitutional guarantees of freedom of spech and freedom of the
press, and separation of church and state.
   People for the American Way, which describes itself as ``the
non-partisan constitutional liberties organization,'' issued a
report that it says shows 241 cases in which the administration
trampled on freedom of speech and freedom of the press, separation
of church and state and other rights guaranteed by the Constitition.
   The group cited a $45,000 federal grant to Pat Robertson's
Christian Broadcasting Network; a White House aide's saying that
anyone directly around Ronald Reagan ``gets saved or gets out''; a
40 percent increase in classified information; the news blackout on
the U.S. invasion of Grenada; and the attempt to induce reporters
for two newspapers not to report various intelligence activities.
   ``The incidents we've cited in our report demonstrate ... a slow,
steady, quiet usurpation of First Amendment rights,'' Arthur J.
Kropp, president of the organization, told a news conference.
   ``It isn't as if Ed Meese and Ronald Reagan sat down (eight years
ago) and said to themselves `How can we sink free speech today?'''
Kropp said.
   ``But the Reagan administration did come to town with a very
specific political agenda ... and, most important, a seeming
willingness to do whatever it takes to effect their agenda. If that
meant violating the principles or rights set forth in the First
Amendment, then, apparently, they were willing to do just that.''
   John H. Buchanan, chairman of the group, said that while Bush is
part of that record, he is encouraged that the president-to-be is
``selecting people of reason, not radicalism, for his
administration.''
   Buchanan said Bush ``should not repay whatever debts he owes the
far right by selecting ideologues for the middle- and lower-level
positions in his administration,'' and that he should choose as
judges ``men and women of unquestioned legal ability and competence.
   ``I am heartened that, after eight years of an administraion that
avoided, manipulated and even attacked the news media, the
president-elect is being accessible and open to the press,''
Buchanan said.
   ``We urge the new president to adopt more reasonable policies on
the classification of government documents; to eliminate the
reclassification of documents that are currently available to the
people; and to prohibit restrictions on unclassified information.''
</TEXT>
