<1ST_LINE>r w AM-JournalismContest     12-08 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Journalism Contest,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Journalists to Compete for College Scholarship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty high-school journalists will gather next
year to cover a simulated news event in Washington as the final
deadline challenge in a national writing competition offering a full
college scholarship as the prize, the sponsor announced Thursday.
   Each of the 27,000 high schools in the country will be invited to
participate in the first stage of the contest, established by Pilot
Pen of Trumbull, Conn.
   ``We have developed the Pilot Pen scholarship to inspire and
reward high school students interested in a career in journalism,''
said Ronald Shaw, president of the writing instrument company.
   The final stage of the contest will come in October 1989, when
one winner from each state will come to Washington to spend the day
coverning ``events'' at the National Press Club related to
international developments. Included in the events will be news
conferences, news releases and other briefings.
   The students will be interrupted as they write their news stories
with more updates and news conferences. At 5 p.m., the stories will
be due. Judging will take place that evening, with the winner
announced at a banquet.
   In addition to the four-year college scholarship for the winner,
the four runners-up will receive $2,500 each.
   Each high school in the nation will be notified by mail in
January how to apply to enter the contest. The first 5,000 schools
to respond will be included in the contest.
   Students will complete a writing assignment in April at their
school. Each school's winner will be forwarded to the contest
administrator, who will decide on a winner for each state to attend
the national competition.
</TEXT>
