<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MilitaryWomenMemorial     12-08 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Military Women Memorial,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contest Opened To Design Women's Military Memorial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sponsors of a proposed memorial honoring women
who served in the nation's armed forces said Thursday they would
hold a contest to select the best design.
   The competition, which begins immediately, is similar to the
contest that produced the design for the Vietnam Veterans Memorial,
one of the most visited sites in Washington.
   The memorial has been authorized by Congress and is to be built
on a three acre site at the entrance to Arlington National Cemetery,
just across the Potomac River from Washington.
   Sally Byington, spokeswoman for the Women in Military Service for
America Memorial Foundation Inc., said the design must incorporate
an existing neo-classical monument, the Hemicycle, at the cemetery's
entrance. The memorial is to include a visitors center, an
auditorium and a computer registry of women who served in the U.S.
military, she said.
   The group, which already has received federal approval for use of
the site, estimates the memorial will cost $15 million to $20
million. It is seeking contributions for the project.
   The competition is open to any American citizen 18 years or
older. The winner will be decided by a panel of judges headed by
Jaan Holt, director of the Washington-Alexandria Center of Virginia
Tech's college of architecture and urban studies.
   Holt said the judges will select three designs and award their
designers $10,000 to further develop their plans. One winning design
will be selected and become the basis for the memorial.
   Those wishing to enter should send a $50 non-refundable
registration fee to Carla I. Corbin, Women in Military Service
Memorial, Department 560, Washington, D.C. 20042-0560. Checks or
money orders should be made payable to WIMSAF Design Competition.
Byington said the deadline for entries is May 15, 1989.
</TEXT>
