<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 1728EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Inauguration     12-08 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Inauguration,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inaugural Committee Borrowing $20 Million-Plus for Festivities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Presidential Inaugural Committee said
Thursday it is halfway to its goal of borrowing more than $20
million to pay for a bicentennial inauguration week crammed with
free public events as well as fancy galas.
   ``We've made every effort to be cost-conscious ... and make sure
what we do is self-sustaining,'' said executive director Stephen
Studdert.
   He and other officials said all the money, in the form of
interest-free loans of at least $100,000, will be repaid when
proceeds from ball tickets and other sales become available.
   Committee co-chairman Bobby Holt said the budget for inauguration
week activities will be between $20 million and $25 million and
added, ``We need the money up front.'' Finance director Walter Ganzi
Jr. said ``we're about halfway there'' when asked about fund-raising
progress.
   The schedule of events released Thursday includes six free ones,
including a pageant, a parade, a children's inaugural festival, a
prayer service at the Washington Cathedral and a White House welcome
on Jan. 21, George Bush's first day in his new residence.
   Other events range from the $30-a-ticket Young American Ball to
the $1,500-a-person Inaugural Dinner. Tickets to the eight other
official balls the night of Jan. 20 will go for $175 apiece.
   Holt and the other co-chairman, Penne Percy Korth, said the Jan.
18-22 inaugural schedule, with its special events for children and
the public, reflects the Bush family's wishes that the celebration
be as open and inclusive as possible.
   ``We're going to try to have more free events than at any
inauguration before,'' Holt said. He said there is a contingency
plan for bad weather included in the budget.
   A bipartisan congressional committee is in charge of the
inaugural ceremony and a luncheon that follows it, events expected
to cost the taxpayers about $2.5 million.
   The Presidential Inaugural Committee sponsors and pays for all of
the other activities, and will reimburse the government for
personnel used for anything other than their usual functions during
inaugural events.
   Holt said there are about 300 staff people on his committee and
5,000 volunteers helping them. By the inauguration, he said, the
staff could be as large as 700 and some 30,000 volunteers will be on
board.
</TEXT>
