<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Quake-USAid 1stLd-Writethru a0692 12-08 0741</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quake-US Aid, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0692,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Red Cross, Administration, Ethnic Groups Offer Aid</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New 3rd and 5th grafs to UPDATE with additional Reagan
comment; SUBS 18th graf, Donations can..., to give additional
Armenian organizations.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Quake Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan offered help Thursday while
the American Red Cross sent money and launched a fund-raising effort
to aid residents of Armenia, the Soviet republic struck by an
earthquake that killed tens of thousands of people.
   ``If there is any way we can be of assistance, either bilaterally
or through the international community, please let me know,'' Reagan
told Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Gorbachev, before leaving New York, expressed gratitude to the
American people for ``their readiness to give assistance in this
difficult hour.''
   ``We are prepared to assist directly or through international
organizations, and if the Soviets request assistance we'll work with
them to determine the kind of assistance most needed and in any way
that we might be helpful,'' State Department spokeswoman Phyllis
Oakley said.
   A few hours after making his telephone call to Gorbachev, Reagan
was asked whether he expected the United States to be providing
assistance for earthquake relief to the Soviets. ``They haven't
asked for any yet,'' he said.
   ``This is an incredible disaster, one that would tax the
resources of any society, including the Soviet Red Cross,'' said
Richard F. Schubert, president of the American Red Cross in
Washington.
   The International Red Cross in Geneva, Switzerland, is working
with Soviet officials to determine what supplies are most needed and
which countries can fill those needs, he said.
   The United States will be providing antibiotics and other
medicines, according to the American Red Cross, which has already
begin efforts to obtain supplies of those medicines.
   Schubert said Soviet officials have ``airlifted in about 15 tons
of blankets, tents, first aid kits. Armenia at this point in the
year is pretty cold, and so there is a critical need for emergency
shelter.''
   The Red Cross has activated a toll-free number for people to call
to offer assistance, reported spokeswoman Terry Gautier. The number
is 1-800-453-9000.
   Already the large Armenian community in Los Angeles has offered
its assistance, Schubert said.
   And Ms. Gautier said Armenian churches across the country have
begun efforts to help.
   ``All our energies, everybody in the Armenian community, is
dedicated, because of compassion, because of understanding, because
of concern for human needs to providing relief for those victims of
this natural tragedy,'' said George Keverian, speaker of the
Massachusetts House and a leader in the Armenian community in that
state.
   What other items the United States may be asked to supply, in
addition to medications, will be determined after Soviet authorities
have had time to assess the damage and determine their needs, Red
Cross officials said.
   ``We have agreed that just as soon as an assessment is made, we
will begin to supply their needs as we have the ability to do,''
Schubert said.
   In the meantime a $50,000 gift has been sent to allow local
officials to purchase needed goods, Ms. Gautier said.
   Schubert said Soviet officials are welcoming assistance, a
strikingly different situation from in 1986 when offers of help in
the wake of the Chernobyl nuclear accident were largely ignored.
   Red Cross officials said it is accepting donations, which should
be earmarked ``Soviet-Armenian Earthquake.''
   Donations can be mailed to local chapters or to the American Red
Cross, International Disaster Relief, P.O. Box 37243, Washington,
D.C., 20013. The Armenian Relief Society of North Armerica Inc.,
based in Watertown, Mass., is collecting donations of money and
clothing, medical supplies, tents, sleeping bags and clothing. The
Armenian Assembly of America, based in Washington, says an Armenian
Earthquake Relief Fund has been established, with monetary donations
to be sent to St. Vartan Armenian Cathedral in New York and the
Armenian General Benevolent Union in Saddle Brook, N.J.
   One thing not requested by the Soviets was blood. ``All blood
needs for the earthquake victims will be collected from internal
Soviet Union resources,'' Schubert said.
   The temblor that devastated much of Armenia leveled cities and
killed thousands of people. It caused Gorbachev to cut short a trip
that would have taken him on to Cuba and Britain.
   The 16,000-resident town of Spitak, near the epicenter of the
tremor, was reportedly wiped out. The government newspaper Izvestia
said just one of the town's eight schools still stood.
</TEXT>
