<1ST_LINE>r w AM-EPALawsuits     12-08 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-EPA Lawsuits,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Claims Record Lawsuits Last Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency said
Thursday it's bringing more lawsuits than ever.
   In the 1988 fiscal year that ended Sept. 30, the agency turned
over 372 civil cases to the Justice Department, compared with the
previous record of 342 civil cases in the 1986 fiscal year. There
were 59 criminal cases in fiscal 1988, compared with 41 in both 1986
and 1987.
   However, the agency's administrative orders totaled 3,085, down
slightly from 3,194 in the previous year. EPA said it tried not to
issue a large number of orders when new school asbestos regulations
took effect at the start of the year, but rather tried to make sure
school boards understood them.
   The agency said state environmental agencies referred 904 civil
cases to their attorneys general and issued 9,363 administrative
orders. Both figures were said to be records, but the old records
were not given.
   EPA said it now had 17 firms on a blacklist of companies barred
from contracts because of certain air or water pollution violations,
compared with three in January 1986, and had 450 judicial consent
decrees in effect, compared with 200 in 1984.
   Though the Justice Department is free to reject cases sent to it
by EPA, EPA spokeswoman Robin Woods said the department accepts
virtually all of them.
</TEXT>
