<DOCNO> AP881208-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 1623EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GanderCrash     12-08 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gander Crash,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Board Divided on Report Ice on Wing Caused Newfoundland Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canada's Aviation Safety Board blamed iced wings
for the air disaster that killed 248 U.S. troops three years ago,
but a minority report concluded a fire possibly ignited by
explosions caused the crash.
   The review of the Dec. 12, 1985, crash at Gander, Newfoundland,
published Thursday, has been plagued by disputes and limited
evidence.
   Four of eight board members signed the minority report concluding
the cause was ``an in-flight fire that may have resulted from
detonations of undetermined origin.''
   Board Chairman Kenneth J. Thorneycroft broke a tie to vote with
the four other members for a report that found no evidence of
sabotage, a fire or explosion before impact of the Arrow Air charter
DC-8.
   Often-public board disputes during the inquiry have led
opposition politicians to call for a judicial review of the accident.
   Canada's worst air disaster killed all 256 aboard _ eight
American crew members and the soldiers heading home for Christmas to
Fort Campbell, Ky., from peacekeeping duties in the Middle East.
   The board report concludes the aircraft stalled at low altitude
100 seconds after takeoff and recovery was impossible.
   ``The most probable cause of the stall was determined to be ice
contamination on the leading edge and upper surface of the wing,''
it says. ``Other possible factors such as a loss of thrust from the
No. 4 engine and inappropriate takeoff reference speeds may have
compounded the effects of the contamination.''
   The minority opinion found ``ice contamination was not a factor
in this accident.'' While it did not conclude terrorism was
involved, it said security arrangements at the flight's point of
origin in Cairo, Egypt, ``were not ideal.''
   ``Fire broke out on board while the aircraft was in flight,
possibly due to a detonation in a cargo compartment,'' says the
minority opinion.
   The board's report concludes, ``the balance of evidence did not
support the occurrence of a preimpact fire or explosion either
accidental or as a result of sabotage.''
   Thorneycroft defended what he told reporters was a ``fair and
balanced'' report produced despite many difficultiesm including:
   _ Witnesses caught only a glimpse of the plane as it crashed in
limited early morning light.
   _ The voice recorder did not capture any conversations or sounds
in the cockpit and the recorder provided only limited information.
   _ There was little left of the plane.
   The board recommended a national safety campaign to ensure all
pilots are aware of the potential consequences of taking off with
even minor amounts of ice on the wing.
   Other suggestions were:
   _ Requiring all Canadian users of DC-8 aircraft to establish
detailed procedures for detecting ice before takeoff.
   _ A Transportation Department review of procedures to check
cockpit voice recorders and possibly similar action in the United
States.
   _ A change in U.S. federal aviation regulations on flight periods
and rest provisions for crews.
   The board's report found the crew's December flight schedule was
heavy enough to have high potential to produce fatigue. But the
minority opinion said ``members of the cockpit crew performed their
duties without apparent fault.''
   Thorneycroft, a former deputy commander of the North American
Aerospace Defense Command in Colorado Springs, Colo., said there was
``no pressure at all'' from American authorities to discount
sabotage as a possible cause.
   DC-8 manufacturer McDonnell Douglas took part in the
investigation as well as Pratt and Whitney, which made the engine,
the U.S. Army and the U.S. National Transportation Safety Board.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881208-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 1823EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Rights     12-08 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Rights,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Celebrates 40th Anniversary of Human Rights Declaration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations honored anti-apartheid
activists Nelson and Winnie Mandela on Thursday as it commemorated
the 40th anniversary of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
   ``The record of human rights in our age is besmirched by summary
executions and arbitrary arrests, `disappearances' and torture, the
killing of defenseless demonstrators, and detentions for reasons of
belief or conviction,'' Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
told the General Assembly.
   The Universal Declaration of Human Rights, adopted without
dissent by the General Assembly Dec. 10, 1948, is the basic U.N.
document under which members pledge to safeguard life and liberty
and abolish torture and slavery.
   All 159 U.N. member states profess their love for human rights.
But over 80 countries still have prisoners of conscience and torture
is practiced in more than 60 nations, according to Franca Sciuto,
chairwoman of the executive committee of Amnesty International.
   Ms. Sciuto and other officials of the London-based organization
which won the 1977 Nobel Peace Prize presented Perez de Cuellar with
a petition signed by more than 3 million people calling on all
governments ``to ratify the world's human rights treaties, to bring
their own laws and practices into line with them and to act to
protect human rights worldwide.''
   Only 43 governments, for example, have signed a protocol allowing
individuals to petition the United Nations with complaints of human
rights abuses, said Ms. Sciuto.
   Awards were presented to six human rights activists.
   Mandela, leader of the African National Congress guerrilla
organization fighting the South African government, has been serving
a life sentence since 1962 on a conviction of plotting sabotage
against the state.
   Winnie Mandela, his wife since 1958, has become a public symbol
of resistance to apartheid. She has been imprisoned several times,
sometimes in solitary confinement.
   The Mandelas received their awards in absentia, as did Murlidar
Devidas Amte of India, a lawyer and aide to Mohandas K. Gandhi who
went on to fight for rights for lepers, the blind, the ill and
disadvantaged children.
   A posthumous award went to Leonidas Proano of Ecuador, the Roman
Catholic bishop of Rio Bamba who worked to protect the rights of his
country's native people. He died in August.
   John Humphrey of Canada received his award in person. Humphrey
was director of the U.N. Division of Human Rights from 1946-66 and
helped prepare the first draft of the Universal Declaration of Human
Rights. He is founding president of Canada's section of Amnesty
International.
   Also present to accept the brass and wood plaque engraved with a
flame symbolizing human rights, was Adam Lopatka of Poland. Since
1983 he has chaired the U.N. commission drafting a Convention on the
Rights of the Child, which the world body plans to adopt next year.
He is now first president of Poland's Supreme Court.
   President Franklin D. Roosevelt and British Prime Minister
Winston Churchill insisted on recognition of human rights in the
U.N. Charter when World War II discussions laid the groundwork for
the United Nations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
