<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Visas     12-08 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Visas,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>France Drops Visa Requirement For Seven Countries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France has decided to drop its visa requirement for
visitors from seven European countries that are not members of the
European Economic Community, the Foreign Ministry announced Thursday.
   Government officials have said recently they may also rescind the
visa requirement for U.S. passport holders, but there has been no
announcement.
   Citizens of Austria, Sweden, Norway, Finland, Iceland, Cyprus and
Malta will again be welcome in France without visas, as they were
before emergency measures put in place in September 1986 during a
wave of terrorist bombings in Paris.
   ``This decision was taken in recognition of the reinforcement of
cooperation in Europe on security and the fight against terrorism
and drug trafficking,'' said a Foreign Ministry spokesman.
   France began demanding visas from people carrying passports of
all nations except the 11 other members of the EEC, plus
Switzerland. The decision was contested by officials from other
European countries, especially Sweden and Austria.
   Other countries affected by the 1986 decision include Algeria,
Morocco, Tunisia and other African nations with traditionally close
ties to France. French officials have said they wanted to avoid any
appearance of a racial criterion, with predominantly white countries
being the only ones exempt from the visa requirement.
</TEXT>
