<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ThrowawayBeef     12-08 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Throwaway Beef,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Beef Over Grading Apparently Dooms Roasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If federal bureacrats have their way, 3{ tons of
edible roasted beef will be destroyed because it might be too chewy
to live up to the ``choice'' grade given by a meat processor.
   There are no provisions in U.S. Department of Agriculture rules
to let the meat go to a charity, even in the spirit of the holiday
season, according to government attorneys.
   In a civil lawsuit filed Tuesday under the name ``U.S. v. 7,007
Pounds of Cooked Roast Beef,'' the USDA seeks the forfeiture of the
504 roasts, prepared at Max Bauer Meat Packers, a wholesale
distributor supplying other South Florida distributors and markets.
   Inspectors examined the 15- to 18-pound roasts last summer and
found them marked USDA Choice when they actually should have been
left ungraded, the lawsuit says. Choice beef sells for 50 to 70
cents more per pound than ungraded beef.
   ``It's just a little more chewy,'' Larry Dyal, a Fort Lauderdale
meat distributor, said Wednesday. ``You'd have to be a gourmet to
tell the difference.''
   But the USDA inspectors found the difference in lab tests and
ordered the beef, some of which had been distributed, detained in
freezers.
   ``The only thing we know is that someone came in, inspected it
and put `Don't touch' on it,'' said Bill Quirch, with E & G Trading
Co. in Miami.
   Mike Pasano, attorney for Max Bauer, dismissed the federal beef
as ``a bunch of government nonsense.''
   ``We've asked for it back, politely,'' he said.
   Pasano said what his company would do with the meat if it was
returned depends on the beef's condition. ``Quite honestly, we have
concerns, and we've expressed them to the federal government, that
they've held onto it for such a long time.''
   He'll make a formal request for the beef in future filings with
U.S. District Judge Leonore Nesbitt.
   If the USDA prevails, there are no provisions in the law to let
the meat be donated to feed the hungry, said U.S. Attorney Dexter
Lehtenin.
   ``Some official will go out to the dump and watch it be buried,''
said Emil Thrasher, a deputy USDA director.
   But the prospect of destroying good food astounds Harry
Somerville, one of the Brothers of the Good Shepherd who operate
Camillus House, a downtown Miami mission for the homeless.
   ``Holy Hannah, yes!'' he said when asked if his organization
could put the beef to use, were it ever offered. ``You could feed a
lot of hungry people with that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
