<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lennon-Prague     12-08 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lennon-Prague,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds Mark Anniversary of Lennon Death in Prague</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 1,000 people gathered in
chilly, damp weather Thursday to mark the death of John Lennon, an
annual ritual once banned by the authorities but held this year
under official auspices.
   The peaceful gathering sponsored by the Communist Youth
Organization came two days before an independent rally on human
rights that will also take place with official permission.
   Thursday's gathering by the so-called ``Lennon Wall,'' which once
was covered with slogans extolling the slain Beatle and peace,
marked the founding of a new independent group, the John Lennon
Peace Club.
   A statement read to the crowd and applauded demanded the release
of four independent peace activists jailed in October.
   It declared the four honorary members of the new group, along
with Lennon himself and Jan Palach, the Czechoslovak student who
burned himself to death on Wenceslas Square in 1969 to protest the
1968 Soviet-led invasion of Czechoslovakia.
   Rock singer Vladimir Merta, one of several poets and singers to
perform for the crowd, welcomed news that some of the 80,000 Soviet
troops stationed in Czechoslovakia since 1968 will be withdrawn in
the next two years.
   A small police presence watched the crowd, but made no apparent
attempt to break up the gathering even when hundreds of people
lingered behind to sing Lennon songs and burn candles for peace.
   Saturday's rally, called by the Charter 77 human rights movement
and four other groups, was originally schedculed for Prague's
Wenceslas Square.
   Authorities banned the gathering there but for the first time in
nearly two decades agreed to let it go ahead at another site further
from the city center.
   Charter 77 activist Jan Urban said Thursday the independent
groups would have people on Wenceslas Square to redirect them to the
alternative site.
</TEXT>
