<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 1642EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Gorbachev'sDecision Bjt   12-08 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev's Decision, Bjt,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev's Early Return Avoids Pointed Contrasts</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev's hurried return to his
earthquake-stricken nation avoids the specter of pictures of the
Soviet president on a lighthearted sightseeing tour while thousands
of his countrymen lay dead.
   ``I have to be there,'' he said Thursday as he left the United
States to fly directly home, bypassing scheduled visits to Cuba and
Great Britain.
   Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze underlined the point,
saying, ``Despite the fact that all necessary measures are being
taken to overcome the extremely grave consequences of this disaster,
Mikhail Gorbachev believes that when the people are suffering, he
has to be there.''
   Gorbachev himself said the earthquake ``was extremely severe and
had extremely grave consequences, devastation and great loss of
life. So I urgently have to return.''
   Although such decisions are reached in secrecy, it was apparent
the remainder of Gorbachev's highly publicized New York stay,
including the opening of a Soviet trade show, a stroll through
Central Park and a museum tour, would have contrasted sharply with
the stark pictures of disaster at home.
   And Gorbachev, whose nationally televised chats with constituents
have set a new, modern style for a Soviet leader, could hardly
ignore the situation. To do so would have been reminiscent of
President Reagan's hesitation in 1983 to return to Washington from a
California vacation after the Soviet shootdown of a Korean Air Lines
passenger jet.
   Gorbachev's decision also demonstrated his ability to respond
quickly to events in a country he often complains is bound by its
own bureaucracy.
   Barely four hours before the president's decision was announced
at a surprise late-night news conference Wednesday, chief Foreign
Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov had dismissed any suggestion
Gorbachev might cut short his stay in New York.
   Although the spokesman acknowledged the situation in the
earthquake-ravaged Caucasus was serious and ``a small village has
practically disappeared from the face of the Earth,'' he told
reporters that relief efforts were being handled routinely by
mobilization of the armed forces and physicians. He noted it was a
natural disaster and gave no indication any presidential action was
necessary or even under consideration.
   Gorbachev at the time was attending a star-studded reception at
the United Nations at the end of a day marked by his announcement of
a dramatic, military force reduction. Earlier in the day, he had bid
a friendly farewell to Reagan, his four-time summit partner, urged
President-elect Bush not to delay the strengthening of U.S.-Soviet
ties and toured New York for the first time.
   A short time later, as other members of his entourage were going
to bed, Gorbachev instructed his foreign minister to round up
reporters for the announcement of his imminent return home.
   The Caucasus calamity took on an added dimension because it
struck a region that for months has been the scene of ethnic strife
between Armenians and Azerbaijanis and more recent nationalist
demonstrations in Shevardnadze's native Georgia.
   The unrest, which has exploded into fatal rioting in several
Azerbaijani cities and sparked massive demonstrations and general
strikes in Armenia, has prompted authorities to deploy troops and
tanks in the streets in some areas. Tens of thousands of refugees
have fled their homes in fear.
   But despite the military presence, Gorbachev's policy of
glasnost, or openness, also has been evident in the region.
Authorities have tolerated dissent and criticism they once would
have crushed with brutal force.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
