<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ReaganRelics     12-08 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan Relics,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Sending Relics of Presidency to Eureka College</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PE1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EUREKA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A piece of the Oval Office floor, a
commemorative jellybean jar, scores of autographed books and other
White House memorabilia are piling up at Ronald Reagan's alma mater,
tiny Eureka College.
   About a dozen boxes of assorted trinkets have come in the past
few weeks, and school officials have been notified to expect many
more presidential odds and ends before Reagan leaves office in
January.
   ``It's interesting and exciting and may be just the tip of the
iceberg,'' said Lynn Beer, director of college relations. ``He knows
we have a display of his memorabilia so he sends anything he feels
is suitable.''
   For now, the boxes are piling up in a small storeroom adjacent to
the office of George Hearne, school president. Most are wrapped in
old Washington Post newspapers and appear in no particular order.
   Hearne said Reagan had notified the school about three months ago
that the materials were available, and Hearne said the school was
interested.
   A small library could be created from the books Reagan has
shipped. Personal messages of good will abound in autographed books
by authors such as Richard Nixon, Jimmy Carter, Ted Kennedy, Henry
Kissinger, Ferdinand Marcos and even Sam Donaldson.
   One box contains small gifts Reagan regularly gave White House
visitors, including a commemorative jar of jelly beans and a
paperweight made from a piece of cork taken from the Oval Office
floor. A note says the cork supported six presidents from 1934-69
before the floor was replaced.
   Other items included an inaugural book set and a belt buckle with
a rodeo cowboy that proclaims ``the buckaroo stops here.''
   Two of the more unusual items were a pair of cowboy boots
emblazoned with the presidential seal and a Plexiglas-enclosed
Wheaties box bearing a photo of the 1988 Super Bowl champion
Washington Redskins.
   Eureka College officials welcome all contributions from the
school's most famous graduate.
   ``President Reagan has a deep affection for Eureka College and
remains consistently in touch with us,'' said Hearne. ``He started
sending us memorabilia as governor of California, including
souvenirs from his career as a movie star as well as his tenure as
governor.''
   The school is planning a permanent display in a new campus center
not far from the Reagan Physical Education Center, and near Reagan
Street.
   Officials plan to invite Reagan to campus in 1992 for grand
opening ceremonies of the campus center and to celebrate his 60th
class reunion. He has been a regular visitor on campus, including
two visits during his presidency.
   Reagan graduated from the private, liberal arts college in 1932
with a degree in social science and economics.
</TEXT>
