<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Quake-USArmenians     12-08 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quake-US Armenians,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Armenians Struggle to Find News of Devastating Earthquake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Armenian communities throughout the United States scrambled to
collect donations and medical supplies Thursday to rush to Soviet
Armenia in the wake of an earthquake believed to have killed tens of
thousands.
   International phone lines were flooded by Armenian immigrants
trying to reach relatives and obtain news beyond the sketchy reports
that up to 50,000 people have died and whole villages were wiped out
by Wednesday's temblor.
   ``We can't reach Armenia,'' said Suren Bursalyan, editor of the
Armenian biweekly Paros in California. ``All of the phone lines are
shot. Our only information is American television. It's really hard.
We would like to know the extent of damage.''
   In Southern California, home to the nation's largest Armenian
community, the Western Prelacy of the Armenian Apostolic Church
announced that eight days of mourning would begin Friday, and that
area Armenian churches would hold special requiem services Friday
and Sunday.
   At least 250,000 Armenians, the largest concentration outside of
Soviet Armenia, live in Southern California, mostly in Hollywood and
Glendale.
   Archbishop Datev Sarkissian said he, Like Bursalyan, had been
unable to uncover any information to pass on to parishioners.
   ``Yesterday I was trying to get in touch with Armenia and the
operator was overrun by the telephone calls,'' he said.
   Local Armenians are ``in a state of shock. They are in a state of
grief and great pain,'' the archbishop said. ``But a great relief
operation is being organized by the community to help rebuild the
cities.''
   California Gov. George Deukmejian, himself of Armenian descent,
said, ``As Californians, we are all too familiar with devastating
earthquakes. Although the details are still incomplete, we can all
envision the effect of a reported 6.9 Richter scale earthquake
centered near cities with populations approaching 1 million each.''
   A quake of 6.9 is capable of causing widespread damage. In
addition to Armenia, the temblor caused extensive damage in Georgia
and the Azerbaijan republic in the northern Caucasus.
   A Soviet exchange student attending college in Maine did get
through to her parents. She said that the quake, while devastating,
had spared her family, which lives in the Georgian capital of
Tbilisi.
   ``I talked with my parents and I asked, `Is it true or not?' and
they answered that it was a very hard earthquake,'' said Tamara
Sulukhyia, an exchange student at Bowdoin College.
   Hundreds of people telephoned the offices of Asbarez, a
Glendale-based newspaper catering to the Armenian community. ``The
phones started ringing at 6 o'clock this morning,'' said Abraham
Boghigian, the paper's editor. ``Right now for us here in Los
Angeles, (obtaining information) is very hard.''
   Boghigian said that an affiliated paper in Montreal had
established phone contact with government offices in Armenia, and
the sketchy information obtained (only listing deaths in the ``tens
of thousands'') would be passed along to readers.
   Meanwhile, Archbishop Torkom Manoogian, Primate of the Eastern
Diocese of the Armenian Church in America, said at a news conference
at New York's Armenian cathedral that ``the devastation is heavier
than we can imagine.''
   ``The immediate needs are shelter, medical supplies, clothing and
blood,'' he said.
   Manoogian and a delegation of Armenian prelates from around the
world held the news conference after a one-hour meeting with Soviet
officials at the USSR mission to the United Nations.
   ``We are asking all people of good will and compassion ... to
assist financially,'' Manoogian said.
   The church is coordinating with other relief agencies such as the
Red Cross and the World Council of Churches to ship doctors, nurses
and supplies to Armenia, but he had no immediate details to announce.
   The Boston University School of Medicine set up a phone bank to
coordinate relief locally, along with the Zoryan Institute and other
Armenian organizations. There are some 95,000 Armenians in
Massachusetts.
</TEXT>
