<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 1841EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Aspin-Tower     12-08 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aspin-Tower,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aspin: Bush Errs by Not Ending Speculation on Tower Appointment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush may be making ``his first
serious misstep'' by prolonging speculation over whether former Sen.
John Tower will be appointed defense secretary, Rep. Les Aspin said
Thursday.
   Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services Committee,
was referring to reports circulating since Bush's election last
month that Tower, former chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee, will be named to head the Pentagon.
   There have been reports that Bush and his advisers want to name
as many as five top Pentagon officials at one time, including Tower.
   ``If Tower is named defense secretary, he will come into office
in a weakened condition,'' said Aspin, speaking in La Jolla, Calif.,
at a board meeting of Science Applications International. A copy of
his speech was released in Washington.
   ``For one thing, with all that twisting in the wind, questions
will be raised about how much confidence the president has in him,''
Aspin said.
   ``If what we read is correct, Tower won't have much of a hand in
picking the other top figures in the Department of Defense,'' Aspin
said. ``That means that when he goes into a huddle with his
officials, their playbooks will be full of end runs.''
   ``In sum, if nominated, Tower could well enter office already
wounded,'' he said.
   If Bush goes ahead with the Tower appointment, he will need to
back the former Texas senator strongly, Aspin said.
   ``To recover with John Tower, Mr. Bush is going to have to make
it clear his secretary has his emphatic support,'' Aspin said.
``Perceptions on this point are everything.''
   One of the biggest problems of the Bush administration will be
dealing with the budget, particularly Pentagon projections that
large defense spending increases will be needed to pay for programs
begun earlier, Aspin said.
   ``In spite of campaign promises to the contrary, my guess is that
zero real growth _ only enough to offset inflation _ is the very
best that the Pentagon can hope for,'' he said.
   Tower also has been the subject of rumors about his personal
life, particuarly following his 1987 divorce from his second wife,
Lilla.
   The divorce was granted after a legal battle in which she alleged
Tower had committed ``marital misconduct'' during their 10-year
marriage. Tower's deposition responding to the charges was sealed by
agreement of both parties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
