<1ST_LINE>u w AM-AIDS-Mice     12-08 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Mice,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tight Security May Have Killed Crucial Mice, Researcher Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Institutes of Health researcher
who lost all but three of 130 mice that had been genetically altered
to carry AIDS said Thursday he hopes their apparently accidental
death will lead to less drastic guidelines for isolating such
animals.
   ``Maybe that's the silver lining,'' said Dr. Malcolm Martin, a
top virologist at the national Institute of Allergy and Infectious
Diseases.
   Citing the growing importance of animals in AIDS research, Martin
said the accident underscores the difficulty researchers have with
acquiring the large numbers of animals they need while at the same
time operating under strict guidelines to keep the animals from
escaping.
   Martin, who headed the team that developed the unique strain of
mice at the laboratory in nearby Bethesda, Md., said he got a
telephone call at 5 a.m. Monday telling him most of the mice were
dead.
   By Wednesday, Martin and his assistant concluded that it was a
freakishly simple accident: power was turned off in the building for
several hours over the weekend for maintance work.
   As a result, the 30-foot-long glass and steel tube where the mice
were housed under tight security lost ventilation and overheated.
   The accident came just a few days before Martin and his team were
preparing to begin preliminary experiments on the mice to see how
various drugs might act in their bodies.
   It will take at least four or five months to replenish the mice
herd from the three survivors, Martin said.
   The elaborate structure designed to keep the AIDS mice, in
Martin's view, amounted to overkill and made it almost impossible to
breed the large numbers of mice that would be needed for really
significant research.
   ``A good number to keep in mind is that it took 500,000 ...
monkees to test and certify the Salk and Sabin polio vaccines,''
said Martin. ``If we're going to be serious about AIDS research,
we've got to turn more and more to animals systems.''
   He said fellow researchers in California are running into the
same difficulties with breeding the necessary numbers of mice that
have been altered to duplicate the human immune system, a new
development with tremendous implications for AIDS research since
such mice could be injected with the AIDS virus and then subjected
to various drug and vaccine testing.
   While Martin's mice carry the genetic marker for the AIDS virus
in each cell of their bodies, they do not have human immune system
characteristics like the California mice and thus, in some ways, are
not as pure an ``animal model'' for AIDS research as the California
mice.
</TEXT>
