<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DC-Drugs     12-08 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DC-Drugs,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal, Local Authorities Seek to Stem Drug Murders in Capital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A task force of local and federal officials is
being created to help solve the record number of drug-related
killings in the nation's capital, U.S. Attorney Jay B. Stephens said
Thursday.
   ``The escalating violence level in this city, attributable in
large part to narcotics trafficking, threatens the safety of the
people,'' Stephens said.
   So far in 1988, 337 people have been slain in Washington, far
surpassing the previous one-year record of 287 killings set in 1969.
Police estimate 60 percent of the killings are drug-related, and
blame the influx of crack, a potent, highly addictive cocaine
derivative, for many of those slayings.
   Stephens said he has assigned five senior prosecutors and five
investigators to probe drug-related killings. Prosecutors will
decide on a case-by-case basis whether to seek the death penalty,
which Congress approved in the recently enacted drug bill, he added.
   The District of Columbia criminal code does not have a death
penalty, and all cases involving deaths and drugs would be
prosecuted in federal court. Stephens' office is responsible for
prosecuting all serious criminal cases in this city of 625,000.
   District Police Chief Maurice T. Turner hailed the agreement as
``long overdue. The joint effort of homicide detectives and
senior-level prosecutors will help close cases.''
   Stephens said he decided on the plan after investigators told him
that a variety of organized crime groups are making inroads in the
city's drug trade.
   Turner, who previously has said that many of the slayings result
from young entrepreneurs fighting for turf, acknowledged the
importance of the gangs, and added that individual dealers may be
starting to work together.
   The police chief also renewed his support for Operation Clean
Sweep, an anti-drug program that has produced more than 44,000
arrests since it began in 1986. But at the same time, he said drug
treatment, prevention and education programs are needed to solve the
city's drug epidemic.
</TEXT>
