<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev-Command Center,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev's Departure Brings Smiles at Security Post</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal and local trouble-shooters at a special
command center exchanged smiles and handshakes Thursday as Mikhail
S. Gorbachev's plane made its way out of U.S. airspace.
   ``Wheels up,'' shouted Deputy Police Chief Tosano Simonetti as he
watched the departure, which came one day earlier than expected, on
a huge video screen.
   The Soviet leader cut short his visit to return home because of a
severe earthquake in Soviet Armenia.
   Despite the tremendous security concerns involved in Gorbachev's
visit, Simonetti said ``we've been through so many of these things
that it's kind of old hat.
   ``Now that he's gone, we'll start planning something else.''
   More than 20 agencies, including the Secret Service, the FBI, the
Federal Aviation Administration and city emergency, traffic and fire
departments, were represented at the command center at Police
Headquarters.
   Simonetti thanked all the participants for their cooperation.
``We couldn't do it alone,'' he said.
   The last flurry of calls that came into the command center
involved reports of rubbernecking and cars stopped along the
motorcade's route to the airport.
   Simonetti said motorists apparently slowed down or pulled over to
the side to catch one last glimpse of Gorbachev before he returned
to the Soviet Union. Extra highway patrols were dispatched to keep
traffic moving.
   ``I'm glad it's all over,'' said Jack Mulligan of the FAA. ``We
were all scared that something was going to happen.''
   Simonetti said there no major security problems came up during
the abbreviated visit, even though Gorbachev caught police by
surprise when he made two unscheduled stops in midtown Manhattan on
Wednesday as he toured the city in his motorcade.
   He said there had been 15 bomb threats, all unfounded, called
into the 911 emergency number during Gorbechev's stay. Three were
believed to be directed toward the Soviet leader _ two of them at
the United Nations and one at a location that was not disclosed.
   Another concern of the command center, traffic, went as smoothly
as could be expected, according to Gregory Perrin of the city
Department of Transportation.
   He said there were periods of gridlock when streets were closed
for the motorcade, but residents appeared to take it in stride.
   ``They did very well. In terms of traffic, New Yorkers proved to
be road scholars,'' Perrin said.
</TEXT>
