<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Iran     12-08 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Iran,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>50 Iranians Join International Hunger Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The color returned to Farzaneh Shojaei's wan face
Thursday as she explained why she joined Iranian students in a
12-day international hunger strike to protest recent executions in
their homeland.
   ``As I'm Iranian, I really think it's the least I can do to show
my support for the families of those killed,'' she said on the west
London sidewalk where 50 Iranians have taken turns camping since
their hunger strikes began Nov. 30. Two have been hospitalized for
short periods, she said.
   ``My brother or sister or relatives could be one of those killed.
Fortunately they have not, but they could,'' says Ms. Shojaei, 32,
who has lost 13 pounds since she began the fast that ends Saturday.
   The Union of Moslem Iranian Student Societies said it organized
the hunger strike in 17 countries to protest mass executions in the
country since the Aug. 20 cease-fire in the eight-year war with Iraq.
   The opposition Mujahedeen Khalq, the largest Iranian opposition
group seeking to topple the government of Ayatollah Khomeini,
claimed last Friday that 12,000 people have been executed in Iran
since August.
   The group, which is supported by the student union societies,
says the political prisoners, their families, and other supporters
of the Mujahedeen, or People's Holy Warriers, have been killed.
   Two London policeman stood near the low enclosure where the
Iranians, who are drinking only tea and water, sat on benches,
wrapped in blankets to ward off the chill.
   Some stomped their feet or paced as patriotic songs and poems set
to music played quietly from a cassette player. Some have relatives
who were killed, while others are simply sympathizers.
   The U.N. General Assembly's Third Committee, which deals with
human rights matters, approved a resolution Nov. 30 criticizing Iran
for alleged human rights abuses, including the execution of
political prisoners. An earlier United Nations human rights report
on Iran also criticized the Tehran government for the executions.
   ``It's a true massacre which is going on,'' Hussein Abedini, a
spokesman for the hunger strikers, said in an interview.
   Along with the London group, hunger strikes were said to be under
way in New York, Paris, Amsterdam, Bonn, Rome, Geneva, Brussels,
Athens, Copenhagen, Stockholm, Madrid, New Delhi, Ottawa, Sydney,
Vienna and Oslo.
   An estimated 1,000 people worldwide are fasting until Saturday,
the United Nations International Human Rights Day, organizers said.
In London, they will hold a rally and march to mark the end.
   Abedini said the protesters were also fasting to demand Iran's
ouster from the United Nations and its replacement with the
Mujahedeen, and to ask the General Assembly to condemn the current
regime.
   Ms. Shojaei was certain their efforts will help in the long run.
   ``It's got to do something, ... maybe not in the short time,''
she said. ``But it's going to make the situation worse for
(Khomeini) inside and outside Iran.''
</TEXT>
