<2ND_LINE>AM-Orbison Album,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Singer's Posthumous Album Due In 1989</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new album by rock 'n' roll pioneer Roy
Orbison, who died Tuesday, is due out in early 1989.
   ``Mystery Girl'' on Virgin Records will feature guest stars
including U2, Elvis Costello, Albert Hammond, George Harrison, Steve
Cropper, Tom Petty, Billy Burnette and others.
   Funeral services for Orbison, who died of a heart attack at age
52, remained incomplete Thursday. Arrangements were delayed because
his wife was in Germany visiting relatives at the time of his death.
   The singer had been scheduled to fly to Europe next week to film
a second music video as a member of the Traveling Wilburys, a group
that also includes Harrison, Petty, Bob Dylan and Jeff Lynne. Their
album ``The Traveling Wilburys'' is No. 8 on the charts.
   Meanwhile, the singer's band members said this was Orbison's
first full week off in more than six months.
   ``His last words to the band were, `I'll see you in January.
We'll get back together, learn some new songs and have a ball,'''
said Michael Joyce, bass player.
   ``He'd really been working hard,'' Joyce said. ``The crowds have
been getting wilder and wilder. The crowd in Boston (last week) was
shouting `Roy, Roy, Roy' before he went on stage. There was a real
momentum building.''
   David Briggs, a record producer and song publisher, recently
finished producing two songs with Orbison for the forthcoming album.
   ``He was in great spirits, and he seemed to be in relatively good
health,'' Briggs said. ``We worked seven days a week, and he held up
well after midnight. In fact, he held up a lot better than I did.''
   In three decades of performing, Orbison was best known for his
hits ``Oh, Pretty Woman,'' ``Only the Lonely'' and ``Cryin'.''
   Orbison spent Tuesday afternoon and evening playing with
remote-control model airplanes, his hobby. He suffered the heart
attack at his mother's house and died later at a hospital.
   Orbison, who had open heart surgery in 1978, is survived by his
wife Barbara; sons Wesley, 23, Roy Jr., 18, and Alexander, 12; his
mother and a brother.
