<HEAD>Peace Corps Seeking Trainers for Philippine Teachers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Peace Corps is looking for a few good
teachers to volunteer for a one-year stint in the Philippines.
   Loret Ruppe, the Peace Corps director, said Thursday the teachers
are needed to serve as assistants and advisers to Filipino teacher
trainers.
   While Peace Corps volunteers normally serve two years, the
teachers are being recruited as associate volunteers to serve in
village, provincial, municipal and national schools on the big
island of Luzon.
   The Peace Corps wants to recruit 10 primary and 20 secondary
teachers for the Philippine positions. In addition, at the secondary
level, seven math teachers, seven science teachers and six English
teachers are needed to assist in teacher training on Luzon.
   The teachers recruited would take part in a pre-departure
orientation in San Francisco next April 5 and arrive in the
Philippines on April 9 for eight weeks of training.
   ``We are particularly looking for qualified substitute and
retired teachers to spend a year overseas,'' Ruppe said.
   Those interested can call the teacher education program at
1-800-424-8580, Extension 293, or contact local Peace Corps
recruiting offices.
