<HEAD>U.S. Welcomes Move of Mandela</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration on Thursday welcomed
the move of South African nationalist leader Nelson Mandela to a
house on a prison farm.
   ``We welcome this move as a further step toward freedom for Mr.
Mandela,'' State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley told
reporters.
   ``Nonetheless,'' she said, ``until Mr. Mandela and others
detained and imprisoned from the black community are released
unconditionally from detention, prospects for the peaceful
resolution of South Africa's problems will remain dim.''
   The United States is one of a number countries which frequently
call for Mandela's release from prison.
   On Wednesday the South African government transferred Mandela,
70, from a clinic, where he was recovering from tuberculosis, to a
house at a prison farm northeast of Cape Town.
   Mandela, a leader of the African National Congress, has been
imprisoned since 1962. He was sentenced in 1964 to life in prison on
charges of sabotage and conspiracy to overthrow the government by
violence.
   The South African Prisons Service said Thursday that Mandela is
not confined to the house and has free use of a wide range of
facilities.
