<DOCNO> AP881208-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 1739EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Bukharin     12-08 0719</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bukharin,0740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bukharin Policies, Foreshadowing Gorbachev's, Clashed with Stalin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nikolai Bukharin, the Russian revolutionary leader
whose liberal economic blueprints foreshadowed the Mikhail S.
Gorbachev era, probably lost his mind after realizing Josef Stalin
was determined to destroy him, his widow says.
   In what is billed as her first interview with Western television,
Anna Larina Bukharin has described to the British Broadcasting Corp.
the last heart-rending days before her husband was arrested, tried
on trumped-up charges and shot in 1938.
   ``He wrote Stalin endless letters proving his innocence. ... By
then he was psychologically unbalanced, and I can't say he was by
this time a person in full command of his mind,'' Mrs. Bukharin said
in the interview aired Wednesday night.
   ``So much had landed on him, and on top of it all (he had) a
young wife and son who was virtually newborn, only 10 months old,
and all of this together had a terrible effect on him,'' she said.
   Bukharin was a close friend and adviser of Vladimir Lenin,
founder of the Soviet state who died in 1924. Stalin became dictator
in 1929, and Bukharin clashed with him over economic policy.
   Stalin believed in forced collectivization to modernize Russia, a
feudal country where 80 percent of the population was agrarian.
Bukharin favored a mix of small-scale capitalism and nationalization
of major industries.
   In 1938, Bukharin and other senior officials were arrested on
charges of spying, sabotage and plotting to murder Lenin. They were
convicted at a show trial and executed the same year. Buharin was 49
at the time.
   Fifty years later, on July 9, Bukharin and 15 other veteran
Bolsheviks were posthumously rehabilitated and readmitted to the
Communist Party in a move indicative of Gorbachev's drive to
exorcize the Stalinist ghost from Soviet society.
   Mrs. Bukharin, who is in her mid-70s, and other Soviets recently
interviewed for the film of Bukharin painted a picture of a colossus
of Russian communism and a man of great charm and popular appeal who
at first could not believe Stalin was bent on having him disgraced
and murdered.
   Dmitri Volkogonov of the Institute of Military History in Moscow
told how Bukharin at one point telephoned Stalin, and, addressing
him by his nickname, said: ``Koba, do you really believe that I am
an enemy?''
   Stalin replied: ``Nikolai, calm down, we'll get to the bottom of
things and everything will be OK.''
   During the interview in her Moscow apartment, Mrs. Bukharin was
asked why Bukharin returned to Moscow from Paris in 1936 when he was
in such danger.
   Speaking in Russian through an interpreter, she replied:
``Nikolai didn't have an inkling, no.'
   Stalin's agricultural policies caused catastrophic famine, which
deeply affected Bukharin, said his widow.
   ``He used to go to the Crimea and see the starving children with
swollen tummies. He used to come to my father and relate it all. And
he even burst out crying. It was a terrible episode. He was most
upset by it,'' she said.
   ``But he wept in silence, in his own home,'' said Professor Alec
Nove, a Glasgow University Soviet expert, noting in the film that
there is no record of Bukharin ever making his misgivings public.
   ``He was a loyal member of the party, and Stalin played on
that,'' Nove said. With World War II looming, ``was this the time to
rock the boat? I think Bukharin kept silent not only because the
secret police were hovering on the doorstep, but because he felt it
his duty to keep silent.''
   Bukharin died at age 49, and the location of his grave is
unknown. Mrs. Bukharin spent more than 20 years in exile and prison
camps, separated from her son.
   Professor Anthony Kemp-Welch of Nottingham University said ``the
past closely relates to the present'' in the similarities between
Bukharin and Gorbachev, the Soviet president and party leader.
   ``Gorbachev is the first intellectual in the Politburo since
Bukharin,'' he told the BBC.
   ``That is why the similarities between Bukharin and Gorbachev are
most compelling,'' he said.
   ``They have the same supporters. Both appeal quite directly to an
educated intelligentsia and to the population at large that wishes
to be active in advancing itself economically, whether peasants or
workers, in order to assist the economy as a whole.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
