<1ST_LINE>r w AM-GreenhouseHurricanes     12-08 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greenhouse Hurricanes,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Insurance Rep Says Greenhouse Effect Spurs Stronger Hurricanes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stronger hurricanes spawned by global warming
could cost U.S. insurance companies an extra half-billion dollars a
year in wind and hail damage claims, an insurance company executive
said Thursday in a discussion of the greenhouse effect.
   ``You don't have to wait until 2030 or 2040 to get a sizable
increase'' in claims, Donald Friedman of the Travelers Insurance Co.
said at a conference sponsored by the Climate Institute.
   Most hurricane damage is from ocean water surging inland, driven
by the storm, and Friedman presented no estimate of claims increase
there.
   The institute is a nonprofit group trying to call attention to
the warming of the earth predicted by many scientists to result from
the accumulation of heat-trapping gases in the atmosphere
   Friedman, a meteorologist and head of natural hazards research at
Travelers, studied 117 years' worth of records that estimated the
tracks of the 240 hurricanes known to have come ashore in that
period.
   Using a computer model that assumed the peak surface temperature
of the Caribbean would rise at 0.9 degrees Fahrenheit per decade,
Friedman concluded that the hurricane season could begin almost two
weeks earlier and last almost two weeks longer.
   Almost all hurricanes happen between June and November, mostly in
August and September. The higher ocean temperature would make
August-September storms stronger, he said.
   Damage depends on the strength of a storm and where it hits, he
said, but on the average ``you could get about a 30 percent greater
damage production potential,'' he said.
   ``What now happens on June 1 could happen on May 20 ... and what
happens in the middle of November could happen in early December,''
he said.
   Currently, property insurers pay about $1 billion to $1.5 billion
a year in wind and hail damage claims from hurricanes, with large
variations from year to year. This figure could increase by 30
percent, he said.
   In a conference session on Tuesday, James Hansen, a climatologist
with the National Aeronautics and Space Administration, quoted one
estimate that peak hurricane wind speeds could reach 220-225 mph,
compared with about 175 mph at present.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
