<2ND_LINE>AM-LaRouche,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LaRouche Aide Says He Used Aliases to Gain Information</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An aide to Lyndon H. LaRouche Jr.
testified Thursday that he frequently used aliases when trying to
gain information for the political maverick.
   Herbert Quinde, who described himself as an investigator for the
LaRouche organization, told LaRouche's federal fraud and conspiracy
trial that he misidentified himself because he described himself as
an ``intelligence and counterintelligence'' agent for LaRouche.
   ``If they knew who I worked for, they wouldn't give me any
information,'' he said. ``You don't think Bob Woodward identifies
himself, do you?''
   Woodward is an assistant managing editor and investigative
reporter for The Washington Post.
   Quinde said he telephoned the late noted attorney Edward Bennett
Williams, gave an alias and then attempted a trade of information.
Quinde said he called Williams because he had heard that Williams,
as a member of the Foreign Intelligence Advisory Board said at a
meeting that LaRouche ``had used dirty tricks.''
   ``I wanted to find out if he said those things. If he knew I
worked for LaRouche, he would not have told me anything.''
   Quinde, who declined to say what name he used, said Williams
wanted to exchange information with him.
   ``He said, `Kathy Graham is my client. I want to get LaRouche,'''
said Quinde. ``He told me he wanted to nail LaRouche to the boards.''
   Katharine Graham is chairman of the board of The Washington Post
Co.
   Quinde was one of more than a dozen witnesses on the first day of
the defense's case. Odin Anderson, LaRouche's attorney, submitted a
list of over 50 witnesses but told U.S. District Judge Albert V.
Bryan Jr. he believes the defense will complete its case in two or
three days.
   The case was recessed until Monday.
   LaRouche, a four-time minor party presidential candidate who
missed two days of his trial this week because of illness, was in
the courtroom Thursday but said little.
   LaRouche and six associates are charged with mail fraud and
conspiracy for allegedly raising more than $30 million in loans from
individual supporters without any intention of repaying them.
   In addition, LaRouche was accused of conspiring to defraud the
Internal Revenue Service by failing to file income tax returns for
any year since 1978 and having all his personal expenses paid by
various corporations he controls.
   If convicted on all 13 counts against him, LaRouche would face a
maximum penalty of 65 years in prison and fines totaling $3.25
million.
</TEXT>
