<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Hahn,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jessica Hahn's Contract Not Renewed; Says No Reason Given</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM F. RAWSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jessica Hahn's first job in radio won't be her
last, she vowed Thursday, even though the former secretary who lead
to the fall of TV-evangelist Jim Bakker said she knew she was hired
as ``a no-talent.''
   KOY-FM, the Phoenix radio station that hired Ms. Hahn as a disc
jockey in August, won't renew her contract when it expires Dec. 31,
general manager Mike Horne said.
   Horne said it was ``really just a matter of the situation that
exists here at the station.''
   ``Jessica is very serious about a radio career, and we all really
appreciate that,'' Horne said. ``She has made tremendous progress in
her role here at the station. It's not so much that we don't think
she could do her own show, it's we just don't have a position for
her.''
   ``I asked, but they didn't give me a reason,'' Ms. Hahn said. ``I
was hired as a no-talent and I know I've improved. I was hired for
my name, I know that. But I know I've improved.''
   Ms. Hahn said she learned her contract wouldn't be renewed the
day before Bakker and three ex-aides were indicted on federal fraud
and conspiracy charges ``so I know that had nothing to do with it.
It wasn't that publicity or anything.''
   A former church secretary who was paid $363,000 to keep quiet
about a sexual encounter with Bakker, Ms. Hahn lived for a time in
the Playboy Mansion in Los Angeles, wrote an article for Playboy
about her affair with Bakker, and posed nude for the magazine.
   But her future, she said, is in radio.
   ``I'm going to continue in radio. I truly love it,'' she said.
``I've gotten offers from all over the country, from New York to
Houston. I've also had offers for books and movies. In fact, I think
I've had more offers for movies than for radio. But I love radio.
That's what I want to do.''
   Ms. Hahn said she had no idea where she would go from here, but
is willing to listen to all offers.
</TEXT>
