<1ST_LINE>r i AM-JewishMarch     12-08 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jewish March,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jewish Protesters March on Temple Mount</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 50 young Jews with torches and Israeli
flags marched Thursday to the Temple Mount to demand free Jewish
access and removal of the Dome of the Rock, one of Islam's holiest
shrines.
   ``Some day it will be blown up, and we'll throw out all the
Arabs,'' said 17-year-old Shlomo Boxer, a demonstrator who carried
an Uzi machine gun on his shoulder. ``This is a holy place for Jews,
and it belongs to us.''
   The Temple Mount, which Moslems call the Noble Enclosure, is
sacred to both Jews and Moslems. Jews pray regularly at the Western
Wall, or ``wailing wall.'' It is believed to be the last remnant of
the Second Temple destroyed by the Romans 2,000 years ago.
   The demonstrators, members of a right-wing group called the
Temple Mount Faithful, protested a law requiring Israelis to gain
police permission before praying on the mount, where the Dome of the
Rock shrine sits near the Al Aqsa Mosque. Moslems believe the
prophet Mohammed ascended to heaven at the Dome of the Rock.
   The law is intended to prevent religious friction between Jews
and Moslems in this city that Israel captured in the 1967 Middle
East War and later declared its capital.
   ``The Arabs can carry Palestinian flags inside, but Jews can't go
in and pray when we want,'' said Danny Cohen, 17, referring to
anti-Israeli protests that sometimes take place on the Temple Mount.
``The Arabs shouldn't make the rules.''
   Gershon Solomon, founder of the group, led the flag-waving
procession. Protesters wore T-shirts emblazoned with nationalistic
slogans and chanted ``Israel is not for Arabs.''
   Police would not allow the group to enter until the demonstrators
put aside the flags and agreed to wear their T-shirts inside out. An
officer at the scene, who would not give his name, said police
feared the flags and shirts would ``create disturbances'' among Arab
worshipers.
   Solomon later told cheering supporters through a bull horn that
the government should completely open the Temple Mount to Jews. He
told reporters the Dome of the Rock, built in the seventh century,
should be dismantled and moved to ``a more suitable place.''
   ``This is the heart of the Jewish people,'' he said.
   Police barred reporters from the site and would not allow in more
than 10 demonstrators at once. They said there were no disturbances.
   Soldiers and police in riot gear watched as protesters danced in
circles and lit torches for Hanukkah, the Jewish festival of lights.
   ``I want to show I'm not afraid to be in my country,'' said Haim
Arbel, 17, of Tel Aviv. ``All of this land belongs to us.''
</TEXT>
