<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan     12-08 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bhutto's Government Proposes Budget Inherited From Rival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto on
Thursday introduced a budget that she inherited from her rivals, and
government officials said Pakistanis must wait for the economic
relief she has promised.
   The spending plan would raise defense spending to 34 percent of
the $7.7 billion operating budget and impose unpopular tax increases
to combat a budget deficit of about $3 billion.
   Ms. Bhutto had campaigned for parliamentary elections last month
on a platform of improving conditions for the poor. The vote
represented the country's first free elections in more than a
decade, and Ms. Bhutto took power Dec. 1 as the first woman to lead
a modern Islamic nation.
   But the populist leader said shortly afterward that her
government faced an impoverished economy on the brink of bankruptcy.
   The budget was put together by a caretaker government appointed
by Ms. Bhutto's archrival, the late Gen. Mohammed Zia-ul Haq, who
died Aug. 17 in an airplane crash. The father of Ms. Bhutto,
Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, was executed two years after Zia ousted him in
a 1977 military coup.
   The only program Ms. Bhutto's Pakistan People's Party introduced
Thursday was a $105 million development program aimed at upgrading
village roads and other facilities. She said they had deteriorated
during Zia's 11-year rule.
   In Thursday's televised budget speech to the National Assembly,
Ehsan-ul-haq Piracha, minister of state for finance, asked people to
be patient.
   ``Our hands are tied. ... It was not possible to amend within two
weeks this budget prepared by the caretaker government.''
   In an interview on the eve of the budget speech, Bhutto's
financial adviser, V.A. Jafaray, tried to lower people's
expectations for the immediate future.
   ``It may not be possible to do anything for the next six
months,'' he said. ``But this government will be in power for five
years.''
   Pakistan faces a foreign debt of $12.4 billion and domestic
borrowing of $15.2 billion.
   Ms. Bhutto also is expected to complete a deal with the
International Monetary Fund within two weeks. The agreement
reportedly would provide $1 billion to bolster the economy of
Pakistan, which would impose austerity measures in exchange.
</TEXT>
