<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru   12-08 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0710,0635</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Young Palestinian Killed On 1st Anniversary of Uprising</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout with army confirming some casualties, details
of
uprising anniversary, comments by defense minister, fight at rally
in Jordan. Edits to trim. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GAZA CITY, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers shot a
teen-ager in the heart Thursday, and Palestinians held a general
strike on the first anniversary of their uprising against Israel's
21-year occupation.
   The death of Yussef Mohammed Sbaith, 17, raised the number of
Palestinians killed to at least 320 since the rebellion began Dec.
8, 1987, in the West Bank and Gaza Strip. Eleven Israelis have been
slain and more than 7,000 Palestinians have been wounded.
   An army spokesman said Sbaith was shot in the heart when troops
were stoned during a sweep of the West Bank village of Kafr Rai.
   Soldiers also wounded a 22-year-old woman in the leg after
meeting ``violent resistance'' from stone-throwing youths in the
village, said the spokesman, whose name cannot be revealed under
army rules.
   Hospital officials said a 23-year-old man suffered head injuries
from a beating by troopers.
   Army gunfire wounded 11 other Palestinians, including a
14-year-old boy shot in the stomach, Arab doctors said. The clashes
occurred in the West Bank's largest city, Nablus, in the villages of
Kabatiya and Beit Lid to the north and in Gaza City, they said.
   An army spokesman confirmed six of the woundings, three in Nablus
and three in Beit Lid.
   Arab witnesses said two of the wounded were hit by bullets fired
from the window of a house the army used as a lookout post in the
open-air Nablus market, the center of many clashes between soldiers
and Arab youths.
   Palestinians closed businesses and halted public transportation
throughout the occupied territories.
   The underground leadership, which the Palestine Liberation
Organization supports, called the strike for the anniversary of the
revolt in the occupied lands. Israel captured the West Bank from
Jordan and the Gaza Strip from Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Israeli military authorities clamped a curfew on the entire Gaza
Strip, confining more than 650,000 Palestinians to their homes. The
curfew was announced on Israel television and over loudspeakers in
the area.
   Despite the curfew, Palestinian youths shot red and white
fireworks in Gaza City to mark the anniversary of the uprising.
   Residents of the old city also said people shouted ``Allahu
Akbar,'' or ``God is great,'' a traditional rallying cry of Moslems.
   The intefadeh, the Arabic word for uprising used even by the
Israelis, has generated international sympathy and a new sense of
purpose and identity among the 1.5 million Palestinians of the
occupied lands.
   Throughout the Gaza Strip, Palestinians erected roadblocks and
burned tires in sporadic acts of defiance Thursday. About 20
Palestinian youths were seen lobbing rocks from a barricaded alley
in Gaza City.
   A second strike is scheduled for Friday.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin told Israel television that
dealing with the uprising was ``a very uncomfortable mission'' for
the army.
   ``This is a confrontation of mostly civil violence,'' he said.
``Ninety percent of the incidents are concerned with rocks,
roadblocks or burning tires. Only about 10 percent of the incidents
are firebombs, perhaps even less.''
   In Amman, Jordan, a rally to commemorate the anniversary of the
Palestinian uprising ended in a fist fight between members of
opposing factions.
   Supporters of the Corrective Movement of the Palestine Liberation
Organization attacked people shouting slogans praising Fatah, the
main PLO faction headed by Yasser Arafat. Atallah Atallah, who heads
the Corrective Movement, seeks to unseat Arafat.
   No serious injuries were reported, but at least three Fatah
members were thrown out a first-floor window.
</TEXT>
