<1ST_LINE>r p AM-ChappellRuling 1stLd-Writethru a0716 12-08 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chappell Ruling, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0716,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Issues Decision; Congressman Still Doesn't Concede</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 4-6 to reflect certified results; picks up 7th
graf: `The justices ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BIRK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Supreme Court turned down an
appeal Thursday from 10-term Democratic Rep. Bill Chappell seeking
to throw out votes from a county that cost him the election.
   In a unanimous opinion, the court ruled Flagler County election
officials substantially complied with a deadline for reporting
election results, but Chappell still has not conceded.
   Chappell will read the opinion before deciding whether to appeal,
said press secretary Kay Thomas.
   Republican Craig James, a DeLand attorney and political newcomer,
defeated Chappell by 791 votes in final certified results of the
recounted Nov. 8 election.
   Chappell asked the Florida court to invalidate the Flagler County
votes, claiming county election officials didn't submit returns to
state officials within a seven-day deadline of the election.
   Had the court agreed, Chappell would have won by 229 votes.
   The justices said Flagler election officials ``substantially
complied'' with the deadline by telephoning the results before the
deadline. They noted the results were then transmitted by facsimile
machine one day later.
   Justice Parker Lee McDonald, writing for the court, said to throw
out the Flagler results would deny voters in that county their
constitutional rights.
   ``There has been substantial, and perhaps complete, compliance,''
he wrote. ``Chappell has presented no compelling reason for
disenfranchising the 11,000 residents of Flagler County who cast
their ballots on Nov. 8.''
   Chappell had been hampered during the campaign by persistent
reports that he was part of a probe into contract mismanagement by
the Pentagon. No charges have been filed.
   Meanwhile, Gov. Bob Martinez's general counsel, Peter Dunbar,
said he has no plans to recommend sanctions against Flagler
Elections Supervisor Etta Peterson.
   After an investigation earlier this year into illegal wiretapping
in her office, Mrs. Peterson entered a deferred-prosecution
agreement with the state attorney's office that said she will not be
prosecuted if she doesn't break any laws.
   She was accused of taping telephone conversations in the summer
of 1987 of a man she thought might run against her. As part of the
agreement, she wrote the man an apology.
</TEXT>
