<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan-Hideout     12-08 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Hideout,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nancy Sneaked President Out of L.A. Hotel To Go House-Hunting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nancy Reagan whisked President Reagan from his
Los Angeles hotel to show him a prospective Bel Air home, insisting
he hide from reporters on the floor of the back seat of her car, the
first lady's spokeswoman said Thursday.
   The incident occurred when the Reagans were vacationing in
California at a time when an investment group was considering the
purchase of the expensive home for the Reagans' use after they left
office, the spokeswoman, Elaine Crispen, said.
   The first lady wanted Reagan to see the house ``before the deal
was closed,'' Mrs. Crispen said in response to a reporter's question.
   ``I put him on the floor of the back seat of the car,'' Mrs.
Crispen quoted the first lady as saying. A Secret Service agent was
driving, and there may have been other agents in the car or in chase
vehicles, Mrs. Crispen said.
   Normally, the president travels in an armored limousine,
accompanied by a motorcade consisting of more than a dozen vehicles,
including a van containing Secret Service agents armed with
submachine guns. Other cars transport additional Secret Service
agents, special communications gear, police cars, an ambulance and
members of his staff and the press.
   The spokeswoman defended the first lady's action, saying it
allowed the couple ``to make a decision in private.''
   ``It doesn't bring up a question of security because he went and
he returned in good health,'' Mrs. Crispen said.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the incident occurred
sometime prior to his becoming Reagan's chief spokesman in February
1987.
   The Reagans decided last March to lease, rather than buy, the
$2.5 million estate. It is located in the luxurious Bel Air district
and is owned by Wall Management Services, a group of about 20
friends of the Reagans who bought it with them in mind.
   The three-year agreement gives the Reagans the option to renew
the lease or purchase the property. The estate includes 1\ acres of
ground and a secluded house with 6,500 feet of living space and a
pool.
   Wall Management bought the estate on Aug. 21, 1986, from a
90-year-old woman who the investors said would lease it back from
them until the Reagans were ready for it.
</TEXT>
