<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Thornburgh-Terrorists     12-08 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thornburgh-Terrorists,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorney General Blasts Greece's Explanation for Freeing Suspect</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh on Thursday
characterized as ``deplorable'' the Greek justice minister's
explanation for freeing a suspected terrorist in a 1982 attack on a
Rome synagogue.
   Thornburgh met in Athens with Greek Justice Minister Vasos Rotis
to express the U.S. government's deep concern over the decision to
free Abdel Osama Zomar, the Justice Department said in a statement
released in Washington.
   Zomar, a 27-year-old Palestinian, was expelled to Libya after
serving a sentence in Greece for smuggling arms. He is suspected of
membership in the Abu Nidal terrorist group and allegedly helped
organize the attack on Rome's main synagogue.
   The Italian government had sought Zomar's extradition from Greece
to prosecute him for the attack, which killed a 2-year-old child and
injured 37 other people.
   Rotis had justified his freeing of Zomar by calling his attack on
the synagogue ``an act of freedom,'' according to the Justice
Department statement.
   ``I told the minister that this explanation was deplorable,''
Thornburgh said.
   On Wednesday the Justice Department filed additional documents
with the Greek Supreme Court as part of an effort to extradite
another suspected Palestinian terrorist, Mohammed Rashid.
   Rashid has been accused in the United States with the 1982
bombing of a Pan American World Airways airliner that killed a
15-year-old boy and wounded 15 others.
   Rashid was arrested last May in Athens on other charges.
   The Justice Department statement quoted Thornburgh as saying
Rotis told him only that freeing Zomar would not serve as precedent
for the U.S. extradition request for Rashid.
</TEXT>
