<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 1906EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-World-QuakeAid     12-08 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-World-Quake Aid,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World Offers Cash, Blankets, High Technology To Quake-Struck
Armenia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Nations and organizations around the world responded Thursday to
the earthquake in Soviet Armenia with offers of aid ranging from
blankets to high-tech equipment aimed at detecting life under the
rubble.
   Armenian journalists said a Politburo commission led by Premier
Nikolai I. Ryzhkov heard preliminary estimates that up to 50,000
people died in Wednesday's quake. Officials said several cities in
the southern region were virtually destroyed.
   The Soviet Red Cross appealed for international aid, including
cash, medical supplies and food.
   In Geneva, the League of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies
said it opened a special Aid to Armenia account to receive
contributions.
   A statement by the world Red Cross body said aid pledges were
received from the national societies in the United States, Britain,
Bulgaria, France, Greece and Norway.
   Immediate needs cited by the Soviets were antibiotics, disposable
syringes and needles, blood substitutes, blood collection
containers, blood-transfusion equipment, canned meat and fish, dried
fruits and porridge, the league said.
   The West German Red Cross said it was ready to send 20,000
blankets and 1,000 tents and was offering $115,000 in aid. West
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl also offered emergency aid to the
Soviet government.
   ``We want to help within our capabilities, we are ready to give
relief aid to the victims,'' Kohl said in a telegram to Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   British officials said four London firefighters will travel to
Armenia on Friday with heat-detecting cameras and ultra-sensitive
microphones to detect minute sounds of life under the rubble.
   British rescue workers used the cameras to locate trapped people
after a 1985 earthquake in Mexico City, and helped save three babies
trapped in the ruins of a destroyed hospital. About 9,500 people
were killed in that quake.
   ``In that disaster, people were being removed from the debris a
week after the earthquake,'' said Londong Fire Brigade officer Paul
Quick.
   The Swiss Disaster Relief Corps offered to send rescue experts
and search dogs to help locate earthquake victims, a spokesman said.
   The government agency had not received a reply by Thursday
afternoon, the spokesman said on condition of anonymity. He said
Turkey, which suffered less damage from the quake than the Soviet
Union, declined a similar offer.
   In Havana, Cuban President Fidel Castro offered to send a
contingent of construction workers to help rebuild areas devastated
by the temblor.
   Castro made the offer in a message to Gorbachev, who was to have
begun a three-day visit to Cuba on Friday but cut short his trip in
New York to return home to deal with the crisis.
   President Reagan told Gorbachev before the Soviet leader returned
to Moscow: ``If there is any way we can be of assistance, either
bilaterally or through the international community, please let me
know.''
   Later, Reagan was asked whether he expected the United States to
be providing assistance. ``They haven't asked for any yet,'' he
replied.
   The United States will be providing antibiotics and other
medicines, said Richard F. Schubert, president of the American Red
Cross in Washington.
   Soviet officials have ``airlifted in about 15 tons of blankets,
tents, first aid kits,'' Schubert said. ``Armenia at this point in
the year is pretty cold, and so there is a critical need for
emergency shelter.''
   The Red Cross has activated a toll-free number for people to call
to offer assistance. The number is 1-800-453-9000.
</TEXT>
