<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Pardon 3rdLd-Writethru a0802 12-08 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Pardon, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0802,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyer Says Nofziger Told Reagan He Wouldn't Accept Pardon</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 8th graf pvs, bgng: ``He was ...'' to
include Reagan comments on whether he would pardon North.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former White House aide Lyn Nofziger told
President Reagan he wouldn't accept a presidential pardon for
ethics-law convictions because he wants to be vindicated in the
courts, his lawyer said Thursday.
   At the same time, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said
that first lady Nancy Reagan ``was given to understand'' that
another former Reagan aide, Michael K. Deaver, had discussed a
pardon with someone in the White House.
   Deaver, however, said he never had discussed a pardon for his
three perjury convictions with the president, the first lady or any
government official.
   Nofziger wrote a letter to the president ``a number of weeks
ago'' to state his refusal to accept any pardon that might be
contemplated before Reagan leaves office next month, said defense
attorney E. Lawrence Barcella.
   ``He happens to be an honorable guy who strongly believes in his
innocence and consequently felt that his vindication should come
through the courts and not through the president,'' Barcella said.
   ``It was something purely on his own initiative,'' Barcella said
of Nofziger's letter.
   Nofziger, 63, is free on bond while appealing a 90-day sentence
and $30,000 fine he received earlier this year for three felony
ethics-law convictions.
   He was found guilty of lobbying former Reagan administration
colleagues on behalf of private clients after he resigned in early
1981 as White House political director. He was convicted of
violating the one-year ban on lobbying by former officials after
leaving office.
   Reagan repeatedly has ruled out a pre-trial pardon for former
White House aide Oliver North, who is one of four people under
indictment in the Iran-Contra affair. The president last week said
even considering such a pardon ``would leave them under a shadow of
guilt for the rest of their lives. I think the law has got to take
its course.''
   Nofziger, who likened his offense to running a stop sign, has
repeatedly professed his innocence and criticized the Ethics in
Government Act for not imposing lobbying restrictions on former
members of Congress as well as officials of Cabinet agencies.
   A federal appeals court that heard arguments on the case Nov. 22
appeared receptive to arguments by Nofziger's attorneys that the
conviction should be overturned because prosecutors didn't prove a
willful violation of the law.
   Members of the three-judge panel questioned whether the statute
provided a clear warning to former officials of what would
constitute illegal lobbying.
   Barcella said Nofziger wrote Reagan before the appellate panel
heard arguments in the case.
   Deaver, the former deputy White House chief of staff, said in
response to a reporter's question: ``I have never discussed a pardon
with the Reagans, either or them, and I don't have any intention
to.''
   Deaver was given a suspended three-year sentence, fined $100,000
and ordered to perform 1,500 hours of community service for lying to
Congress and a grand jury investigating his lobbying business for
possible ethics-law violations. He is appealing the three felony
convictions.
   Deaver also denied raising the pardon issue in discussions or a
letter to anyone in government. ``I never wrote anybody a letter
about a pardon.''
   Deaver refused to further discuss the issue of a pardon.
</TEXT>
