<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     12-08 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Near-Blizzard Conditions Sock New Mexico and West Texas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   An invasion of arctic air, moisture from the Gulf of Mexico and
an upper-level storm system over Arizona combined to produce
near-blizzard conditions over parts of New Mexico and west Texas
Thursday.
   Up to 8 inches of snow was expected in New Mexico through the
evening. In the South Plains of western Texas, 25- to 35-mph winds
whipped up drifting snow, reducing visibility to near zero.
   In Texas, snow was found as far south as Wink and the southwest
mountains and sleet was reported between Midland and San Angelo.
Strong winds were expected to produce wind chill readings of 5 to 10
degrees below zero.
   A winter storm watch was posted for the night for New Mexico's
south-central and southwestern mountains and the southeastern Plains.
   Rain, heavy at times, extended across much of central and eastern
Texas. Victoria, north of Corpus Christi, got nearly 2 inches of
rain in six hours.
   Rain also fell over parts of the lower Mississippi Valley. Light
snow fell across northern Arkansas, and a snow advisory was posted
for north-central and northwestern Arkansas through the night.
   Light snow also fell across parts of the northern and central
Rocky Mountain region, the northern Plains and the northern Great
Lakes.
   Rainshowers were scattered from northern Florida and the central
Gulf Coast through the Tennessee Valley to the lower Great Lakes and
over western Washington state.
   Heavier snowfall totals for the six-hour period ending at 1 p.m.
EST included 4 inches at Sault Ste. Marie, Mich., and 3 inches at
Lubbock, Texas.
   High winds buffeted the southwestern United States during the
morning. Gusts to 58 mph were clocked at Ontario, Calif. High wind
warnings were in effect through the night for gusts up to 65 mph in
Southern California's mountains, the Mojave area, and Orange and San
Diego counties.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 4
degrees at Thief River Falls, Minn., to 83 degrees at Fort Myers,
Fla. The morning low for the nation was 9 below at Jackson and
Laramie, Wyo.
   Friday's forecast called for continued snow in southern New
Mexico and southwest Texas as well as the central Appalachians
through much of New England and the Great Lakes region. Rainshowers
were predicted for much of the rest of the area from southeastern
Arizona through the lower Mississippi Valley to the southern and
middle Atlantic Coast. Scattered showers should dot northern
Washington state, with scattered snowshowers over the northern
Plains and fog over western Oregon and central California. Fair to
partly sunny skies should prevail elsewhere.
   High temperatures should remain freezing from eastern Montana
through the upper half of the Mississippi Valley to New England,
with highs in the teens from eastern North Dakota and eastern South
Dakota to upper Michigan and northern lower Michigan, and across
northern Maine. Temperatures should rise above 50 degrees along the
northern Pacific Coast, from the California Coast to southern
Arizona, across the lower Rio Grande Valley of Texas, and from the
central Gulf Coast to the southern Atlantic Coast. Highs should
range in the 60s from California's central coast to southwestern
Arizona, and in southern Georgia and northern Florida. Highs in the
70s should be the rule for coastal Southern California and the
Florida Peninsula.
</TEXT>
