<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Locusts-Glance     12-08 0140</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Locusts-Glance,0145</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Locusts-at-a-Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Plane Downed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are a few facts about the locusts that two U.S. AID planes,
which were attacked Thursday over Mauritania, were sent to combat.
   
   WHAT THEY ARE _ Locusts are migratory grasshoppers with 3-inch
legs. They travel in hordes, stripping vast areas of vegetation.
   
   WHERE THEY ARE _ North Africa is now suffering its worst locust
infestation in 30 years. The insects were born on winds from the
Sahara Desert. However, winds also have blown them to other
continents. They have appeared in southern England and in 12
Caribbean nations, blown westward across the Atlantic Ocean by
tropical storms.
   
   THE THREAT _ Because they ravage vegetation, locusts pose a great
threat to food supplies. In North Africa, the locusts are striking
areas already suffering from severe drought.

</TEXT>
