<DOCNO> AP881208-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 2055EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Sakharov     12-08 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sakharov,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sakharov Ends Monthlong U.S. Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andrei Sakharov, wrapping up his first visit to the
United States Thursday, said Mikhail Gorbachev's speech to the
United Nations should strengthen the general secretary's position in
the Soviet Union.
   However, the 67-year-old physicist and Nobel Peace laureate
warned that Gorbachev's political restructuring known as perestroika
``cannot yet be called irreversible.''
   Sakharov also called for an international effort to aid victims
of the massive earthquake that hit Soviet Armenia on Wednesday. Tens
of thousands of people are believed dead.
   With his stepdaughter as an interpreter, the dissident said the
United States has vast experience with disaster relief and expressed
hope that Soviet authorities would allow international volunteers
into the stricken areas.
   Since arriving in the United States Nov. 4, Sakharov has visited
with relatives, undergone medical testing, promoted a new
international organization and met with President Reagan in
Washington.
   He boarded a 6:40 p.m. flight from Logan International Airport
for Paris, where he plans to attend a celebration of the 40th
anniversary of the United Nations' Universal Declaration of Human
Rights. He said he may meet in Paris with Polish Solidarity leader
Lech Walesa.
   In his well-received speech to the United Nations Wednesday,
Gorbachev offered to cut the Red Army by 10 percent and withdraw
50,000 Soviet troops from Eastern Europe.
   Sakharov said, ``I believe that Gorbachev has taken a very
important initiative and that this will broaden international
support for him and therefore strengthen his position in the Soviet
Union.''
   However, Sakharov repeated a sentiment often voiced during his
trip _ that Gorbachev's plan of political and economic restructuring
faces some serious obstacles.
   ``I believe that the process of perestroika is now in a very
critical phase,'' he said. ``There are a whole spectrum of serious
problems. The economic restructuring is especially complex. My
country is in a stage of searching for solutions, and this period
could last a long time.''
   Sakharov, who won the 1975 Nobel Peace Prize for his human rights
activities, was exiled to the closed industrial city of Gorky in
January 1980 for his criticism of the Soviet military intervention
in Afghanistan. He was released in December 1986.
   He received a visa to visit the United States as a member of the
Soviet delegation to the International Foundation for the Survival
and Development of Humanity, a non-profit organization that plans to
sponsor research on global problems such as hunger, arms control,
pollution and energy conservation.
   Sakharov came to the United States without his wife, Yelena
Bonner, who remained in Moscow. He spent much of his time visiting
her daughter and son-in-law in the Boston suburb of Newton.
   Asked whether he would like to live in the United States,
Sakharov said no.
   ``I think that my fate is completely bound up with the country
where I was born and I want to live there,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
