<DOCNO> AP881208-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 2135EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CreationInstitute     12-08 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Creation Institute,0653</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Prepares Appeal of State's Ban</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HOWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The founder of a fundamentalist
Christian college said Thursday he will appeal the state's decision
to bar his school from granting master's degrees in science as
motivated by an anti-creationist bias.
   Dr. Henry Morris, president of the private, San Diego-based
Institute for Creation Research, said the college has granted
graduate degrees in science for seven years and never had a problem
with state education authorities.
   He said he will file an appeal with the Council on Private
Postsecondary Institutions, the 15-member state panel reviewing the
decision next month.
   ``At that point,'' Morris said, ``we will decide whether to take
it to the courts or not.''
   California schools superintendent Bill Honig announced Wednesday
that the state Education Department's licensing agency ordered the
institute to stop offering master's degrees in science, declaring
that the classes offer students religious dogma instead of
scientific theory.
   A report of the agency's decision, which received little
attention when it was made last week, was carried in Thursday's
editions of the New York Times.
   Since 1981, 12 students have obtained master of science degrees
at the college, and about ``30 to 40'' are currently pursuing
similar graduate studies, Morris said. ``We are a very small
operation,'' he added.
   ``Everybody's agreed that they have the right to teach the course
_ they agree to that and we agree to that. They say they want to
issue a degree in science, but they say creationism is science. We
don't,'' Honig said.
   ``The question here is whether we let them call it science or
not,'' he added. ``I assume it (the curriculum) is good creationism,
but can you say that a person there has a degree in physics or
geology?
   ``When you believe the world is 6,000 years old, it's pretty
tough to get a degree in geology.''
   In a related development Thursday, the Policy and Planning
Committee of the state Board of Education postponed action on
proposed ``anti-dogmatism'' guidelines for science teaching.
   ``The guidelines make a distinction between theory and belief and
fact, and they get into definitions as they relate to the teaching
of the origins of life,'' said Susan Lange, a spokeswoman for Honig.
   The goal of the guidelines, she added, is to ensure that ``dogma
is not presented as fact or scientific evidence.'' The board is
expected to consider the issue again next month.
   At issue in the degree dispute, Honig and Morris said, is the
philosophical gap between those who accept the biblical version of
the divine creation of the earth, and those who contend that life
evolved over millions of years.
   The state's decision stemmed from an inspection of the college in
August by a state panel of five scientists who decided, after
consulting with Honig, that religious theory was being taught, not
science.
   Honig has the authority to affirm or reject the decision of the
Council on Private Postseconday Institutions on Morris' appeal. If
rejected, Morris can appeal to an administrative law judge, then
appeal through the court system.
   State rejection of the master's of science degree means that
graduates cannot claim in applications for jobs, financial
assistance or other colleges, that they have completed a science
curriculum.
   It also means that the course would not satisfy state
professional credentialing requirements _ for example, for a
teacher's credential, Honig said.
   Major colleges and universities in California are accredited
through recognized national or regional academic-standards groups.
Smaller schools, such as technical or business colleges, require
approval from the state school superintendent to grant degrees.
   In 1986, the Legislature and governor tightened the state's
credentialing laws, requiring numerous small schools, including the
Institute for Creation Research to apply to the state for permission
to grant degrees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881208-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 2141EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan-KeyMoments     12-08 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Key Moments,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Reminisces About High Moments, Low Moments</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Thursday night the
hardest part of his job has been to send young Americans into
combat, and the thing he ``enjoyed the most'' was the economic
recovery.
   ``I think there have been many tough things,'' the president said
when asked at what may have been his final news conference to
describe what had made him feel good and what had made him feel
badly.
   ``I don't think there's anything tougher than to have to order
these magnificent young men and women in our military today ... into
danger, to order them to go someplace where their lives are
threatened and their lives are taken,'' he said. ``That's got to be
something that any president would hesitate on and have to say was
the greatest burden.''
   In response to another question asked later in the 33-minute,
nationally broadcast news conference, Reagan added that the taking
and holding of Americans as hostages in Lebanon was one of the
heaviest burdens he has borne.
   ``It is ... again one of those things ... that you go to bed with
every night,'' he said when asked about prospects for winning the
release of nine Americans held by pro-Iranian elements in Lebanon.
   During Reagan's presidency, more than 200 U.S. military personnel
were killed during a bombing of a Marine barracks in Beirut,
Lebanon, 19 servicemen were killed when several thousand troops were
sent into combat during the invasion of Grenada, and 37 crewmen
aboard the USS Stark were killed when their ship was struck by
missiles fired by an Iraqi fighter while it was patrolling the
Persian Gulf.
   When asked what he most enjoyed about the presidency, Reagan
replied that ``there are a number of things to miss.''
   But Reagan said ``let me simply say one I enjoyed the most is the
economic recovery.''
   ``When I came here, for almost half a century, the debate on the
(Capitol) Hill in the Congress had always been between more big
spending programs, more power for the federal government, more
intervention in private affairs by the federal government, as
against those who were preaching less,'' he said.
   ``We were in a disastrous situation when we came here,'' Reagan
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
