<DOCNO> AP881208-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 2157EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan-Gorbachev     12-08 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Gorbachev,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Voices Respect, Admiration For Gorbachev</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Questions on U.S.-Soviet relations dominated
President Reagan's nationally broadcast news conference on Thursday
and he voiced both admiration and respect for Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev a day after their final meeting as leaders.
   Reagan's first complimentary mention of his Soviet counterpart
came in his opening statement as he characterized Gorbachev's hasty
return home, prompted by the devastating earthquake in Armenia, as
``a sad final note to what has been an otherwise successful _ and I
use the next words advisedly _ happy and historic visit to the
United States.''
   The president also mentioned that he had given Gorbachev an
inscribed photo of the walk they had taken together in Geneva in
1985. Reagan said he and his wife, Nancy, ``were delighted'' the
Gorbachevs had invited them to Moscow and that he hoped the
Gorbachevs could come visit them in California.
   Reminded of his earlier stern criticism of Soviet leaders and the
Soviet system, Reagan said there were differences in recent Soviet
leaders, ``but, I must say, I have never met with one of those
leaders that was comparable to this man or had the approach that he
has.''
   Still, Reagan added, ``He knows that I feel that _ well, we put
it this way, as I've said, my philosophy is, trust everybody, but
cut the cards.''
   Asked if he trusted Gorbachev fully, Reagan said:
   ``He hasn't shown me any reason yet that I shouldn't. But, again,
as I've said, that's why I kept referring to ``doveryai, no
proveryai,'' trust but verify, and he knows that.''
   Asked to assess Gorbachev's long-term chances for political
survival, Reagan said: ``Well, I realize, and I think we all should,
that he is battling a bureaucracy, because whether it's a Russian
bureaucracy or one of our own, the first rule of bureaucracy is
protect the bureaucracy.''
   ``And it would mean some great changes for some of the
``Nomenklatura,'' as they call their bureaucracy there, if he
institutes the reforms that he's talking about.
   ``But, on the plus side for him, it's very evident that the
people of the Soviet Union are on his side,'' Reagan continued.
``And I have to believe that the Nomenklatura is going to have to
think twice with regard to how far they would go in trying to block
him when the man in the street over there wants the things that have
been seen.''
</TEXT>
