<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Steinberg     12-08 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Steinberg,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Suggests Ms. Nussbaum Was Jealous of Lisa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer for a man charged with fatally beating
his 6-year-old illegally adopted daughter suggested Thursday that
his client's live-in companion was jealous of his relationship with
the girl.
   Hedda Nussbaum, who lived with defendant Joel Steinberg for 12
years, could have had a motive to hurt the little girl, Steinberg's
attorney Ira London implied.
   Last week, WABC-TV quoted a psychiatric report that stated that
Ms. Nussbaum, who has testified that Steinberg frequently beat her,
had feelings of ``rivalry'' with Lisa Steinberg.
   Ms. Nussbaum, the key prosecution witness at Steinberg's murder
trial, denied she was jealous of Lisa but admitted that Steinberg
often would take the child out on social occasions and leave her
home.
   ``I wished that I could go, too,'' Ms. Nussbaum told London
during her third day of cross-examination. ``I was not happy that I
could not go.''
   During a break in the questioning, Ms. Nussbaum's lawyer, Barry
Scheck, said, ``London's trying to show she didn't care about the
child. It's just not true, so it's not happening.''
   ``Did it become more frequent in 1987 that Joel took Lisa and
left you at home?'' London asked Ms. Nussbaum.
   ``In '86 and '87,'' she answered, and offered a reason: ``At that
time Joel did not want me to be showing myself to new people who
didn't know me because I didn't look too terrific.''
   Steinberg, 47, is accused of murder for allegedly beating Lisa to
death. He denies that he hit the girl; Ms. Nussbaum has testified
that he did.
   The first-grader was removed unconscious from Steinberg's
Greenwich Village apartment on Nov. 2, 1987. She died of head
injuries three days later.
   The death of the little girl in an affluent, well-educated
household _ Steinberg was an attorney, now disbarred, and Ms.
Nussbaum was a children's book editor _ shocked the city and led to
a re-examination of responsibilities of neighbors, teachers and
social workers to recognize and report suspected child abuse.
   Steinberg obtained Lisa shortly after her birth from an unwed
Long Island teen-ager, telling the mother the baby would be placed
with a Catholic family in Manhattan. The mother, Michelle Launders,
paid Steinberg $500 for ``filing fees.''
   Ms. Launders, 27, has watched the seven-week trial daily from a
front-row seat. She said she was angry that Ms. Nussbaum had not
prepared her home for the baby after Ms. Nussbaum testified she and
Steinberg had planned to keep the infant even before she was born.
   Ms. Nussbaum, who said she was unable to conceive, testified that
it was a complete surprise to her when they got a second child, a
boy born to another unwed teen-ager. ``Joel always said he wanted a
son,'' she said.
   The boy, named Mitchell, was 16 months old when Lisa died. He has
since been returned to his natural mother.
   London asked Ms. Nussbaum whether she had ever told a
psychiatrist Mitchell was her favorite of the two children. She
denied she had said that.
</TEXT>
