<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan-Quotation     12-08 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Quotation,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Tries To Straighten Out 8-Year-Old Quotation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Thursday used what was
probably his last formal news conference to straighten out one of
the most familiar quotations from his first. The quotation, he said,
is actually a misquotation.
   The president was asked if, after his warm meeting with Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev in New York on Wednesday, he still
believes the Soviets would lie, cheat and steal to achieve their
political goals.
   ``Do you think he has really change, to what extent has he
changed and how have you changed?'' was the question.
   ``I know so many of you quoted this in that first press
conference of mine,'' said Reagan. ``But none of you ever thought to
give the complete answer.
   ``I said, `in their own words,' this was their philosophy and it
was in writing that there was no crime, all of these things were not
a crime if they advanced the cause of socialism,'' Reagan added.
   ``Now I didn't make that up. That's what they said. I think
there's been a change. That was four leaders back before this one.''
   Well, he's right.
   In his news conference of Jan. 29, 1981, Reagan was asked what he
saw as the Soviets' long term intentions.
   ``I don't have to think of an answer as to what I think their
intentions are; they have repeated it,'' the then-new president
replied. ``I know of no leader of the Soviet Union since the
revolution ... that has not more than once repeated in the various
Communist congresses they hold their determination that their goal
must be the promotion of world revolution ...
   ``Now, as long as they do that and as long as they, at the same
time, have openly and publicly declared that the only morality they
recognize is what will further their cause, meaning they reserve
unto themselves the right to commit any crime, to lie, to cheat, in
order to attain that, and that is moral, not immoral, and we operate
on a different set of standards, I think when you do business with
them, even at a detente, you keep that in mind.''
</TEXT>
