<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Holloway-IRS     12-08 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Holloway-IRS,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRS Says Louisiana Congressman Owes $76,000 in Payroll Taxes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Internal Revenue Service has filed a
lien against Rep. Clyde Holloway, R-La., claiming he owes more than
$76,000 in payroll taxes from his central Louisiana nursery.
   Holloway, contacted Thursday in Opelousas, said he didn't have
his files with him but expressed the belief that ``probably
sixty-some-odd thousand'' dollars was paid after the lien was filed
Tuesday in state District Court here.
   He said he hoped to have the balance paid by Friday.
   In its claim, the IRS maintained that Holloway, owner of
Holloway's Nursery in nearby Forest Hill, was delinquent in paying
$76,088.69 in payroll taxes from June 30, 1987, through June 30,
1988.
   Payroll taxes include money employers are required to pay the
government for such things as Social Security benefits for their
employees, the IRS said.
   Henry Holmes, an IRS spokesman in New Orleans, said the lien was
a standard procedure aimed at protecting ``the interest of the
government. Our emphasis in this case is to work with the taxpayer
to resolve it.''
   Holloway blamed Louisiana's depressed oil economy for the
delinquency, as well as his preoccupation with last fall's
re-election campaign in Louisiana's large, meandering 8th
Congressional District.
   Asked if his business is in financial trouble, Holloway replied:
``I'm sure my being gone doesn't help it any.''
</TEXT>
