<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Helicopter     12-08 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Helicopter,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honduras Checking if Nicaraguan Pilot was Spy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honduras said Thursday it is
investigating whether a Nicaraguan helicopter pilot was spying when
Honduran authorities intercepted his Soviet-made helicopter gunship.
   His mission ``could well have been espionage,'' Foreign Minister
Carlos Lopez said in messages to the United Nations and the
Organization of American States.
   Earlier Thursday, Lopez said Honduras has not decided whether to
grant political asylum to pilot Edwin Rafael Estrada Leiva, who
landed his helicopter Wednesday at a Honduran air base.
   The Nicaraguan government said an army defector flew the
helicopter across the border and described him as a ``CIA
terrorist.''
   Nicaraguan Foreign Minister Miguel D'Ecoto Brockmann said in a
protest note to Honduras on Wednesday that the helicopter incident
might be linked to a U.S. plan to invade Nicaragua.
   The Honduran armed forces said it intercepted Estrada in Honduras
air space on Wednesday and made him land his Soviet-made MI-25
helicopter at an air base near the capital.
   Nicaragua immediately demanded the return of the helicopter and
pilot. It also accused Honduras of kidnapping the pilot.
   The United States funds the war of the Contra rebels against
Nicaragua's leftist government, and the Soviet bloc arms Nicaragua.
Honduras has allowed the Contras to maintain bases on its territory,
and the United States also maintains a military presence there.
   Both Honduras and Nicaragua have accused each other of border
incursions, and tension remains high despite a truce in Nicaragua's
civil war.
</TEXT>
