<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 2303EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ComputerExtortion     12-08 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Computer Extortion,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Men Accused of Computer Extortion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two unemployed aerospace workers described by
acquaintances as ``oddballs, misfits'' have been charged with
attempted extortion in computerized death threats to prominent
Antelope Valley residents.
   Roman Stephan Makuch, 27, and Richard Mathew Faroni, 26, who were
arrested in Las Vegas on Thanksgiving Day, were being returned
Thursday to the community of Lancaster, said Deputy District
Attorney Steve Cooley.
   Although the two are suspected of sending 265 computer-produced
threats, they were charged with only 10 specific acts to simplify
the case, Cooley said.
   Cooley said the recipients were all ``substantial people''
including a former Lancaster city manager, bank vice presidents and
professionals in the Antelope Valley, the rapidly expanding suburbs
60 miles north of downtown L.A. on the southern rim of the Mojave
Desert.
   Cooley said many of the letters were nearly identical but that
the text of each was ``customized'' to include personal information
about the recipient.
   The letters, attached to the complaint, began with an obscenity
and a threat of death. The writers then demanded specific amounts of
cash as high as $600,000 with instructions for its delivery. They
went on to give gruesome details of how victims would be killed and
threatened harm to their children, spouses and relatives.
   ``These victims did not take it as a joke,'' said Cooley. Some
fled the Antelope Valley and stayed in hotels while others installed
security systems after recieving the letters on Nov. 2 and Nov. 3,
he said.
   ``There were two people hospitalized as the result of their fear
and concern,'' he said.
   No one paid any money, and all recipients who did not discard the
letters as junk mail contacted authorities.
   Cooley said it appeared that the letter writers had researched
their targets, including in some letters specific information about
the recipients' business relationships and homes. One letter
referred to the satellite dish on a resident's house and threatened
to ``fertilize your fruit trees with your decaying ... body.''
   ``We can put toxic chemicals in your toothpaste or glue laced
with poison cyanide on envelopes and stamps that you lick,'' the
letters said. Many contained the phrase, ``The organization has
watched this area over a year and we know what you can pay.''
   Makuch and Faroni waived extradition from Las Vegas. Cooley said
a search of their apartment and a nearby storage facility turned up
a computer, printers and computer discs, a handgun and several CB
radios.
   The letters had told some recipients to bring a CB radio to Las
Vegas and tune in a specific channel for instructions on where to
deliver money.
   The prosecutor said the men were unemployed but both had
previously worked on an assembly line at Rockwell International's
Palmdale plant on the B-1B bomber project.
   He said acquaintances who spoke to local news media about them
said, ``They could be characterized as being a couple of oddballs,
misfits.''
   Cooley said other people may be involved and the investigation
was continuing.
   Both men were charged with conspiracy to commit extortion,
attempted extortion and sending threatening letters for extortion
purposes. If convicted, they could draw maximum sentences of six
years in prison.
</TEXT>
