<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Soviet Leader Returns to Lead Rescue Operation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: COMBINES, a0857,a0860, a0864. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev returned to
Moscow early Friday, cutting short his trip to the United States,
Cuba and Britain after an earthquake leveled cities and killed
thousands of people in northern Armenia.
   The official Soviet news agency Tass announced Gorbachev's return
in a brief statement that did not say whether he would stay in
Moscow or immediately fly to Yerevan, Armenia's capital.
   Gorbachev's return also was reported as the first item on the
morning television program ``120 Minutes.''
   Tass said, ``interrupting his trip abroad ... Gorbachev returned
from New York to Moscow.''
   It said he was accompanied by Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze, a native of the Georgian republic just north of the
stricken area; Politburo member Alexander N. Yakovlev, and Deputy
Premier Vladimir Kamentsev.
   Gorbachev interrupted his trip a day after addressing the United
Nations in New York and holding a summit meeting with President
Reagan and President-elect George Bush.
   He had been scheduled to leave New York on Friday for Cuba, and
then travel to Britain.
   But Shevardnadze announced in New York that Gorbachev instead
would be heading home to lead the rescue and clean-up operations
following the Wednesday earthquake.
   Shevardnadze said thousands of people had died, but Soviet
officials have given no figures.
   Unofficial reports have said the toll is in the tens of thousands.
   Armenian journalists said a Communist Party Politburo commission
headed by Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov was told at a meeting in
Yerevan on Thursday that the toll could approach 50,000.
</TEXT>
