<2ND_LINE>AM-Boardinghouse Reunion,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tipster in Boardinghouse Murders Reunited With Family</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KOLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROMULUS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man's role in helping police arrest a
woman charged in a series of California boardinghouse murders led
him to an emotional reunion Thursday with a son he hadn't seen in
more than three decades.
   ``This is the moment I've been waiting for for the last 32
years,'' Charles Willgues Sr., 59, said after embracing Charles Jr.
at Detroit Metropolitan Airport. ``I'd always hoped, but I was about
to give it up. You know the record by Frank Sinatra, `For Once In My
Life?' That's what I'm experiencing right now.''
   Two of Willgues' daughters didn't come to the airport to avoid
publicity. He was to meet with them later.
   ``I'm just going to take this day-by-day,'' said 35-year-old
Charles Willgues Jr. of Taylor.
   Willgues' children hadn't seen their father since he left
Michigan more than three decades ago. They say they might not have
found him if he hadn't helped police find a California murder
suspect.
   Willgues Sr. met Dorothea Puente in a Los Angeles bar last month,
five days after she fled her Sacramento boarding house following the
discovery of seven bodies on the property. He tipped off authorities
and she was arrested.
   A television reporter trying to locate Willgues after Puente's
arrest visited his old apartment, where there was a letter from
Willgues' youngest daughter, Debbie Sculley. She had traced her
father to California, but didn't know he had recently moved.
   The reporter passed the letter on to Willgues and Taylor Police
helped him get in touch with his family, leading to Thursday night's
reunion.
   ``I'm a little bit excited and a little bit confused,'' the
younger Willgues said before the plane arrived. ``I mean, I haven't
seen my father in 33 years. I never really even knew him.''
   The son, who drives a tractor-trailer for a Detroit trucking
company, said he and his sister wrote the letter found by the
reporter.
   ``We said: `This is so-and-so, your long-lost son and daughter,
and we'd like to get together sometime,''' he said. ``If (the Puente
case) had never come about, we might have never gotten together.''
   The elder Willgues' 34-year-old daughter, Linda, said earlier
Thursday she was waiting for a private moment with her dad.
   ``I'm not going,'' she said of the airport trip. ``It's just too
public.''
   A woman who identified herself in a telephone interview only as
Willgues' first wife said she was not anxious to see him again.
   ``He left when the kids were babies,'' she said. ``I don't know
why the kids are so anxious to see him. I guess it's mostly
curiosity.''
</TEXT>
