<HEAD>Some of Britain's Top Public Schools</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-English School Elites, b0779</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public schools were named centuries ago to
distinguish the education they provided from that received at home.
   They were founded as religious seminaries. The first was
Winchester, with the motto ``Manners makyth man.''
   Among the best-known are the following dozen, with the years they
were founded and the student body size in parentheses. G connotes a
school that admits girls to the sixth form, equivalent of the 12th
grade.
   Winchester 1382 (650)
   Eton 1440 (1,250)
   St. Paul's 1509 (770)
   Shrewsbury 1552 (650)
   Westminster 1560 (610) G
   Merchant Taylors' 1561 (720)
   Rugby 1567 (730) G
   Harrow 1571 (770)
   Blundell's 1604 (485) G
   Charterhouse 1611 (713) G
   Marlborough 1843 (900) G
   Wellington 1856 (810) G
