<1ST_LINE>s a BC-DeathontheSidewalk Adv11-2Takes   12-08 1109</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Death on the Sidewalk, Adv11-2 Takes,1141</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 11, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Son of Wealth Dies Homeless and Alone on Cold City Sidewalk</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   ``Joe was a fabulous swimmer. No one I ever knew looked as
graceful as he did in the water. He just had a hard time on land.''
   _ Nick Eaton, whose brother, Joe, died on a San Francisco
sidewalk last week after a sad life of alcholism and failed
opportunity.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph Emerson Eaton Jr., born to wealth and
privilege in Boston, met death as a homeless alcoholic, tossed
unconscious from a fast food restaurant to die alone on a cold
sidewalk in San Francisco's Tenderloin.
   Eaton was an unlikely member of the city's legion of street
people, and family riches couldn't overcome his love of vodka or the
despair he felt after losing his lover to AIDS a year ago.
   His crumpled, lifeless body became as invisible to dozens of
passersby in those chilly hours of early Saturday morning as the
hundreds of other huddled forms that line the city's streets and
crowd into doorways.
   Advocates for the homeless have seized upon Eaton's death at age
38 as a symbol of the homeless crisis and public callousness.
   ``If he had been a middle-class person at a restaurant anywhere
else in town and passed out, they'd have called for an ambulance, or
the cops if he was drunk,'' said the minister who discovered Eaton's
body. ``They wouldn't just throw him out onto the sidewalk and let
him lay there and die.''
   Eaton's lonely death has raised questions about society's
responsibility for the homeless, but his life was a story of sadness
and failed opportunity.
   A prep school graduate and the grandson of a Boston banker,
family members said Eaton's troubles began when he started drinking
at 13.
   After years of battling alcohol, Eaton's final tailspin began as
he was mourning the death of the man who had inspired him to forsake
the bottle.
   It ended when he collapsed over a bacon cheeseburger at a Carl's
Jr. restaurant around midnight Dec. 2. He died after a security
guard, thinking Eaton was drunk, dragged him outside into the
48-degree cold and left him in a misshapen pile.
   Almost five hours later, the Rev. Thomas Flower, an Eastern
Orthodox monk who feeds hundreds of homeless people from his van,
recognized Eaton and discovered he was dead. The exact cause of
death will not be known for at least a week, pending results of
toxicology tests.
   In an ironic twist to an already tragic story, the guard was
himself homeless before he was hired by the restaurant 3{ years ago.
   Eaton grew up the son of privilege in Duxbury, Mass., a
well-to-do suburb of Boston. His late grandfather, Charles Freedom
Eaton Jr., co-founded Investors Bank & Trust Co. His father, Joseph
Sr., is a retired business executive.
   But Eaton's alcoholism systematically destroyed whatever
stability his family's wealth provided, according to friends and
family.
   ``He was an alcoholic,'' said Eaton's older brother Nick, a
contractor in New Hampshire. ``He was also a person who was gay, and
I think that it took him a long time to come to grips with that and
to start feeling really good about himself.''
   Although Nick disputes it, some friends say Joe's homosexuality
was a source of family tension.
   ``The family had limitations on how much they could accept Joe
because of his homosexuality,'' said one friend, Stephen Irvine, 43,
of San Francisco.
   The family repeatedly paid Eaton's enrollment fees at some of the
nation's most expensive alcohol and drug rehabilitation programs,
but Eaton repeatedly fell off the wagon.
   Irvine, who last saw Eaton almost a year ago on the eve of his
beginning yet another treatment program, said his friend didn't
struggle with his drinking problem, but ``went right head first into
it.''
   When friends would intervene with his drinking, ``it was as
though he'd get just clear-headed enough to recognize his despair
and plunge out,'' said Irvine. ``Vodka. He really liked vodka.''
   Eaton's sponsor in Alcoholics Anonymous for six years said
Eaton's problems were not with his family but with himself.
   ``Sobriety is for people that want it,'' said Skip B., who
withheld his last name in compliance with AA tradition. ``I'm really
sorry it ended this way, but I can't say I'm surprised.''
   ``I like Joe as a person,'' Skip said later, lapsing into present
tense. ``He's a nice guy and I somehow felt that under all that
booze ... there was somebody trying to get out. I just figured that
someday maybe he'd get it.''
   Although Irvine and some of Eaton's acquaintances on the streets
accuse family members of using their wallets to say what their
hearts could not, others portray a man trapped in self-destruction,
refusing to take responsibility for his life.
   Eaton never went to college and worked as a chef and a florist
when he was sober. After some years in Denver, he came to San
Francisco in 1981. The next year, he was arrested on drug charges.
   Eaton's life turned around when he met Phillip Coleman through
AA. They became lovers and lived together for five years. Until
Coleman's death of AIDS in November 1987, Eaton stayed clean and
sober.
   Irvine said Eaton ``just adored and lived through Coleman.'' But
after his lover's death, Eaton ``had no real desire to go on. All
the life he'd known was dead. I think he was a passive suicide.''
   Eaton, who knew he had AIDS-related complex, spent a lot of time
drinking alone in the apartment the couple had shared, according to
Skip.
   He lost his job as a florist's driver. Finally, in late January,
Nick flew out, packed Eaton's belongings and enrolled him in a
$7,000, one-month program at St. Mary's Hospital in Minneapolis.
   When Eaton returned to San Francisco, he lived with Skip
rent-free for several months, but quickly returned to sporadic heavy
drinking.
   He asked his family if he could move back East. Nick agreed and
was readying a cabin on his property.
   But family members had agreed with Joe after the Minneapolis
treatment that if he came home, he should be sober _ and if he
started drinking again, he had to bear responsibility.
   ``He felt very strongly about that,'' said Nick, emphasizing that
his brother had not requested any assistance this time. ``I think he
was trying to prove himself. ... He was making an effort _ not that
night, I guess _ to pull it together.''
   ``I think he was having one last fling.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
