<DOCNO> AP881208-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 1723EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-DeathontheSidewalk Adv11-1stAdd   12-08 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Death on the Sidewalk, Adv11-1st Add,0449</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 11, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>SAN FRANCISCO: last fling.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Eaton lost his home with Skip after passing out during a binge
and starting a minor fire with a lit cigarette. The landlord ordered
him out, and Skip, who said he ``doesn't give up on people,'' had to
comply.
   On Nov. 13, the day Skip turned him out, Eaton landed in an
intensive care unit in a coma, with a blood-alcohol level experts
said could have killed him.
   ``The last I heard from him was Friday (hours before his death)
when he called to see if his welfare check had arrived,'' said Skip.
   That same day he called Nick to ask if the family would pay for
one more treatment program. Nick promised they would.
   Compared to many of the city's thousands of homeless, Eaton had a
short life on the streets. Yet his death has refocused attention on
the problem and the inadequacy of support programs.
   ``These are our people,'' said Rev. Cecil Williams, pastor of
Glide Memorial United Methodist Church and a frequent spokesman for
the city's underpriviliged. ``We've got to make sure our people
don't need to go through serious misery from year to year before
something is done.''
   John Crew, a lawyer with the American Civil Liberties Union, said
Eaton's death is ``another tragic example of how this society has
not dealt with the fundamental social and health issues of
homelessness.''
   A spokesman for the restaurant that put Eaton on the street said
the eatery had no choice.
   ``If somebody is obviously passed out drunk, we're not going to
have people sleeping in our restaurant. No one is,'' said Carl's Jr.
spokesman Paul Mitchell. He said the same thing takes place ``one,
two or three times a night.''
   The Eaton family plans no legal action against the restaurant or
the guard who ejected Joe. As the man who discovered Eaton's body
said at an informal street memorial service Tuesday, the time for
anger is past.
   ``It is time for reconciliation,'' said Flower. ``The best
memorial for Joseph Eaton is reconciliation.''
   One of the mourners was Barry Tompkins, who used to be homeless.
He said it is easy to become anonymous living on the streets.
   ``People just walk by,'' he said. ``I don't think anybody knew he
was wealthy. Nobody really cared. You sort of lose your identity. ...
   ``When you live like this, you can get caught,'' said Tompkins.
``It's not easy to break out. You've got to have dreams. You've got
to have something to pull yourself out.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
