<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     12-08 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev's Speech Gets Mixed Market Reaction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail Gorbachev's peacemaking efforts got a mixed reaction in
the financial markets, strengthening the dollar, depressing gold and
causing shrugs of indifference among stock and bond traders, who
dismissed the Soviet leader's remarks as old news.
   Gorbachev told the United Nations on Wednesday the Soviet Union
would cut troop strength by half a million and reduce the number of
conventional arms. Speculation on Tuesday that he would make an
announcement along those lines already had pushed up stock and bond
prices.
   But in the currency markets, traders reacted enthusiastically to
Gorbachev's speech and bid the dollar higher against major
currencies.
   They reasoned that reduced Soviet military spending would give
George Bush's incoming administration a greater chance of cutting
this country's staggering budget deficit, which many economists
consider a long-term threat to the dollar's value and the economy in
general.
   ``All of a sudden when the Gorby stuff came out, people said gee,
maybe Bush will have flexibility to do some budget cutting,'' said
James Hohorst, director of foreign exchange at Manufacturers Hanover
Trust Co. in New York. ``This is leading to a reassessment of the
dollar.''
   Prospects of a peaceful world apparently were too much for the
gold market, however, and traders dumped bullion aggressively. Gold
historically has been considered a safe-haven investment during
times of international tension. Prices dropped by as much as $4 an
ounce in New York to the $422.50 level.
   In the bond market prices retreated, largely because of traders
taking profits from the rally on Tuesday, when speculation about
Gorbachev's peace speech incited the biggest rally in three months.
   The Treasury's closely watched 30-year bond lost ] point, or
about $3.75 for every $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves
inversely to price and often indicates broader interest rate trends,
rose to 8.97 percent from 8.92 percent late Tuesday.
   On Wall Street the Dow Jones industrial average, which shot up
more than 25 points Tuesday in a spillover from the bond market
rally, added 4.27 points to close at 2,153.63, reflecting a muted
reaction to Gorbachev's speech.
   In other economic news Wednesday, the Federal Reserve said
Americans took out $3.56 billion more in consumer debt than they
paid off in October, reflecting what some analysts called a rebound
in consumer spending, which accounts for two-thirds of overall
economic activity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881208-0272 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 0207EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     12-08 0158</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0164</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Concern about crude oil supplies has helped push
energy futures mostly higher.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the January contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, settled
28 cents higher Wednesday at $15.74 a barrel, after rising 12 cents
on Tuesday. Other contract months also gained ground.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange
Wednesday, the January contract for wholesale home heating oil
closed 0.29 cent higher at 48.89 cents a gallon. The contract had
risen 0.24 cent in Tuesday's session.
   But January unleaded gasoline, which lost 0.09 cent on Tuesday,
fell another 0.59 cent to 43.76 cents Wednesday.
   William Byers, senior energy analyst for Bear, Stearns & Co.,
attributed the higher prices to lower-than-expected crude oil supply
figures released late Tuesday in the American Petroleum Institute's
weekly report.
   ``The drop in crude stocks was more than expected,'' Byers said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881208-0273 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 0143EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Fed-Currency Bjt   12-08 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fed-Currency, Bjt,0679</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fed Reports Active Intervention During August-October Period</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States spent more than $2 billion to
hold down the dollar's value in foreign-exchange trading during
August and September, but it started to support the currency the
following month, a Federal Reserve report shows.
   The latest quarterly foreign-exchange report issued Wednesday by
the Federal Reserve Bank of New York said the Fed and the Treasury
Department sold $2.136 billion for the equivalent West German marks
several times between Aug. 5 and Sept. 26.
   On Oct. 31 both agencies sold $200 million in Japanese yen to buy
dollars, the report said.
   Sam Y. Cross, an executive vice president of the New York Fed,
said the operations were designed to maintain market stability and
generally were ``coordinated'' among the central banks of the
so-called Group of Seven nations. Besides the United States, the G-7
includes Japan, Britain, West Germany, France, Italy and Canada.
   The G-7 has agreed to work together to stabilize the currency
markets, and reinforced those efforts at a special meeting in late
September.
   ``Some of them (intervention operations) ... occurred at the same
time,'' but other times the U.S. government acted alone after
notifying its major trading partners, Cross told a news briefing
Wednesday.
   Currency traders are often keenly aware of the activities of
central banks in the open markets. The Fed's policy, however, is to
comment only well after the fact.
   Cross declined to specify the exact amount of the foreign banks'
intervention during the August-October period, saying it was up to
them to do so.
   The dollar-selling operations by the Fed and the Treasury came as
the U.S. currency was reaching its peak for the year, especially
against the mark, where it traded at a high of 1.9230 marks on Aug.
22. The dollar also was close to the 135-yen level during that time.
   Still, the dollar ended the August-October period 5.5 percent
lower in value against the yen and 5 percent lower against the mark,
compared with the beginning of the period, as sentiment toward the
currency changed course, according to the New York Fed. Lately it
has been trading in the markets at around 1.75 marks and 122 yen.
   The dollar's strength had come amid signs of an improving U.S.
trade deficit, a growing economy and rising interest rates,
particularly in the early weeks of the Fed's latest reporting period.
   On Aug. 9, the Fed signaled its desire to cool down the economy
and prevent inflation from accelerating by raising its discount
rate, or the interest charged on loans to member banks.
   The heaviest intervention occurred between Aug. 5 and Aug. 23,
when the government bought $1.806 billion worth of marks, the Fed
report said. The government also bought $230 million of marks
between Sept. 14 and Sept. 22, and $100 million of marks on Sept.
26, it said.
   The Oct. 30 purchase of $200 million with yen was the only effort
during the period to support the dollar, the report said.
   In the previous three-month period, from May to June, U.S.
intervention totaled $2.93 billion, solely through the sale of marks
to resist upward pressure on the dollar.
   Cross said sentiment toward the dollar had turned decidedly
bearish in October, after central banks overseas started raising
their interest rates and as the U.S. economy was showing signs of
slowing down. Falling oil prices also helped bring interest rates
down in the United States.
   The dollar reached its highest point of the decade in February
1985. It declined slightly until September 1985, when G-7 leaders
agreed to lower its value to help narrow the U.S. trade gap and
stave off protectionist sentiment in Congress.
   The dollar touched bottom in the final days of 1987 before
rebounding sharply at the beginning of 1988. It is now trading in a
fairly narrow range.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881208-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 0143EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Drexel Bjt   12-08 0687</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drexel, Bjt,0712</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senior Trader Strikes Deal; Milken Said Determined Not to
Capitulate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. trader has
decided to cooperate in the government's criminal fraud probe of the
Wall Street giant and its high-yield bond financier Michael Milken,
but the impact of the defection is unclear and Milken remains
determined to prove his innocence in court.
   Sources familiar with the Drexel case said Wednesday that defense
lawyers had expected the plea bargain by Cary Maultasch, a trader
who had been under especially heavy pressure by federal prosecutors
to capitulate because he had been threatened with numerous
indictments.
   The sources, who spoke on condition they not be identified, also
said Milken was adamant about exonerating himself of any wrongdoing,
contradicting press accounts that suggested he had wavered and even
entered into preliminary discussions with prosecutors about a
possible guilty plea.
   The defense was further said to believe Maultasch's disclosures
would not substantially damage Drexel or Milken, who have been under
intense investigation for more than two years but have maintained
they are innocent.
   News of the Maultasch defection coincided with rampant
speculation that a decisive turning point was near in the protracted
legal travails of Drexel, one of the nation's leading investment
firms and a pioneer in the market for high-yield, high-risk
securities commonly called ``junk bonds.''
   Contrary to Milken's position, Drexel has expressed interest in
reaching a settlement with the government over as-yet unfiled
criminal securities fraud charges, although any settlement would
almost certainly involve a guilty plea and a heavy fine, possibly in
the hundreds of millions of dollars.
   Negotiations have taken place, but one source said both sides
remained substantially far apart as of Wednesday.
   It was unclear what new evidence could be provided by Maultasch,
who struck a deal Tuesday with the Manhattan U.S. attorney's office
and the Securities and Exchange Commission for his cooperation. In
exchange, it is expected that he will not face prosecution on any
serious charges.
   SEC aides and Bruce Baird, the assistant U.S. attorney for
securities and commodities fraud, would not comment on the Maultasch
development in accordance with their policy of official silence on
pending investigations.
   Aubrey Harwell, a Maultasch attorney, was out of his office and
did not return telephone calls for comment. Drexel spokesman Steven
Anreder declined to comment.
   Drexel, Milken, Maultasch and two other senior aides at the firm
were accused by the SEC in a civil complaint filed three months ago
of conspiring with now-imprisoned speculator Ivan F. Boesky to
commit a litany of frauds ranging from insider trading to stock
manipulation.
   A Manhattan federal grand jury has been expected to indict the
defendants on criminal charges that would likely include
racketeering, which carries enormous penalties.
   Some sources said that indictment was nearly filed last week but
prosecutors delayed it, perhaps as a pressure tactic to extract
guilty pleas from the defendants.
   An underlying problem facing prosecutors has been their one key
witness, Boesky, an admitted doublecrosser and liar who settled the
biggest insider trading case in history by paying the SEC a record
$100 million fine in 1986.
   Without additional witnesses to corroborate Boesky's claims, the
government's case faces serious attack by the Drexel-Milken defense
team, comprised of some of the best-paid legal talent in the country.
   On its surface, the Maultasch defection was seen by some
attorneys as possibly bolstering the government's case and
encouraging others threatened with indictment to come forth to
cooperate.
   But others questioned why the government waited so long to strike
a deal with Maultasch, suggesting it was largely a pressure device
that was deliberately leaked to the press to amplify its effect.
   Federal prosecutors also have been seeking cooperation for the
Drexel investigation from partners in a much smaller firm, Princeton
Newport Partners, who were indicted on tax fraud and racketeering
charges in August.
   Lawyers for the Princeton Newport defendants announced Wednesday
that the partnership had been dissolved, blaming the move on the
uncertainties raised by what they called prosecutor threats to file
additional charges.
   Baird declined to comment on their accusation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881208-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 0140EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CarInsurance Bjt   12-08 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Car Insurance, Bjt,0621</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two U.S. Cars Top List, But Americans Dominate Low End</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTHBROOK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A full-size luxury Ford sedan had the
lowest insurance rates while two flashy sports coupes by General
Motors Corp. had the highest on Allstate Insurance Co.'s annual list.
   Ford's LTD Crown Victoria costs 35 percent to 50 percent less to
insure than the standard rate, while Chevy's Camaro IROC-Z28 and the
Pontiac Firebird TransAm are being charged 100 percent to 140
percent higher than standard rate levels for collision and
comprehensive coverages, Allstate said.
   The cars are among the automobiles on Allstate's list of
insurance rates for 1987 and 1988 models of 119 foreign and domestic
cars.
   ``One of the things that we have found is that American-made cars
seem to be getting better treatment than foreign cars,'' Allstate
Vice President Mike LaMonica said Wednesday, attributing the
difference to the cost of repair and parts, and to theft records.
   Forty-three of the 49 cars being charged 10 percent to 40 percent
less than standard rates were domestic models.
   Allstate rated the Porsche 944 model and Chrysler's Conquest as
the second-most expensive to insure, charging drivers of those cars
insurance rates 60 percent to 100 percent higher than standard rates.
   The 1988 rating guide is based on the company's own loss
experience for the collision and comprehensive portions of its auto
policies, the Northbrook-based insurer said.
   The cost of insuring a particular model is generally based on its
price when new, LaMonica said.
   But the ``loss experience,'' or the amount Allstate has paid out
in claims for that model over time, affects the insurance rate, he
said.
   In its survey, Allstate assigned each car a standard rate based
on the car's price when new, and a hypothetical suburban Chicago
residence for the driver.
   The standard annual rate for the LTD Crown Victoria had been
$550, but was reduced to $360 based on claims filed with Allstate
for that model, LaMonica said.
   The TransAm initially was given a standard rate of $550, but that
rose to $1,296 based on Allstate's claim record for the car, he said.
   Pontiac spokesman Bill O'Neill blamed the TransAm's high
insurance costs on the car's theft rate and its popularity with
younger, mostly male drivers.
   ``The Firebird series, especially the TransAm has ... among the
highest theft rates in the country,'' he said in a telephone
interview.
   ``It is a performance-oriented machine ... this is prime pickings
for people who like to steal automobiles,'' O'Neill said.
   But he said the sports car's theft rate has dropped by about 50
percent since last year, when the automaker began equipping each car
with a special ignition key. Without the key, the car won't start
for three minutes _ about the time it takes to steal a car.
   Susan Kane, a spokeswoman for Chevrolet, said all 1989 Camaros
would also be equipped with the ``Pass Key,'' to help eliminate
theft problems, and possibly to lower insurance rates for the sports
car.
   In releasing its survey, Allstate denied claims by critics who
say insurance companies aren't doing enough to keep their prices
down.
   ``Those critics are ignoring the fact that our research into
repairability has led to our drive for stronger bumpers and cars
that are easier and cheaper to repair,'' said Ray Kiefer, president
of Allstate's Personal Property and Casualty unit. ``We share that
information with auto manufacturers.''
   LaMonica said Allstate planned to give its rate results to
manufacturers ``to encourage them to make better designs'' and to
``give customers an opportunity save insurance dollars.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881208-0276 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 0212EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ConsumerCredit     12-08 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Consumer Credit,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consumers Boost Debt by $3.5 Billion in October</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reflecting a rebound in consumer spending,
Americans took out $3.56 billion more in consumer debt than they
paid off in October, the government has reported.
   The Federal Reserve said Wednesday that the October increase
followed a tiny $2 million rise in debt during September, the
smallest change in six years. Consumer credit fell by $81 million in
October 1982 at the bottom of the last recession.
   The October advance, which translated into credit growth at an
annual rate of 6.5 percent, was still down from the 8.75 percent
annual rate of growth recorded over the first nine months of the
year.
   Still, analysts said they believed consumer spending was
strengthening after a period of sluggishness. They noted that retail
sales shot up 0.9 percent in October, the biggest gain in seven
months.
   ``The latest numbers suggest that consumers are a little more
optimistic about buying,'' said Michael Evans, head of a Washington
consulting firm. ``I think they are not fighting higher prices as
much as they had in the past.''
   Consumer spending accounts for two-thirds of overall economic
activity. Newfound strength in the consumer sector has prompted some
analysts to boost their projections for growth in the current
October-December quarter.
   The $2 million advance for September represented a sharp revision
from the original report a month ago that had put the rise in
consumer debt at $1.88 billion. Fed officials said new data showing
weaker activity in car sales accounted for much of the change.
   The October increase was the strongest since a $5.32 billion rise
in August.
   Auto loans rose by $1.32 billion in October after falling by $779
million in September. The poor showing in September was blamed on an
absence of sales incentive programs that have boosted demand at the
end of previous model years.
   The category that includes credit card debt rose by $2.17
billion, up from a $1.1 billion September increase.
   Bank and credit union loans not secured by real estate edged up
by $178 million in October. They had declined by $158 million in
September.
   Loans for mobile homes fell for the second straight month,
declining by $101 million after a drop of $169 million in September.
   The various changes left total consumer debt at a seasonally
adjusted $656.88 billion in October. Total consumer debt was 8.2
percent higher than a year earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881208-0277 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 0214EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-S&LActivity     12-08 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-S&L Activity,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>S&L Capital Up for Third Straight Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Continued efforts by government regulators to
close or rescue failed institutions brought an increase in savings
and loan industry capital in October for the third consecutive
month, the government has reported.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board said Wednesday that capital _
representing the difference between loans and other assets and
savers' deposits and other liabilities _ edged up by $507 million in
October following advances of $2.47 billion September and $6.11
bilion in August.
   Through the first 10 months of the year, S&L capital has risen by
$2.94 billion, compared with a loss of $3.07 billion in the same
period of 1987.
   The bank board began increasing the pace of S&L rescues in
mid-August. Rescues in effect wipe out the red ink of the failed
institutions by transferring it to the Federal Savings and Loan
Insurance Corp., the agency that insures deposits up to $100,000.
   The agency has dealt with more than 150 troubled institutions so
far this year.
   Meanwhile, deposits increased by $390 million in October,
representing the first net increase in deposits since April.
   The October net increase in deposits represented a sharp contrast
to net withdrawals of $2 billion in September. A year earlier, there
was a much larger deposit increase of $6.17 billion, when investors
sought a safe haven for their money after the October 1987 stock
market crash.
   The assets of federally insured S&Ls, made up primarily of loans,
grew at an annual rate of 9.5 percent in October, down from an 11
percent growth rate in September.
   Abouth three-fourths of the asset growth in October reflected a
$7.8 billion increase in mortgage holdings, including purchases of
mortgage-backed securities. This followed a September increase of
$4.7 billion.
</TEXT>
