<2ND_LINE>PM-Princeton Newport,0160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Securities Firm To Liquidate Amid Racketeering Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The securities firm Princeton-Newport
Partners says it plans to liquidate amid government racketeering
charges.
   The company said Wednesday that business has been severely hurt
after five of its partners were indicted in August in connection
with an alleged tax-fraud scheme. A former trader from Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc. also was named in the government suit.
   The case marks the first time that securities executives have
been charged under the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt
Organizations law, known as RICO.
   ``The government has succeeded in destroying Princeton-Newport,''
said Paul Grand, a New York attorney for one of the indicted
officials.
   On Monday many of the firm's investors withdrew their capital.
   The indictment accuses the six of a multimillion-dollar mail and
wire fraud conspiracy to make false stock trades to create phony
long-term capital gains and short-term capital losses for
Princeton-Newport.
