<2ND_LINE>BC-Taiwan-Economy,0132</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taiwan Projects 7 Percent Economic Growth in 1989</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taiwan's economy is expected to expand by 7
percent in 1989, roughly the same as this year's growth, the
government said Thursday.
   The rate would be well below the 11 percent growth recorded in
1987.
   Vincent Siew, vice chairman of the Council for Economic Planning
and Development, said inflation could pose a serious problem next
year and that the United States was expected to continue pressuring
Taiwan to reduce its massive trade surplus.
   Under the 1989 economic plan, Taiwan's total trade surplus next
year is expected to fall to $10 billion from the $11.9 billion
projected for this year, he said. Taiwan had a record trade surplus
of $19 billion in 1987.
