<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Pepperell-Farley     12-08 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pepperell-Farley,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farley Extends Bid for Pepperell</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farley Inc. today extended for a third time its
$1.4 billion unsolicited tender offer for Georgia-based textiles
maker West Point-Pepperell Inc., this time to midnight EST next
Wednesday.
   The $48-a-share offer was to expire at midnight Wednesday of this
week.
   Farley, a Chicago-based maker of Fruit of the Loom underwear and
several other well-known clothing brands, said 13.7 million shares
of Pepperell's common stock had been tendered by stockholders.
   Those shares, together with the shares already owned by Farley,
represent about 56.3 percent of Pepperell's common shares, Farley
said.
   Farley's offer is contingent on getting Pepperell's ``poison
pill'' shareholder rights plan overturned in court. The 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta has scheduled a hearing on the
matter for the week of Jan. 9.
   Farley Chairman William Farley said today he is ``confident of a
successful conclusion'' to his bid for Pepperell, which is based in
West Point, Ga., and whose products include Gold Toe socks.
   On Monday, Pepperell said it was offering early retirement to
more than 800 employees. On Wednesday, the company said it had
notified about 400 employees of its Cluett, Peabody & Co. plant in
Troy, N.Y., that it may shut down that operation.
   Farley contrasted those cutbacks with its own announcement that
it has created 9,000 jobs at Fruit of the Loom since it acquired the
company in 1985.
   ``Our emphasis at Fruit of the Loom is on job creation,'' the
company said today. ``We believe Pepperell and Fruit of the Loom
would make a great team and that, working together, we would be
better able to meet the challenges of an increasingly competitive
industry and create more jobs.''
   Pepperell officials have disputed Farley's stated intentions,
underscoring a statement by Farley in a Securities and Exchange
Commission filing that he might consider selling some Pepperell
divisions if he succeeds in acquiring the company.
</TEXT>
