<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Summit-TradeShow 1stLd-Writethru   12-08 0869</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Trade Show, 1st Ld-Writethru,0894</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Come to New York on Capitalist Mission</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with show opening, quotes, date
of closing; Picks up 6th graf, ``I think ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From vodka to rifles to tractors to furs, the
fruits of the Soviet economy were displayed today in an
unprecedented trade show left somewhat less glittering by the
absence of its chief sponsor, Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   The Soviet leader, who was to open the exhibit, decided instead
to cut short his New York visit and fly back to Moscow today because
of an earthquake that devastated three southern Soviet republics,
Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze said at a news conference
late Wednesday.
   Viktor Kamentsev, a deputy Soviet premier, opened the show along
with C. William Verity, the U.S. secretary of commerce.
   Kamentsev urged a lowering of trade barriers between the United
States and the Soviet Union and said his country was eager to
increase its exports here. He then rushed from the hall to catch a
plane to Moscow.
   Verity, congratulating the Soviets for Gorbachev's
``electrifying'' United Nations speech, also hailed the improvement
in trade between the two nations.
   ``We believe this is an important step in building long-term,
mutually beneficial, non-strategic trade between the United States
and the Soviet Union,'' Verity said.
   Despite Gorbachev's no-show, Soviet sponsors hope the show _ an
outgrowth of his policy of perestroika, or restructuring _ will mark
a major turning point in trade relations between the world's two
largest economies. The show is scheduled to end Dec. 20.
   By air and by sea, the Soviets have shipped hundreds of tons of
products to the Jacob K. Javits Convention Center in hopes of luring
U.S. dollars.
   ``I think the Soviets are saying that they are looking at the
Americans as a most-favored-nation trading partner,'' said David
Wolstenholme, whose American marketing firm has spent more than a
year putting together the show. ``You really only do this to someone
you want to impress.''
   But some U.S. trade experts say the Soviet Union is likely to
remain among the most minor of American trading partners, in part
because the Soviets lack the products that Americans want and the
money to buy what Americans have.
   ``I do not believe that significant sales will result,'' said Val
Zabijaka, an economist on the Soviet desk at the U.S. Commerce
Department. ``I may be proven wrong.''
   By Wolstenholme's reckoning, the Soviets are spending more than
$2 million to prove the nay sayers wrong, including $700,000 in
advertising for the show.
   ``We consider it to be very important,'' said Bagrat Aroutiounov,
the Soviet director of overseas exhibitions. He said the event is
the first ``pure commercial'' trade show ever mounted by the Soviet
Union in this country.
   Previous trade shows had primarily political aims, Aroutiounov
said, and were intended to show off the advantages of a
state-controlled economy. This year's show has a single, thoroughly
capitalist goal: profit.
   Furthermore, Aroutiounov said, this will be the first time that a
Soviet trade fair has been financed by the participants _
cooperatives, foreign trade organizations and enterprises _ and not
the government.
   The show, officially titled the Soviet Export Goods Exhibition,
initially was scheduled to begin Dec. 14, but was hastily
rescheduled to Dec. 8 to coincide with Gorbachev's visit to New York.
   Forty-eight participants will display approximately 4,500
products, including tractors, toys, computer programs, jewelry,
cars, bicycles, vodka and hunting rifles. The Soviet House of
Fashion Design will present ``fabulous Russian furs,'' as well as
``jackets and suits inspired by the Soviet military uniform.''
   In addition, some U.S. companies have rented booths to show off
the benefits of their business ties with the Soviet Union. The
Soviets are looking not only for buyers, Wolstenholme said, but for
American companies willing to take part in joint business ventures.
   ``I think Mr. Gorbachev himself said that the only limit is the
creativity of the American businessman,'' he said.
   But other observers see tougher barriers to improvements in
U.S.-Soviet trade. One limit is the Soviet shortage of hard currency.
   Since the ruble cannot be converted into Western currencies, the
Soviets must pay for American goods and services with gold or
Western currency. Given the Soviets' trade imbalance with the West,
the policy has built-in limitations.
   Some have speculated that Soviet economists would propose plans
at the fair for making the ruble convertible. Aroutiounov said he
expected the process would take ``two or three years, maybe longer.''
   But U.S. officials scoff at such suggestions. ``You probably
believe in Santa Claus, too,'' Zabijaka said in reference to the
Soviet proposals.
   According to Commerce Department figures, the Soviet Union
exported $500 million worth of products to the United States last
year and imported $1.5 billion worth of American goods, including
$900 million worth of grain.
   That represents a sharp drop from the peak year of
Soviet-American trade, 1979, when the Soviets imported $3.6 billion
in U.S. goods and exported $900 million to the U.S.
   Those levels dropped sharply when the U.S. imposed a limited
grain embargo in the wake of the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan and
sharply reduced purchases of Soviet goods.
</TEXT>
