<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Higher On Soviet Nuclear Fears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened sharply higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade on rumors, later denied, that
the devastating earthquake in Soviet Armenia had damaged two nuclear
power plants.
   ``The rumors of nuclear involvement have now largely been
discounted and the market is coming back to realize that although
the loss of life is tragic, the possibility of agricultural damage
is pretty remote,'' said Richard Feltes, director of commodities
research with Refco Inc., a large, Chicago-based futures brokerage
house.
   Soybean futures also were supported by reports that the South
American soybean belt had received less rain overnight than traders
had expected, analysts said.
   Wheat futures got an additional boost from the Agriculture
Department's announcement late Wednesday that it had targeted China
for 1 million metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices.
   In early trading, wheat was 3\ cents to 4 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.27 a bushel; corn was 1\
cents to 4} cents higher with December at $2.60 a bushel; oats were
2{ cents to 4 cents higher with March at $2.14 a bushel; soybeans
were 8 cents to 11 cents higher with January at $7.79 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .15 cent to .40 cent lower with December at
71.40 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .12 cent to .38 cent lower
with January at 82.05 cents a pound; hogs were unchanged to .25 cent
lower with December at 40.87 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.47 cent lower to .18 cent higher with February at 42.57 cents a
pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Wednesday.
