<2ND_LINE>BC-Kraft,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philip Morris Completes Acquisition of Kraft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philip Morris Cos. Inc. said Thursday it
completed its $12.9 billion acquisition of Kraft Inc. in a deal that
makes the food and tobacco giant the world's largest consumer
products company.
   The size of the buyout ranks only behind Chevron Corp.'s $13.4
billion acquisition of Gulf Oil Corp. in 1984 and RJR Nabisco Inc.'s
impending $24.5 billion purchase by the investment firm Kolhlberg
Kravis Roberts & Co.
   Philip Morris said its buyout of Kraft was completed on
Wednesday, five days after the closing of its $106-a-share tender
offer under which Kraft shareholders tendered more than 98 percent
of the company's outstanding shares.
   As a result of the transaction, Kraft shares that were not
tendered under terms of the offer were converted into the right to
receive $106 in cash.
   Philip Morris, whose products include Marlboro cigarettes, Miller
beer, Maxwell House coffee, Jell-O desserts and Post cereals, will
be boosting its revenue by about a third as a result of the deal,
vaulting ahead of Unilever NV as the world's biggest consumer
products concern. Philip Morris had $27.7 billion in revenue in
1987, and Unilever had nearly $31 billion in sales.
   Kraft, based in Glenview, Ill., had revenue of about $9.9 billion
in 1987 and makes products such as Miracle Whip salad dressing,
Velveeta cheese, Parkay margarine and Breyers ice cream.
   Kraft stock was trading at $60.12{ a share when Philip Morris
launched an unsolicited tender offer at $90 a share in mid-October.
Kraft management rejected the offer as inadquate and proposed a
recpaitalization, but by the end of the month had agreed on the
takeover at $106 a share.
</TEXT>
