<HEAD>Defense Lawyer Says Minkow Case Is A Government Cover up</HEAD>
<HEAD>lcdesr1jcr2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Minkow was portrayed as a ``big
spender'' by a prosecutor who said the onetime carpet-cleaning king
was motivated to defraud investors of millions of dollars not by
threats but by his desire to live the good life.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney James Asperger, during his rebuttal
arguments Wednesday, portrayed Minkow as someone who committed fraud
for his own personal gain.
   ``He loved the high life. He was motivated not by threats. He was
motivated by his own personal desires,'' said Asperger. ``Barry
Minkow was doing it for himself.''
   Minkow, on trial on fraud charges, has testified that he bilked
investors out of millions of dollars but did so only because
mobsters had taken over his ZZZZ Best carpet-cleaning company and
were threatening his life.
   The jury was scheduled to receive instructions today, beginning
deliberations afterward.
   Minkow is charged with 57 counts of securities, credit-card and
mail fraud. The government contends major banks and securities firms
lost millions of dollars along with individual investors as a result
of Minkow's alleged scheme.
   During his closing arguments earlier Wednesday, Minkow's attorney
accused the government of engineering a massive cover-up of its
failure to short circuit the $15 million ZZZZ Best stock fraud.
   Attorney David Kenner said the FBI improperly dropped a probe of
Minkow's possible mob victimization in 1986 before his company hit
Wall Street.
   ``I think the government made a mistake,'' said Kenner. ``They
didn't do anything.''
   Minkow, who launched his carpet-cleaning business at 16 in his
parents' garage, became familiar to millions of Californians through
his television ads and talk show appearances.
   But he admitted during the four-month trial that his business was
``86 percent fraud.'' He had told investors that ZZZZ Best was
making a fortune restoring fire and water damaged buildings when no
such jobs existed.
</TEXT>
