<HEAD>Britain Liquor Company Posts 24 Percent Profit Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Metropolitan PLC said Thursday its profit
rose 52 percent in its latest fiscal year, boosted by gains in its
liquor, food and retailing businesses.
   Grand Met, which has launched a hostile $5.23 billion takeover
bid for U.S.-based Pillsbury Co., said net profit in the year ended
Sept. 30 rose to 701.7 million pounds, or $1.3 billion, after an
extraordinary gain of 289.7 million pounds, or $536 million from
business disposals.
   A year earlier, an extraordinary gain of 127.8 million pounds, or
$236 million, boosted net profit to 461 million pounds, or $853
million.
   Grand Met said its revenue rose 5.6 percent to 6.03 billion
pounds, or $11.2 billion from 5.71 billion pounds, or about $10.6
billion.
   Grand Met's liquor division continued to be the major earner,
with operating profit up 23 percent at 316 million pounds,or $585
million.
   Food businesses had operating profit of 84 million pounds, or
$155 million, up 21.7 percent, while retailing showed operating
profit of 179 million pounds, or $331 million, an 11.9-percent gain.
   Grand Met said its sale of the Inter-Continental hotel chain to
Seibu Saison Group of Japan, due to be completed Dec. 15, will
realize 1.2 billion pounds, or $2.2 billion.
   Grand Met didn't break out quarterly or half-year results. It is
not required to under British law.
