<HEAD>Europeans Get Peek at New English-Language Daily</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special edition of The European was distributed
Thursday, giving Europe its first look at the English-language daily
by British publisher Robert Maxwell.
   The sample issue was distributed free in major cities. It will
hit newsstands on May 9, 1989, and cover news, finance, sports and
lifestyle from major European points.
   The paper resembles USA Today, also sold in Europe. There were
big color photos _ two on the front page alone along with bold
headlines, captions, cartoons and a color weather map on the back
page.
   Maxwell said it cost $1.4 million to prepare, print and
distribute 7 million sample copies in 20 European cities.
   Stories in the sample edition honored Jean Monnet, the founding
father of the European Community. Another recounted an outlandish
Amsterdam wedding in which the bride carried a bouquet of plastic
tulips adorned with lights.
   On a ``News from Home'' page, the paper also carried stories
written in French, Dutch, Spanish, Italian, German, Portugese, Greek
and Danish.
   The European will cost about 85 cents and have a circulation of
550,000 reaching 2 million readers.
