<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writehthru   12-08 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writehthru,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Off 13.8 Points</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with closing prices</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the London Stock Exchange closed
down but higher than their session lows on Thursday.
   Trading was marked by a general lack of buying interest and
concern about continuing over-capacity in the British securities
markets.
   Trading volume was concentrated in a few blue chip stocks, with
the British retailing sector attracting some of the heaviest
turnover.
   But dealers said the market shook off its brief euphoria over
Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev's troop reduction proposals on
Wednesday and focused once again on the uncertain prospects for the
British economy.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed 13.8
points, or 0.8 percent, lower at 1,757.9, above the day's low of
19.7 points off. The session peak was 3.1 points down.
   The Financial Times 30-share index closed 13.9 points lower at
1,437.1.
   Volume was a moderate 543.8 million shares, up from 490.1 million
shares a day earlier.
   Dealers said the market drifted lower for much of the day as
institutional investors again held back from buying stock at the
market's lower levels. Prices were also affected by concern that
more brokerage firms will cut back their British operations
following Morgan Grenfell Group PLC's decision earlier this week to
withdraw from market making in equities and government bonds.
   The Financial Times 500-share index fell 9.49 points to close at
987.80.
</TEXT>
