<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Interco-ShoeFactories     12-08 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Interco-Shoe Factories,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interco Announces Two Shoe Factory Closings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interco Inc. announced Thursday that as part of
its corporate restructuring plan, the Florsheim Shoe Co. division
will close plants in Paducah, Ky., and Hermann, Mo.
   The company said the Paducah plant will close Feb. 10, and the
Hermann plant will close Feb. 24.
   The moves will result in direct cost savings of more than $2
million annually, Interco said. A total of 650 jobs will be
affected, a spokesman said, as production from the plants is
reassigned to Florsheim's remaining four domestic plants.
   The restructuring was made necessary to head off a $2.7 billion
hostile takeover of Interco by Cardinal Acquisition Corp., headed by
brothers Steven M. and Mitchell P. Rales of Washington, D.C.
   No further plant closings in the Florsheim division are
anticipated, Interco said.
   ``The closings reflect our commitment to implement as soon a
practicable our recapitalization and restructuring plan,'' said
Interco.
   As previously announced, the plan calls for annual cost savings
totaling $75 million, the sale of the Apparel Manufacturing Group,
Ethan Allen Inc. and other assets.
</TEXT>
