<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ResearchSpending     12-08 0165</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Research Spending,0170</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release 6:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<HEAD>Flat Research and Development Spending Forecast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Research and development spending by industry,
government, universities and non-profit organizations will increase
4.6 percent next year, but inflation will account for most of the
rise, a magazine predicted Thursday.
   Research & Development magazine projected in its January issue
that $130.8 billion will spent on research next year, compared to an
estimated $125 billion for 1988.
   ``We expect that research and develepment spending will be flat
in constant dollars in 1989,'' said Timothy Kelly, the magazine's
publisher.
   The magazine attributed the leveling off to slow corporate
growth, a business climate focusing on short-term profits, a wave of
mergers and acquisitions, and expectations of smaller government
outlays because of needs to reduce the deficit.
   The 1988 spending level is about $7 billion lower than expected
because of cuts in government and private financing, the magazine
said. The government accounts for about half of the nation's
research spending.
</TEXT>
