<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   12-08 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Export Hopes Boost Wheat Futures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices closed substantially higher
Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade on talk that China was set to
bid for 400,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices,
analysts said.
   Soybean and oat futures also closed higher while corn was
narrowly mixed.
   The Agriculture Department announced late Wednesday that it had
targeted the Chinese for 1 million metric tons of wheat under the
Export Enhancement Program, and ``the trade talk is that they are
bidding for wheat right now,'' said Ted Mao, a grain specialist with
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Grain and soybean futures had opened sharply higher on fears that
Wednesday's devastating earthquake in Soviet Armenia had damaged two
nuclear power plants in the area, but those gains were quickly pared.
   ``The markets managed to weed out what appears to be the truth,
which is that the reactors are operating without any difficulty,''
Mao said.
   At the close, wheat was 5 cents to 6\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.29\ a bushel; corn was 1{
cents lower to 1\ cents higher with December at $2.56{ a bushel;
oats were 1{ cents to 4 cents higher with December at $2.03 a
bushel; soybeans were 2} cents to 6\ cents higher with January at
$7.73 a bushel.
</TEXT>
