<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 1636EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-ChristmasSales Bjt   12-08 0813</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Christmas Sales, Bjt,0842</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Christmas Season Generally Proceeding Well</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1988 Christmas shopping season is off to a
modestly good start, although retailers in some parts of the country
report warmer weather has put a damper on their holiday spirits.
   ``We're doing fine _ right on target,'' Miraed Smith, a
spokeswoman at Bloomingdale's flagship store in Manhattan, said
Thursday.
   Frank DeLuca, vice president of I.J. Fox, a Boston furrier, said
his company has had steady, if not spectacular, sales increases
since Thanksgiving.
   ``It looks solid and that's fine by me,'' he said. ``Everybody
likes growth, but a nice steady growth to me is better than wild
swings and roller-coaster rides.''
   At Marshall Field's, the Chicago-based department store, ``At
lunchtime, especially in the downtown store, you see so many people
with big boxes and bags that it's difficult to weave your way
through the aisles,'' said spokeswoman Hillary Rosenfeld.
   Field's expected to meet or exceed its target of a seasonal sales
increase in the ``high single digits,'' Ms. Rosenfeld said, adding,
``Each day's sales definitely play right into that plan, at least
reaching that goal.''
   Securities analysts who track the industry said the first two
weeks of the season have been good, and they are optimistic
retailers will have moderately strong increases from the dismal
performance of Christmas 1987.
   ``So far, it looks positive, but the proof of the pudding is the
last 10 days'' when most shoppers are expected to make their
purchases, said Monroe Greenstein, an analyst with Bear, Stearns &
Co.
   ``For most retailers, Christmas sales are slightly above plan,''
said Walter Loeb, an analyst with Morgan Stanley & Co. Inc.
   Loeb said the occurrence of Hanukkah at the beginning of December
this year ``shifted some shopping to the early part of the month,''
but that sales of Christmas gifts also were proceeding well.
   ``The rest of the year will be quite good,'' Loeb predicted.
   Retailers across the country have gone into this Christmas season
with caution and lowered expectations because of a retail sales
slump that is nearly two years old. Holiday sales last year were
disappointing, and many retailers slashed prices to bring customers
into the stores.
   This Christmas, there are ``sale'' signs up in many stores, but
they are not as widespread as they were a year ago, Greenstein said.
   The analysts said sales will get a boost this season since
calendar shifts have created two more shopping days than there were
in 1987.
   The fact that Christmas falls on Sunday this year is another help.
   ``It gives you that major Saturday on Christmas Eve, which is
going to be gangbusters,'' said Tom McCracken, vice president for
sales at Crowley Milner & Co., which operates 10 department stores
in Michigan.
   Sales have slowed in areas such as the Northeast because of
unseasonably warm weather, said Jeffrey Feiner, an analyst with
Merrill Lynch & Co.
   Consumers don't feel in the mood to shop for Christmas when it's
warm, and in Texas, where temperatures also have been high,
retailers are disappointed by lower-than-expected sales.
   ``The Thanksgiving weekend was not very good for us,'' said Scott
Glass, president and chief operating officer for Scarbroughs
department stores in Austin. ``We expected the big Christmas rush,
but we did not get it.''
   Dallas-based Neiman Marcus stores also have seen some slow days,
spokeswoman Pat Zajac said.
   ``We went gangbusters on Thanksgiving weekend and we had a good
first week, but we saw a slight slowing trend last weekend,'' Ms.
Zajac said. ``It now seems to be picking up again, so we think it
looks good for us.''
   However, the Texas retailers said an early trend toward more
expensive items seems to be holding firm. Fine jewelry, home
decorator items and other upscale gifts are doing well.
   At Bloomingdale's, $129 cashmere sweaters are big sellers, and so
are $300 separates by designer Donna Karan, Ms. Smith said. But $25
watches and $40 bathrobes are also popular, she said.
   At the nation's largest discount retailer, K mart Corp.,
``seasonal items such as decorations and apparel are selling well,
but there is no one hot item,'' said vice president for marketing
Michael Wellman.
   K mart's sales across the country slightly exceeded expectations
in the first week after Thanksgiving but were off the mark somewhat
this week, Wellman said.
   ``If you put the two together we're about on track with our
expected 6 percent increase,'' he said.
   ``This is not a Christmas that will go down in the history books,
but we didn't expect it to be,'' Wellman said.
   At Crowley Milner in Michigan, ``Things at this time have been
soft for us. We've had some good days and we've had some soft
days,'' said McCracken, the vice president for sales. ``But we feel
good _ we think it's going to be there,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
