<DOCNO> AP881208-0309 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 1652EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Summit-TradeShow Bjt   12-08 0700</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Trade Show, Bjt,0724</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev a No-Show As Soviets Open Trade Fair</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Their top salesman was missing, but Soviet
entrepreneurs went ahead Thursday with the opening of an
unprecedented trade show intended to usher in a new era of
Soviet-American commerce.
   As fashion models showed off the latest trends from Moscow to the
beat of American pop music, Soviet executives showed off their
wares, including furs, tractors, vodka, books, toys, cars, guns and
caviar.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev had been scheduled to open the
trade fair, which is a showcase for his policy of perestroika, or
economic restructuring. But his appearance was scrubbed when he
decided to return to Moscow early because of a catastrophic
earthquake in Armenia.
   In his place, deputy premier Vladimir M. Kamentsev cut the ribbon
along with U.S. Commerce Secretary C. William Verity.
   Kamentsev hastily delivered a speech calling for the lowering of
trade barriers between the United States and the Soviet Union, then
rushed from the hall to catch a plane to Moscow.
   Verity, congratulating the Soviets for Gorbachev's
``electrifying'' United Nations speech on Wednesday, also hailed the
improvement in trade between the two nations.
   ``We believe this is an important step in building long-term,
mutually beneficial, non-strategic trade between the United States
and the Soviet Union,'' he said.
   The Soviets spent an estimated $2 million on the trade show at
the Jacob K. Javits Convention Center _ one measure of the
importance the Soviet Union places on increased trade with the
United States.
   ``You really only do this to someone you want to impress,'' said
David Wolstenholme, whose American marketing company spent more than
a year putting together the show, which runs through Dec. 20 and is
open to the public.
   The Soviets want to increase exports to the United States to
raise their reserves of hard currency, which they need to purchase
goods from the United States and other Western nations.
   But as Kamentsev suggested and the trade show reveals, U.S. trade
barriers make it extremely difficult for Soviet enterprises to sell
their goods in this country.
   For instance, Vil Rayevskiy, the salesman at a booth offering
Baikal hunting rifles, said the Soviets have had some success
selling the guns to European countries but not to the United States.
   ``The main problem and the main obstacle is your very high duty
for our consumer goods,'' he said.
   According to Rayevskiy, the United States imposes a 60 percent
duty on the guns, whereas gun manufacturers from some countries _
those with most-favored-nation status _ pay only 10 percent.
   ``How can we compete with them?'' he asked. ``Reduce our price to
zero?''
   Asked why he bothered to come to the show, Rayevskiy said, ``We
hope these goods will be interesting to American people and maybe
there will be some changes in this law.''
   Other Soviet enterprises have had more success. Smoky Harrison,
an American spokesman for Soviet-made Belarus tractors, said the
company has been doubling its sales annually since 1985 and expects
to sell more than 2,000 tractors in the United States this year.
   ``It's a basic tractor, a basic tool,'' Harrison said.
   Perestroika also has been profitable for U.S. companies that
operate in the Soviet Union. Perhaps the most successful has been
Pepsi-Cola, which signed a multimillion-dollar agreement Thursday to
expand its trade with the Soviet Union.
   Other Americans, such as Jim Hickman and Peter Buckle of Los
Angeles, have entered joint ventures with Soviet enterprises without
expecting large profits immediately.
   Hickman and Buckle are working with the Symbol Cooperative in
Moscow to market souvenir T-shirts and sweatshirts. Some examples at
the trade fair included a sweatshirt bearing the logo of Moscow
State University and one that says ``Summit '89'' in Russian and
``Gorbachev-Bush'' in English.
   The two said the Russian sweatshirts were not up to the quality
demanded by the U.S. market, and high tariffs made them too
expensive to sell profitably in this country.
   Still, Hickman said, ``the long-term Soviet market'' justifies
their investment.
   ``We're in on the cutting edge of perestroika, which gives one a
lot of opportunities as well as being an exciting time,'' added
Buckle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881208-0310 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 1652EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneyFunds     12-08 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Funds,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Funds Fell $1.22 Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended
Wednesday.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 459 money market mutual
funds fell $1.22 billion in the latest week, the Investment Company
Institute said Thursday.
   The decline to $279.54 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday followed a $1.13 billion decline the previous week, the
Washington-based mutual fund trade group said.
   The funds' assets hit a revised record high of $281.89 billion in
the week ended Nov. 23, 1988.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 231 general purpose funds fell $47.8 million to $89.89
billion, assets of 92 broker-dealer funds rose $145.2 million to
$117.78 billion, and assets of 136 institutional funds fell $1.32
billion to $71.87 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 7.85 percent from 7.75 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose to 7.72 percent from 7.65 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was 35
days, unchanged from the previous week, Donoghue's said.
   The newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of 100 leading
commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and savings banks in
the nation's 10 largest markets showed the effective annual yield
available on money market accounts rose to 6.15 percent as of
Wednesday from 6.12 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super NOW
accounts, was unchanged at 5.13 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 8.08
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 8.02 the
previous week. Yields were 8.35 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 8.27
percent; 8.49 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 8.42 percent; and 8.66
percent on 5-year CDs, up from 8.62 percent.
</TEXT>
