<1ST_LINE>r f AM-GuardianshipAward     12-08 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Guardianship Award,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AARP Honors AP, Others for Contributions Helping the Elderly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Association of Retired Persons
presented a special recognition award Thursday to The Associated
Press, honoring the news cooperative's 1987 series of stories on the
nation's guardianship system.
   Horace B. Deets, executive director of AARP, said the citation
recognizes ``those in the private sector who have made outstanding
contributions to enhance the quality of life for older people.''
   William Ahearn, managing editor of the AP, accepted the award on
behalf of the reporters and editors who produced the six-part
national series on the guardianship system and more than 300 other
stories that examined guardianship in all 50 states and the District
of Columbia.
   The AP's year-long study found that in many states, the elderly
are often placed under guardianship with few of the due process
rights guaranteed even criminals. The investigation also found
courts that placed people under guardianship often failed to monitor
abuse of the elderly and misappropriation of their money.
   Since publication of the articles, at least 20 states have passed
or introduced legislation to reform their guardisanship systems.
Three bills are now before Congress proposing federal standards for
guardiahsip.
   AARP also honored the Puget Sound Power and Light Co., The
Travelers Companies and Oregon Health Decisions Inc.
   AARP cited the Puget Sound company for its efforts to train
staffers to meet the needs of older people. The Travelers was cited
for its ``Older Americans Program,'' which includes a job bank in
which 700 retirees from Travelers and other companies are registered
for part-time or temporary work at the company. Oregon Health was
cited for providing a forum wherein citizens, health policy makers
and health providers can seek solutions to health-care policy
questions.
   Deets said these organizations ``are an inspiration to others in
the private sector to participate in similar community activties.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
