<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Alaska-EnergyPolicy     12-08 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Alaska-Energy Policy,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor Sees Alaska Influencing Bush Administration Oil-Gas Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alaska is poised to become a major player
in developing a national energy policy during the administration of
President-elect George Bush, Gov. Steve Cowper said Thursday.
   ``We ought to be in a position where we're driving American oil
and gas policy,'' Cowper said at a news conference. ``We produce
more than anybody else in the country.''
   Cowper returned late Wednesday from a three-day meeting of the
Interstate Oil Compact Commission in suburban Kansas City, Kan.
Cowper, the commission chairman, predicted the 52-year-old
organization will become more influential in directing national
energy policy.
   The Democratic governor said he met privately Wednesday with
Texas oilman Robert Mosbacher, a longtime Bush associate selected by
the Republican president-elect to be commerce secretary in his
administration.
   Cowper said they discussed opening Alaska's Arctic National
Wildlife Refuge for oil and gas development, the export of Alaska
natural gas and the state's seafood industry.
   ``He was favorably inclined toward our positions on all the
matters I discussed with him, and I think that this administration
will reflect those same views,'' Cowper said. ``I felt very good
about Mr. Mosbacher and I think we'll have a very close relationship
with the Department of Commerce.''
   Cowper declined to discuss details of his talk with Mosbacher
``because he's facing his confirmation hearings and things have a
way of slipping out and being misinterpreted.''
   He noted that Alaska's natural resources commissioner, Judith M.
Brady, was elected a vice chairwoman of the commission, and he will
take over as chairman of the National Governors Association energy
subcommittee in February.
   ``Having those two positions here in Alaska at the same time is
going to put us in a very unusual position to affect national oil
and gas policy, and that's going to be good for all of us,'' Cowper
said.
   The commmission has not yet agreed on which direction the
nation's oil and gas policy should take, Cowper said. The group
represents 29 states, including oil producers and consumers, and
will further discuss policy issues at its June meeting.
   ``Our main goal, believe it or not, is going to be to convince
the country why America needs an active and viable oil and gas
industry,'' the governor said. ``At the moment the oil industry is
on a serious decline, particularly the independents.''
   Cowper said he would like to see a limit on oil imports, combined
with tax credits and incentives to stimulate domestic production.
That may lead to an entitlement program to determine who gets cheap
foreign crude and who gets the more expensive domestic crude, he
said.
   Cowper said he does not expect Congress to adopt an oil-import
fee.
</TEXT>
