<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Kodak-NASA     12-08 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kodak-NASA,0159</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kodak Develops Blood Analyzer for Space</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. has developed a blood
analyzer that works in zero gravity conditions for use aboard the
U.S. space station currently scheduled to go into orbit in 1995.
   Company officials said the analyzer, which doesn't use liquid
chemicals, will allow medical personnel on the ground to evaluate
illness and other conditions of the crew.
   ``Kodak dry chemistry technology is ideally suited to the space
environment in terms of compactness, convenience and storage,'' said
John Zeman, vice president and general manager, Clinical Products
Division.
   The prototype analyzer is being tested by the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration, and is one of two diagnostic
systems Kodak is designing for the space station.
   NASA officials have also asked Kodak to develop an innovative
X-ray system that will permit images to be taken in space and
transmitted to the ground for evaluation.
</TEXT>
