<1ST_LINE>d f BC-Britain-Lloyd's     12-08 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Lloyd's,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Members Barred from Insurance Market for Life</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two prominent members of Lloyd's of London have
been banned from the insurance market for life for allegedly bilking
the company of interest in a scheme to enrich themselves and their
families, Lloyd's said Thursday.
   In addition to the permanent suspension of John Raymond Parry and
Frederick Charles Raven, one of their colleagues, Arthur Henry
Bertram Grattan-Bellew, has been suspended from Lloyd's for five
years and another, Edward Ernest Nelson, for two years.
   Each of the four has been fined 150,000 pounds, or about
$278,000, Lloyd's said.
   The penalties were reached at a special meeting of the Council of
Lloyd's, the market's ruling body, on Wednesday after an internal
disciplinary and appeals procedure.
   All four were found guilty of ``discreditable conduct'' in
siphoning off excessive slices of interest earned on premiums
invested in certain insurance activities for themselves or their
families, Lloyd's said.
   The amount siphoned off was not specified. A Lloyd's spokesman
was unavailable Thursday evening for comment.
   Parry and Raven issued a statement denying wrongdoing and
expressing dismay at what they called the severity of the punishment.
   Documents relating to the accusations have been passed to the
Serious Fraud Office, Lloyd's said.
   Sir Edward Singleton, a former president of the Law Society, was
appointed to carry out an investigation into the Bellew, Parry and
Raven group in 1984.
   He took two years to analyze the activities of the group, set up
by underwriters Parry, Raven and Grattan-Bellew.
   The group did insurance brokering, acting as agents for Lloyd's
investors, as well as reinsurance.
   The investigation led to 132 charges by the Lloyd's authorities
against the three men, as well as Nelson, who had interests in
certain companies within the group, Lloyd's said; and Albert John
Stratton, who was cleared of all allegations.
   The defendants denied all the counts, but Parry and Raven offered
to admit certain matters if the charges were amended. The Council of
Lloyd's rejected their offer.
</TEXT>
