<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Ends Lower, Gold Prices Are Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar retreated in foreign exchange trading
Thursday, as the markets calmed down from Wednesday's frenetic
trading.
   Gold prices were mixed. Republic National of New York quoted a
late bid of $421.30 for a troy ounce of gold, down from $422.50 late
Wednesday.
   The dollar had surged in hectic trading Wednesday after Soviet
leader Mikhail Gorbachev said his country would unilaterally cut its
miltary forces. The market's initial reaction was based on the
belief that the United States would also cut its forces and in so
doing help narrow the U.S. budget deficit.
   But later Wednesday, once the initial euphoria wore off and
dealers decided any reduction in U.S. troops would have a marginal
impact on the deficit at best, the dollar gave up some of its gains.
   It continued to slide in Thursday's trading.
   ``When you look at the hard cold economics, it doesn't really
mean the dollar should be valued upward,'' Richard Witten, vice
president for foreign exchange at Goldman Sachs & Co., said of
Gorbachev's announcement and the market's reaction to it.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.59 to a closing 123.02 yen. But later in London it
was quoted lower at 122.65 yen and in New York, it fell to 122.30
yen from late Wednesday's 123.525.
   The dollar also fell against the British pound. In London, it
cost $1.8510 to buy one pound, higher than $1.8425 Wednesday, and in
New York, one pound was worth $1.85505, compared with $1.8435 late
Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday's prices, included: 1.73865 West German marks, down from
1.75975; 1.4633 Swiss francs, down from 1.4795; 5.9350 French
francs, down from 6.0035; 1,283.00 Italian lire, down from 1,299.00;
and 1.19275 Canadian dollars, down from 1.9925.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday's
rates, included: 1.7420 West German marks, down from 1.7588; 1.4665
Swiss francs, down from 1.4790; 5.9450 French francs, down from
6.0025; 1.9645 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9675; 1,285.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,290.75; 1.1933 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1995.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold fell to $421.80 a
troy ounce, down from $422.80 on Wednesday.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $423.50 a troy ounce,
compared with $422.95 bid late Wednesday.
   In Zurich, gold fell to $423 from a $423.50 bid late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.78 to close at a bid $424.88.
   Silver bullion prices rose on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $6.16 a troy ounce, compared with
Wednesday's $6.14. But on the Commodity Exchange, silver slipped to
$6.128 a troy ounce from late Wednesday's $6.140.
