<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     12-08 0805</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0835</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Copper Futures Soar To New Record High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper for spot delivery on New York's Commodity Exchange soared
to a record-high $1.6475 a pound Thursday, reflecting renewed
concerns about dwindling supplies, lagging production and surging
demand for the metal.
   On other markets, energy futures slipped, pulling precious-metals
futures lower; livestock and meat prices dipped; grains and soybeans
moved higher; and stock-index futures retreated.
   Copper's gains extended the rally launched Wednesday by reports
of an explosion at one of the world's largest copper mines in
Bouganville, Papua New Guinea.
   The blast was ruled sabotage and the mine's owner has shut down
operations there until the government provides security, said Bette
Raptopoulos, metals analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in
New York.
   The Bouganville explosion refocused the market's attention on the
extremely tight availability of physical copper, a key factor in the
dramatic rise in copper's price from around $1 a pound in August.
   Copper inventories registered with the Comex and the London Metal
Exchange have declined by 50 percent in the last four months, and
global stocks have fallen to the equivalent of 2.9 weeks worth of
consumption, an all-time low.
   But world demand for copper, which is used heavily in the
construction and manufacturing industries, keeps rising, analysts
said. Mining and refining companies are trying to produce more but
those attempts frequently lead to problems, Ms. Raptopoulos said.
   ``Everyone's pushing to produce at maximum capacity, pressing too
hard, overloading capacity and they have periodic breakdowns,'' she
said.
   And in Peru, the world's sixth-largest copper producer last year,
a miners' strike is nearing the end of its second month.
   A dearth of deliveries against the December Comex contract
indicates no easing in the supply tightness, said Bernard Savaiko,
metals analyst with PaineWebber Inc. in New York.
   ``Either no one has it to deliver or, if they do, they're
withholding it and waiting for higher prices,'' he said.
   Copper settled unchanged to 6.2 cents higher with most active
contract, for delivery in March, at $1.40 a pound, a new high for
that contract. The spot December contract finished at $1.6325, down
slightly from the day's record high.
   Energy futures prices fell sharply on the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
   In the crude-oil market, a technical sell-off occurred after
traders tried and failed twice to bid the January contract up to $16
a barrel, said Peter Beutel, energy market analyst with Elders
Futures Inc. in New York.
   Meanwhile, prices of gasoline and heating-oil futures tumbled in
a continuing reaction to Tuesday's American Petroleum Institute
report, which showed steep increases in U.S. stocks of both fuels.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 26 cents to 30 cents
lower with January at $15.44 a barrel; heating oil was .81 cent to
1.11 cents lower with January at 48.08 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .80 cent lower to .17 cent higher with January at 43.93
cents a gallon.
   The inflation-sensitive precious metals reacted negatively to the
decline in oil prices.
   On the Commodity Exchange, gold settled $1 to $1.20 lower with
February at $426.70 a troy ounce; silver was 1.2 cents to 2 cents
lower with March at $6.263 a troy ounce.
   Frozen pork-belly ftures fell sharply for the third straight day
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, reflecting concerns about slack
demand for pork products and high hog-slaughter numbers this week,
said Thomas Morgan, president of Sterling Research Corp., of
Arlington Heights, Ill.
   Weak demand for beef contributed to a slide in cattle futures,
Morgan said.
   Live cattle settled .52 cent to .87 cent lower with December at
70.87 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .35 cent lower
with January at 81.92 cents a pound; live hogs were .20 cent to .63
cent lower with December at 40.47 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .20 cent to .92 cent lower with February at 42.02 cents a pound.
   Wheat futures posted substantial gains on the Chicago Board of
Trade on talk that China was set to bid for 400,000 metric tons of
U.S. wheat at subsidized prices, analysts said.
   Other grain and soybean futures had opened sharply higher on
fears that Wednesday's devastating earthquake in Soviet Armenia had
damaged two nuclear power plants, but those gains were quickly pared.
   Wheat settled 5 cents to 6{ cents higher with December at $4.29{
a bushel; corn was 1{ cents lower to 1{ cents higher with December
at $2.56} a bushel; oats were 1} cents to 4} cents higher with
December at $2.03} a bushel; soybeans were 1{ cents to 5{ cents
higher with January at $7.73{ a bushel.
   Stock-index futures settled slightly lower on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, where the contract for March delivery of the
Standard & Poor's 500 index settled .75 point lower at 280.70. Each
point is worth $500.
</TEXT>
