<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneySupply     12-08 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Supply,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>All Three Money Measures Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All three measures of the nation's money supply
rose in late November, the Federal Reserve Board reported Thursday.
   The Fed said the narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, rose
$3.1 billion to a seasonally adjusted $787.8 billion in the week
ended Nov. 28 from $784.7 billion the previous week.
   The central bank said a broader measures known as M2 rose $3.7
billion to a seasonally adjusted $3,061.9 billion from $3,058.2
billion the previous week.
   An even broader measure, M3, increased $1.9 billion to a
seasonally adjusted $3,896.7 billion from $3,894.8 billion.
   M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts
and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings
deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid
accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations
of $100,000.
   In judging its monetary policy, the Fed has indicated it is
monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the
difference between short- and long-term interest rates as well as
the broader money measures M2 and M3.
   In other reports:
   _The Federal Reserve said bank borrowings from the Federal
Reserve System at the discount window averaged $558 million in the
latest week, down from $1.104 billion in the previous week.
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reported that the monetary
base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank reserves held at
Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and in circulation,
was $285.7 billion in the two-week period ended Wednesday, up from
$285.0 billion two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
