<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 1941EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ToyotaLexus     12-08 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Toyota Lexus,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Lexus Nameplate to Woo Luxury Car Buyers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toyota unveiled a new luxury auto
nameplate Thursday, rolling out two new models designed to lure
yuppies graduating from economy imports and compete with top-drawer
European sports sedans.
   The cars introduce the Lexus line, which will be a division of
Toyota Motor Sales U.S.A. Inc., the American arm of Japan's Toyota
Motor Corp.
   In the manner of Honda's Acura, Toyota will try to establish a
separate, upscale identity for Lexus in part through design, price
and advertising, and in part by selling them through a separate
dealer network.
   The cars, to go on sale in September 1989, are:
   _The Lexus LS 400, a 4-door luxury sports sedan with Toyota's
first 4.0-liter V-8 engine and such high-tech features as anti-lock
brakes and a traction-control system, said to help drivers maintain
control in a wide variety of road conditions. The car, which
resembles the new Mercedes-Benz cars with which it is intended to
compete, will cost between $30,000 and $35,000, the company said.
   _The Lexus ES 250, a four-door ``executive sedan'' with a
2.5-liter V-6 engine and five-speed manual or four-speed automatic
transmission that shares many components with Toyota's Vista, a car
sold only in Japan. Closer in price and style to the successful
Acura, the car will sell for $20,000 to $25,000.
   The cars, introduced to the press at the Art Center College of
Design against a backdrop of modern sculptures and the rugged San
Gabriel Mountains, will be shown to the public in January at auto
shows in Detroit and Los Angeles.
   The Lexus line, in the works since 1983, mirrors Honda's strategy
of capturing the high end of the market with Acura and precedes
Nissan's similar Infinity nameplate onto the market.
   The Lexus strategy is two-fold, said J.C. ``Jim'' Perkins, the
American marketing man who is senior vice president at Lexus.
   On one end of the market, the company wants to retain baby
boomers who have long driven Toyotas and other Japanese imports but
who now earn enough to defect to luxury carmakers: ``The college
kids of the '70s who bought Corollas and trucks are moving into the
luxury market,'' Perkins noted. ``We want to be there to meet their
needs.''
   At the top end of the market, the LS 400 will compete with
Mercedes, BMW and the other European companies.
   The company hopes to sell 16,000 Lexus 1989 models from September
through the end of the year, a total of 75,000 in the first year on
the market, and up to 150,000 a year within a few years, Perkins
said. They will be sold initially by about 250 dealers. About 60 of
the first 100 dealers signed up so far also handle Toyotas.
   The car's designer, Kunihiro Uchida, said the cars are Toyota's
first to be made especially for the U.S. market. Uchida, who like
many top U.S. car designers studied at the Arts Center, said his
team did much of their work on the car in Southern California so
they could immerse themselves in the American car culture.
</TEXT>
