<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Torchmark-KCLife     12-08 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Torchmark-KC Life,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kansas City Family Extends Control Over Insurance Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The family holding a majority interest
in Kansas City Life Insurance Co. has pushed its holdings beyond the
50 percent mark to help thwart a hostile takeover bid by a
Birmingham, Ala., company.
   Kansas City Life said Thursday that W.E. Bixby and J.R. Bixby
each acquired 50,000 shares of the company Wednesday, the same day a
federal judge refused a request by Torchmark Corp. to block
additional purchases by the brothers or Kansas City Life.
   Torchmark had asked U.S. District Judge Scott O. Wright to
prevent the Bixbys from buying more stock and gaining a majority of
Kansas City Life shares. Wright also rejected Torchmark's request
that he force Kansas City Life to negotiate with Torchmark, set up a
special directors committee to review the offer and hire new
financial advisers.
   The Bixby family, which already owned 48.8 percent of Kansas City
Life, increased its holdings to 50.3 percent of the company with the
purchases. The family members earlier signed a legally binding
agreement not to sell unless two-thirds of the family's stock voted
to dissolve the agreement. The agreement will expire May 21.
   Torchmark made its bid directly to stockholders and hoped it
could overcome a recommendation from Kansas City Life's directors
that stockholders reject the offer. The offer expires Wednesday.
   Kansas City Life directors earlier rejected offers of $43.50 a
share and $42.50 a share from Torchmark. At a meeting Wednesday, the
directors rejected Torchmark's latest offer of $47.50 a share. The
directors have said none of the offers is adequate considering the
company's value.
</TEXT>
