<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FDIC-ContinentalIllinois     12-08 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FDIC-Continental Illinois,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FDIC Reduces Stake in Continental Illinois Below 50 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. said
Thursday it sold more than $275 million of its stock in Continental
Illinois Corp., reducing its stake in the company to less than 50
percent.
   The FDIC, which insures deposits of up to $100,000 in commercial
banks, paid a record $4.5 billion to rescue the failing Chicago bank
holding company in 1984.
   The agency announced it sold 50 million shares of Continental
stock at $5.25 each to an underwriting syndicate managed by Goldman,
Sachs & Co., Merrill Lynch Capital Markets, Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc. and Dean Witter Capital Markets. It expects to net $250 million
from the transaction.
   The underwriters have the option of purchasing an additional 7.5
million shares.
   Also, the FDIC agreed to sell 5.2 million shares to Continental
Illinois' employee stock ownership plan for $27.2 million.
   By eventually selling all of the stock and bad loans acquired in
the rescue, FDIC expects to reduce its loss on Continental to $1.7
billion.
   In November 1986, it sold 52.5 million shares, also for $5.25 per
share.
   The latest sale reduces the agency's share of outstanding common
stock from 61.5 percent to 25.6 percent. Its overall ownership
position, which includes options for a pool of stock representing
the interests of the bank's original shareholders, is being reduced
to 39.6 percent.
</TEXT>
