<1ST_LINE>u f AM-SEC-WPPSSDealer     12-08 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SEC-WPPSS Dealer,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Owner Of Securities Firm Barred From Business For Life</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of a securities firm that helped
underwrite the ill-fated Washington Public Power Supply System bonds
has been barred from the securities business for life, the
Securities and Exchange Commission said Thursday.
   SEC Administrative Law Judge Max O. Regensteiner barred Donald T.
Sheldon, 49, owner of two now out-of-business firms that were based
in New York City: Donald Sheldon & Co. Inc. and Donald Sheldon
Government Securities Inc.
   The two firms used customers' securities as collateral for the
firms' loans, engaged in business while insolvent, placed misleading
advertisements, made ``misrepresentations'' to customers and charged
excessive mark-ups, the SEC said, charging violations from 1982
through 1985 of anti-fraud provisions of federal securities laws.
   Bruce W. Reid, the manager of the firms' Houston office, was also
barred from the securities business, but can reapply for a
broker-dealer's license after two years. Gregory L. Pattison, a
salesman in the Houston office, was suspended for 45 days.
   In the WPPSS bond case, Sheldon and Pattison were accused of
misrepresenting the safety of the bonds. The power supply system, a
consortium of 15 utilities, defaulted on $2.25 billion of bonds
issued to finance the building of two nuclear power plants.
   In addition to New York and Houston, Sheldon's firms, which were
forced into liquidation in July 1985, had offices in Pompano Beach,
Fla.; Miami; Los Angeles and Honolulu, the SEC said.
</TEXT>
