<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BrassSuit     12-08 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brass Suit,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Dept. Seeking to Block TBG Purchase of Chase Brass</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department announced Thursday it
intends to file a civil suit to block TBG Inc.'s proposed
acquisition of Chase Brass & Copper Co. of Solon, Ohio.
   The department said in a statement it had notified the companies
of its plans and that a lawsuit would allege that the $127 million
transaction would violate federal antitrust law because it might
substantially reduce competition in the production and sale of free
cutting brass rod.
   Chase is a wholly owned subsidiary of BP America Inc. of
Cleveland, which is owned by British Petroleum PLC of London. TBG, a
wholly owned subsidiary of a Netherlands Antilles trust, owns the
Extruded Metals Co. of Belding, Mich.
   The top four companies making free cutting brass rod in the
United States include Chass and Extruded and command over 75 percent
of the U.S. market.
   Chase's share of the $514 million in 1987 U.S. sales of free
cutting brass rod was about 29 percent. Extruded's was about 13
percent.
   Machine shops make free cutting brass rod into a variety of
plumbing fixtures and other building construction materials, parts
for industrial equipment and machinery and vehicular parts and
components.
</TEXT>
