<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Giuliani-Business     12-08 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Giuliani-Business,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Says Feds Not to Blame for Princeton-Newport Woes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani firmly denied on
Thursday that the racketeering indictment of five top officials of
Princeton-Newport Partners pushed the firm into liquidation.
   ``The U.S. government doesn't have any responsibility for
creating a business or destroying a business,'' Giuliani said in
reply to reporters' questions about a published report.
   The Wall Street Journal, in reporting on the firm's liquidation
announcment, quoted officials and lawyers as blaming the demise of
the investment partnership on the indictment.
   Last August five Princeton-Newport partners and a former Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc. trader were charged with a racketeering scheme
that allegedly engaged in generating phony tax losses through bogus
securities trading.
   It was the first time officials of a securities firm were charged
with violating federal racketeering laws.
   Neither Drexel nor Princeton-Newport was charged with criminal
activity.
   ``The government has succeeded in destroying Princeton-Newport,''
said defense attorney Paul R. Grand, according to the Journal's
Thursday editions.
   Giuliani called Grand's charge ``ridiculous'' and
``irresponsible.''
   ``That's their problem to deal with. I don't accept the premise
that we destoyed the business,'' said Giuliani.
   A week after the indictment was handed up, prosecutors _ as
required by federal rules _ informed the judge they planned a
superseding indictment, that might include additional defendants or
additional charges.
   But the government has twice pushed back the planned date for
bringing a superseding indictment.
   ``Postponing that decision repeatedly for several months created
too much uncertainty for the business,'' Grand told the Journal.
   On Monday, most of the investors gave notice they were pulling
out a substantial part of the $200 million total investment, another
defense lawyer, Diana Parker, told the Journal.
   But Giuliani countered: `'We can't determine the effect that (an
indictment) is going to have in the marketplace, any more than we
can't predict the effect of an indictment on an election.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
