<FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-88 2142EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Court-WPPSS     12-08 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Court-WPPSS,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Washington State High Court Agrees To Hear WPPSS Bonds Civil Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Washington State Supreme Court agreed
Thursday to hear new arguments in a civil case in which the state is
accused of fraud and negligence by holders of defaulted Washington
Public Power Supply System bonds.
   The high court provided no details in its brief order, and did
not set a date for arguments in the class-action suit, Hoffer vs.
Washington.
   Last May, justices voted 5-4 in ruling the state must defend
itself against the charges, brought by representatives of the
approximately 40,000 holders of $2.25 billion in bonds for WPPSS
nuclear power plants Nos. 4 and 5.
   In a separate development Thursday, the Securities and Exchange
Commission said the owner of a securities firm that helped
underwrite the ill-fated WPPSS bonds has been barred from the
securities business for life.
   SEC Administrative Law Judge Max O. Regensteiner barred Donald T.
Sheldon, 49, owner of two now-defunct firms that were based in New
York City: Donald Sheldon & Co. Inc. and Donald Sheldon Government
Securities Inc.
   WPPSS defaulted on the bonds in 1983, after the state Supreme
Court ruled that Washington utilities lacked the authority to
contract with WPPSS for construction of the plants. A total of 88
Northwest utilities participated in construction of the plants,
which were terminated when partially complete in January 1982.
   The bondholders, led by Arthur Hoffer of New York, allege that
the state auditor negligently performed, or failed to perform, his
duty to audit the supply system and to examine bond resolutions that
investors depend upon.
   The suit also contends that the auditor certification of the
bonds contained fraudulent and negligent misrepresentations and that
the state's participation in the decision to terminate the plants
constituted interference with the contractual relations between the
supply system and bondholders.
   In the majority opinion written in May, Justice Barbara Durham
wrote that bondholders ``should be allowed the opportunity to
present evidence concerning the certificate's objective, and the
effect it would produce on the ordinary reader.''
   However, she conceded that the auditor's certificate and letter
did not include an explicit assurance of the supply system's
financial health.
   WPPSS No. 4 was built at the Hanford nuclear reservation in
Eastern Washington, while No. 5 was built at Satsop, west of
Olympia. The plants were each less than 25 percent complete when
they were abandoned because the electricity they would have produced
was no longer needed, and because of cost overruns and other
problems.
</TEXT>
