<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0289 12-08 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0289,0312</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with reaction to Miyazawa
resignation; later Nikkei average; No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar remained weaker against the Japanese
yen Friday following Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa's resignation,
while share prices rebounded slightly on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar, which opened at 122.20 yen, was changing hands at
122.33 yen at midday, down 0.69 yen from Thursday's close of 123.02
yen. It moved in a range of 122.10 yen to 122.45 yen.
   The Nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues, a 291.92-point
loser Thursday, edged up 10.76 points, or 0.04 percent, to finish
the morning session at 29,769.66.
   The dollar began trading sharply lower in Tokyo following an
overnight plunge in New York, where it closed at 122.28 yen, down
1.40 yen.
   The dollar's fall in New York was attributed to dealers'
disappointment about a still unclear U.S. reaction to Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev's pledge at the United Nations to unilaterally
reduce Soviet troops and cut the number of Soviet conventional
weapons.
   In Tokyo, anticipation of Miyazawa's resignation Friday left many
currency dealers waiting on the sidelines, said Mitsuhiko Kinugasa
of Daiwa Bank.
   ``Many traders speculate that the resignation of Miyazawa, who
has opposed a weaker dollar, would damage current international
monetary coordination,'' said Kinugasa. ``That gave the market
strong bearish sentiments toward the dollar today.''
   Miyazawa, who had hinted at his resignation earlier, formally
announced he was stepping down to help clear opposition to tax
reform legislation under discussion in Parliament.
   The announcement of Miyazawa's resignation came just as the stock
market ended its morning session.
   Share prices rose slightly but were mixed. Many investors were
inclined to sit on the sidelines following Thursday's sharp fall,
said a dealer with a major securities firm, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
</TEXT>
